n 1981]]\n[[Category:Baseball governing bodies in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "PenulisHantu", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed corrupted link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korea_Baseball_Organization"}
{"title_page": "United States Naval Training Center, Bainbridge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{distinguish|United States Training Center}}\n[[Image:Bainbridge Naval Training Station.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Captain Russel's House in 1943]]\n'''United States Naval Training Center, Bainbridge''' ('''USNTC Bainbridge''') was the [[U.S. Navy]] Training Center at [[Port Deposit, Maryland]], on the bluffs of the northeast bank of the [[Susquehanna River]]. It was active from 1942 to 1976 under the Commander of the [[Fifth Naval District]], based in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\n\nLocated on the appropriated campus of the [[Tome School]] for boys, the training center sat between various important naval centers of [[World War II]]: about {{convert|35|mi|km}} northeast of [[Baltimore, Maryland]], and {{convert|75|mi|km}} from Washington, D.C., and [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. It was reached via [[Maryland Route 222]], about halfway between [[U.S. Route 1 in Maryland|US&nbsp;1]] and [[U.S. Route 40 in Maryland|US&nbsp;40]]. \n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nPresident [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]] personally approved the site, which was seized from the [[Tome School]] by Congressional order. Roosevelt also chose the name to honor Commodore [[William Bainbridge]], who commanded the [[frigate]] [[USS Constitution|''Constitution'']] when it defeated the British frigate [[HMS Java (1811)|HMS ''Java'']] during the [[War of 1812]]. \n\nThe campus was expanded by government purchase from {{convert|330|acre|km2}} to {{convert|1132|acre|km2}}. More than five hundred new buildings were built, some designed by [[Eggers & Higgins]].\n\n===World War II===\n====Recruit training====\nThe center was activated on 1 October 1942, and the first batch of recruits arrived 10 days later to begin \"boot camp\" training. They came in busloads from transportation collection points at [[Havre de Grace, Maryland|Havre de Grace]] and [[Perryville, Maryland]]. The recruits were given a battery of tests to determine their educational and skill levels, then trained in ordnance and gunnery, seamanship, fire fighting, physical training, and military drill.\n\nRecruits were trained in shipboard duties aboard the [[USS Commodore (401B)|R.T.S. ''Commodore'']], a 200-foot \"ship\" built on dry land. The trainer was equipped with  deck guns, a [[pilot house]], [[davit]]s with [[whaleboat]]s, and mooring lines fastened to earth-bound [[bollard]]s, so that crew members could learn casting off [[hawser]]s and other lines connecting the ship to its dock.\n\nHalfway through boot camp, recruits had a \"service week\", which generally included kitchen duty, peeling potatoes, mopping, picking up cigarette butts, etc. Recruits with desirable skills, such as typing, could end up on an office typewriter rather than in a kitchen. One winter, recruits were sent to shovel snow off roads to a largely rural area near Colora and Rising Sun.{{cn|date=February 2014}}<!---probably needs deletion. Sounds like trivia-->\n\nBy the end of World War II, the center had trained 244,277 recruits who transferred to various ships and stations throughout the world.\n\n====Non-recruit training====\nUSNTC Bainbridge also trained new boot camp graduates and other sailors in technical and other skills. During World War II, a total of 24,484 sailors completed various programs under the direction of the Service School Command<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.net/hyperwar/USN/ref/USN-Act/MD.html United States Naval Facilities World War II]</ref>.These included:\n[[File:Building Overtaken.jpg|alt=A panoramic image showing a large \"H-shaped\" building overtaken by nature due to Bainbridge's abandoning.|thumb|A panoramic image showing a large \"H-shaped\" building being overtaken by nature due to Bainbridge's abandoning. ]]\n[[File:Workshop Brick Making.jpg|alt=A brick-making workshop that has been left to rot.|thumb|A brick-making workshop that has been left to rot.]]\n\n* Coast Guard School\n* Rockefeller Research Unit (Report to Naval Training Station).\n* Stewards Mates' School Roll\n*[[Naval Academy Preparatory School]], founded in 1943.\n* Naval Hospital\n* Hospital Corps School\n* Naval Training School (Radio)\n* Naval Training School (Fire Controlmen)\n* Fire Fighters School\n* Naval Training School (Electrical)\n* Naval Training School (Physical Instructors)\n* Naval Training School (Instructors)\n* Naval Training School (Sound Motion Picture Technician)\n* Fire Fighters Training Unit\n* Naval Training School (Motion Picture Operators)\n* Naval Training School (Recruit Instructors \u2013 C)\n\n===First deactivation===\nAfter the war ended, the center continued limited operations until 30 June 1947, when it was first inactivated as a Navy training center. The sole remaining training activity on campus was the Naval Academy Prep School. A maintenance staff remained active to protect the buildings from weather and other damage. \n\n===Reactivation ===\nIn mid-1950, with the advent of the [[Korean War]] crisis, plans were made to reactivate the center, and it was officially reopened on 1 February 1951, when Captain Robert Hall Smith took overall command.\n\nDespite the care of the maintenance staff, the buildings were in severe disrepair. A contract was awarded to Consolidated Engineering Company of [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. The necessary renovations and road work were accomplished ahead of schedule, and the center reopened its gates for recruits on 5 April 1951.\n\nInitially, the center admitted 500 recruits per week, but the rate soon doubled. The first 500 recruits who graduated as seamen recruits on 23 June 1951.\n\nIn 1962, a [[Naval Nuclear Power School]] was installed on the center; this was eventually moved to [[Naval Training Center Orlando]], Florida. \n\nNAPS moved to [[Newport, Rhode Island]], in August 1974.\n\n===Second deactivation===\nThe Navy formally deactivated the Center on March 31, 1976<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cecilcountyhistory.com/cecil-goes-on-a-war-footing-dec-7-1941/|title=Dec 7, 1941 - Cecil Goes on a War Footing & Bainbridge Develops|date=2008-12-07|website=Window on Cecil County's Past|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> and on the evening of June 30, 1976 the last sailor detailed to handle closing matters locked the gates for the final time.  Chief Petty Officer Stephen Kowalki had the duty of performing that final act for the Navy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cecilcountyhistory.com/last-sailor-at-bainbridge-says-goodbye-to-friends-at-the-winchester-bar/|title=Last Sailor at Bainbridge Says Goodbye to Friends at the Winchester Bar|last=admin|date=2009-08-05|website=Window on Cecil County's Past|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>  After this some of its facilities were used by the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] as a [[Job Corps]] Training Center until 1990.  \n\n===Base closing ===\n[[File:Chimney abandoned.jpg|alt=A once used chimney now stands alone next to a previously demolished building's cement foundation.|thumb|A once used chimney now stands alone next to a previously demolished building's cement foundation.]]\nOn 3 November 1986, the [[United States Congress]] authorized the [[Secretary of the Navy]] to dispose of Naval Training Center, Bainbridge by sale to private parties or transfer to other government agencies. NTCB is the federal facilities equivalent of a [[brownfield]] site; the Navy's primary goal was effective re-use of the former property by the State of Maryland and the people of [[Cecil County, Maryland|Cecil County]]. Congress specified that before any sale, the Secretary of the Navy was required to \"restore such property to a condition that meets all applicable Federal and State of Maryland environmental protection regulations\" (Public Law 99-956). \n\nAs of June 2006, the U.S. Navy had transferred this site to the Bainbridge Development Corporation and declared the cleanup complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921093328/http://www.epa.gov:80/reg3hwmd/npl/MDD985397256.htm|title=Current Site Information, Naval Training Center Bainbridge, MD Superfund {{!}} Mid-Atlantic Superfund {{!}} US EPA|date=2015-09-21|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe center was divided into four activities, each with its own commanding officer:\n\n===Administrative Command===\nThe Administrative Command was responsible for the various tasks and services necessary in running a center containing about 35,000 inhabitants. Tasks included base maintenance, physical security, fire protection, logistics, material procurement, medical care, religious services, transportation, and so on.\n [[Image:USNTC Bainbridge graduation.jpg|300px|thumb|right|USNTC Bainbridge seaman recruits performing final graduation exercises (1954).]]\n[[Image:USNTC Bainbridge.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Typical barracks for enlisted personnel attending the Class \"A\" Radioman school (1954).]]\n\n===Recruit Training Command===\nThe Recruit Training Command was the largest of the center's commands and was responsible for the basic training of recruits. It consisted of four independent commands \u2013 known as camps\u2014each of which had its own regimental drill hall, mess hall, barracks, class rooms, and so on:\n* Camp Rodgers\n* Camp Perry\n* Camp James\n* Camp Barney\n\nEach camp contained 5,000 male recruits. A training school was established for [[WAVES|WAVE]] recruits in October 1951. Circa 1959, male recruit training at Bainbridge was closed and male recruit training was only in Great Lakes, Illinois and San Diego, California. Bainbridge was the sole recruit training center for Waves until moving to Orlando, Florida in 1972.\n\n===Service School Command===\nThe Service School Command was organized to train selected personnel who had completed \"recruit\" basic training and demonstrated an aptitude for a skill during initial recruit testing. The command had a capacity of providing specialty training to 4,000 sailors at a time. These personnel were assigned to training in gunnery, fire control, radio, telemetry, and other technical subjects.\n\nThe [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]] was a component of the Service School Command and was chartered to train enlisted personnel for acceptance into the [[U.S. Naval Academy]] at [[Annapolis, Maryland]]. The school also trained sailors and marines in necessary academic skills required for admission to colleges and universities under the [[Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps|Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps]].\n\n===Naval Hospital===\nThe naval hospital was established as a 500-bed hospital to care for the center's operating staff, recruits, students, and dependents, with provision to increase capacity to 1,000 beds or more. Some care was provided by the roughly 1,200 students studying to become [[Hospital Corpsman|Hospital Corpsmen]] at the Hospital Corps School.\n\n==Famous people who served at the USNTC==\n* [[Charlie Justice (American football player)|Charlie \"Choo Choo\" Justice]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] football star & two-time [[Heisman Trophy]] runner-up.\n* Admiral [[Frank B. Kelso II]] (1933\u20132013), who later became [[Chief of Naval Operations]], commanded the U.S. Naval Nuclear Power School at the U.S. Naval Training Center Bainbridge from 1969 to 1971.\n* [[Paul Pierce (American football)|Paul Pierce]], who later became head football coach at [[Sul Ross State University]] and [[Sam Houston State University]].\n* [[Bill Cosby]], Actor, comedian and convict.<ref name=\"navycosby\">{{cite web | url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=58671 | title=MCPON Designates Bill Cosby Honorary Chief | publisher=U.S. Navy | accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Naval Station Great Lakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite book\n| last =\n| first =\n| authorlink =\n| author2 =\n| year = 1954\n| chapter =\n| title = The Compass, United States Naval Training Center, Bainbridge, Maryland\n| publisher = Albert Love\n| location = Atlanta, Georgia\n| id =\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usntcbainbridge.org/ USNTC Bainbridge Association]\n* [http://www.epa.gov/reg3hwmd/npl/MDD985397256.htm Naval Training Center, Bainbridge \u2013 Current Site Information]\n*[https://mde.maryland.gov/programs/LAND/MarylandBrownfieldVCP/Documents/Former%20Bainbridge%20Naval%20Training%20Center%20FS%20122011.pdf Bainbridge Residential Phase 1A Property (Voluntary Cleanup Program), Maryland Department of the Environment. Dec. 2011]\n\n{{Coord|39|36|45|N|76|05|30|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Training installations of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cecil County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:1976 disestablishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Military installations closed in 1976]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{distinguish|United States Training Center}}\n[[Image:Bainbridge Naval Training Station.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Captain Russel's House in 1943]]\n'''United States Naval Training Center, Bainbridge''' ('''USNTC Bainbridge''') was the [[U.S. Navy]] Training Center at [[Port Deposit, Maryland]], on the bluffs of the northeast bank of the [[Susquehanna River]]. It was active from 1942 to 1976 under the Commander of the [[Fifth Naval District]], based in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\n\nLocated on the appropriated campus of the [[Tome School]] for boys, the training center sat between various important naval centers of [[World War II]]: about {{convert|35|mi|km}} northeast of [[Baltimore, Maryland]], and {{convert|75|mi|km}} from Washington, D.C., and [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. It was reached via [[Maryland Route 222]], about halfway between [[U.S. Route 1 in Maryland|US&nbsp;1]] and [[U.S. Route 40 in Maryland|US&nbsp;40]]. \n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nPresident [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]] personally approved the site, which was seized from the [[Tome School]] by Congressional order. Roosevelt also chose the name to honor Commodore [[William Bainbridge]], who commanded the [[frigate]] [[USS Constitution|''Constitution'']] when it defeated the British frigate [[HMS Java (1811)|HMS ''Java'']] during the [[War of 1812]]. \n\nThe campus was expanded by government purchase from {{convert|330|acre|km2}} to {{convert|1132|acre|km2}}. More than five hundred new buildings were built, some designed by [[Eggers & Higgins]].\n\n===World War II===\n====Recruit training====\nThe center was activated on 1 October 1942, and the first batch of recruits arrived 10 days later to begin \"boot camp\" training. They came in busloads from transportation collection points at [[Havre de Grace, Maryland|Havre de Grace]] and [[Perryville, Maryland]]. The recruits were given a battery of tests to determine their educational and skill levels, then trained in ordnance and gunnery, seamanship, fire fighting, physical training, and military drill.\n\nRecruits were trained in shipboard duties aboard the [[USS Commodore (401B)|R.T.S. ''Commodore'']], a 200-foot \"ship\" built on dry land. The trainer was equipped with  deck guns, a [[pilot house]], [[davit]]s with [[whaleboat]]s, and mooring lines fastened to earth-bound [[bollard]]s, so that crew members could learn casting off [[hawser]]s and other lines connecting the ship to its dock.\n\nHalfway through boot camp, recruits had a \"service week\", which generally included kitchen duty, peeling potatoes, mopping, picking up cigarette butts, etc. Recruits with desirable skills, such as typing, could end up on an office typewriter rather than in a kitchen. One winter, recruits were sent to shovel snow off roads to a largely rural area near Colora and Rising Sun.{{cn|date=February 2014}}<!---probably needs deletion. Sounds like trivia-->\n\nBy the end of World War II, the center had trained 244,277 recruits who transferred to various ships and stations throughout the world.\n\n====Non-recruit training====\nUSNTC Bainbridge also trained new boot camp graduates and other sailors in technical and other skills. During World War II, a total of 24,484 sailors completed various programs under the direction of the Service School Command<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.net/hyperwar/USN/ref/USN-Act/MD.html United States Naval Facilities World War II]</ref>.These included:\n[[File:Building Overtaken.jpg|alt=A panoramic image showing a large \"H-shaped\" building overtaken by nature due to Bainbridge's abandoning.|thumb|A panoramic image showing a large \"H-shaped\" building being overtaken by nature due to Bainbridge's abandoning. ]]\n[[File:Workshop Brick Making.jpg|alt=A brick-making workshop that has been left to rot.|thumb|A brick-making workshop that has been left to rot.]]\n\n* Coast Guard School\n* Rockefeller Research Unit (Report to Naval Training Station).\n* Stewards Mates' School Roll\n*[[Naval Academy Preparatory School]], founded in 1943.\n* Naval Hospital\n* Hospital Corps School\n* Naval Training School (Radio)\n* Naval Training School (Fire Controlmen)\n* Fire Fighters School\n* Naval Training School (Electrical)\n* Naval Training School (Physical Instructors)\n* Naval Training School (Instructors)\n* Naval Training School (Sound Motion Picture Technician)\n* Fire Fighters Training Unit\n* Naval Training School (Motion Picture Operators)\n* Naval Training School (Recruit Instructors \u2013 C)\n\n===First deactivation===\nAfter the war ended, the center continued limited operations until 30 June 1947, when it was first inactivated as a Navy training center. The sole remaining training activity on campus was the Naval Academy Prep School. A maintenance staff remained active to protect the buildings from weather and other damage. \n\n===Reactivation ===\nIn mid-1950, with the advent of the [[Korean War]] crisis, plans were made to reactivate the center, and it was officially reopened on 1 February 1951, when Captain Robert Hall Smith took overall command.\n\nDespite the care of the maintenance staff, the buildings were in severe disrepair. A contract was awarded to Consolidated Engineering Company of [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. The necessary renovations and road work were accomplished ahead of schedule, and the center reopened its gates for recruits on 5 April 1951.\n\nInitially, the center admitted 500 recruits per week, but the rate soon doubled. The first 500 recruits who graduated as seamen recruits on 23 June 1951.\n\nIn 1962, a [[Naval Nuclear Power School]] was installed on the center; this was eventually moved to [[Naval Training Center Orlando]], Florida. \n\nNAPS moved to [[Newport, Rhode Island]], in August 1974.\n\n===Second deactivation===\nThe Navy formally deactivated the Center on March 31, 1976<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cecilcountyhistory.com/cecil-goes-on-a-war-footing-dec-7-1941/|title=Dec 7, 1941 - Cecil Goes on a War Footing & Bainbridge Develops|date=2008-12-07|website=Window on Cecil County's Past|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> and on the evening of June 30, 1976 the last sailor detailed to handle closing matters locked the gates for the final time.  Chief Petty Officer Stephen Kowalki had the duty of performing that final act for the Navy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cecilcountyhistory.com/last-sailor-at-bainbridge-says-goodbye-to-friends-at-the-winchester-bar/|title=Last Sailor at Bainbridge Says Goodbye to Friends at the Winchester Bar|last=admin|date=2009-08-05|website=Window on Cecil County's Past|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>  After this some of its facilities were used by the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] as a [[Job Corps]] Training Center until 1990.  \n\n===Base closing ===\n[[File:Chimney abandoned.jpg|alt=A once used chimney now stands alone next to a previously demolished building's cement foundation.|thumb|A once used chimney now stands alone next to a previously demolished building's cement foundation.]]\nOn 3 November 1986, the [[United States Congress]] authorized the [[Secretary of the Navy]] to dispose of Naval Training Center, Bainbridge by sale to private parties or transfer to other government agencies. NTCB is the federal facilities equivalent of a [[brownfield]] site; the Navy's primary goal was effective re-use of the former property by the State of Maryland and the people of [[Cecil County, Maryland|Cecil County]]. Congress specified that before any sale, the Secretary of the Navy was required to \"restore such property to a condition that meets all applicable Federal and State of Maryland environmental protection regulations\" (Public Law 99-956). \n\nAs of June 2006, the U.S. Navy had transferred this site to the Bainbridge Development Corporation and declared the cleanup complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921093328/http://www.epa.gov:80/reg3hwmd/npl/MDD985397256.htm|title=Current Site Information, Naval Training Center Bainbridge, MD Superfund {{!}} Mid-Atlantic Superfund {{!}} US EPA|date=2015-09-21|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe center was divided into four activities, each with its own commanding officer:\n\n===Administrative Command===\nThe Administrative Command was responsible for the various tasks and services necessary in running a center containing about 35,000 inhabitants. Tasks included base maintenance, physical security, fire protection, logistics, material procurement, medical care, religious services, transportation, and so on.\n [[Image:USNTC Bainbridge graduation.jpg|300px|thumb|right|USNTC Bainbridge seaman recruits performing final graduation exercises (1954).]]\n[[Image:USNTC Bainbridge.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Typical barracks for enlisted personnel attending the Class \"A\" Radioman school (1954).]]\n\n===Recruit Training Command===\nThe Recruit Training Command was the largest of the center's commands and was responsible for the basic training of recruits. It consisted of four independent commands \u2013 known as camps\u2014each of which had its own regimental drill hall, mess hall, barracks, class rooms, and so on:\n* Camp Rodgers\n* Camp Perry\n* Camp James\n* Camp Barney\n\nEach camp contained 5,000 male recruits. A training school was established for [[WAVES|WAVE]] recruits in October 1951. Circa 1959, male recruit training at Bainbridge was closed and male recruit training was only in Great Lakes, Illinois and San Diego, California. Bainbridge was the sole recruit training center for Waves until moving to Orlando, Florida in 1972.\n\n===Service School Command===\nThe Service School Command was organized to train selected personnel who had completed \"recruit\" basic training and demonstrated an aptitude for a skill during initial recruit testing. The command had a capacity of providing specialty training to 4,000 sailors at a time. These personnel were assigned to training in gunnery, fire control, radio, telemetry, and other technical subjects.\n\nThe [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]] was a component of the Service School Command and was chartered to train enlisted personnel for acceptance into the [[U.S. Naval Academy]] at [[Annapolis, Maryland]]. The school also trained sailors and marines in necessary academic skills required for admission to colleges and universities under the [[Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps|Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps]].\n\n===Naval Hospital===\nThe naval hospital was established as a 500-bed hospital to care for the center's operating staff, recruits, students, and dependents, with provision to increase capacity to 1,000 beds or more. Some care was provided by the roughly 1,200 students studying to become [[Hospital Corpsman|Hospital Corpsmen]] at the Hospital Corps School.\n\n==Famous people who served at the USNTC==\n* [[Charlie Justice (American football player)|Charlie \"Choo Choo\" Justice]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] football star & two-time [[Heisman Trophy]] runner-up.\n* Admiral [[Frank B. Kelso II]] (1933\u20132013), who later became [[Chief of Naval Operations]], commanded the U.S. Naval Nuclear Power School at the U.S. Naval Training Center Bainbridge from 1969 to 1971.\n* [[Paul Pierce (American football)|Paul Pierce]], who later became head football coach at [[Sul Ross State University]] and [[Sam Houston State University]].\n* [[Bill Cosby]], Actor, comedian and convict.<ref name=\"navycosby\">{{cite web | url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=58671 | title=MCPON Designates Bill Cosby Honorary Chief | publisher=U.S. Navy | accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Naval Station Great Lakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite book\n| last =\n| first =\n| authorlink =\n| author2 =\n| year = 1954\n| chapter =\n| title = The Compass, United States Naval Training Center, Bainbridge, Maryland\n| publisher = Albert Love\n| location = Atlanta, Georgia\n| id =\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usntcbainbridge.org/ USNTC Bainbridge Association]\n* [http://www.epa.gov/reg3hwmd/npl/MDD985397256.htm Naval Training Center, Bainbridge \u2013 Current Site Information]\n*[[Bainbridge Residential Phase 1A Property (Voluntary Cleanup Program), Maryland Department of the Environment. Dec. 2011]]\n\n{{Coord|39|36|45|N|76|05|30|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Training installations of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cecil County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:1976 disestablishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Military installations closed in 1976]]\n", "name_user": "Dixonhistory", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed broken link to external resource, the Maryland Dept. of the Environment Report on Bainbridge-NTC.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Naval_Training_Center,_Bainbridge"}
{"title_page": "Dappy", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2017}}\n{{Tone|date=July 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| birth_name = Costadinos Contostavlos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], [[London]], England\n| image  = Dappy and Tulisa Contostavlos at Tup Tup Palace.jpg\n| caption = Dappy and Tulisa Contostavlos, 2008\n| instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* actor}}\n| genre  = {{Flat list|\n*[[British hip hop]]\n*[[Grime (music genre)|grime]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| years_active  = 2000\u2013present\n| label  = {{Flat list|\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n*[[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]]\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*[[Island Records|Island]]\n*[[Takeover Entertainment|Takeover Entertainment Ltd]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flat list|\n*[[N-Dubz]]\n*[[Richard Rawson]]\n*[[Tulisa Contostavlos]]{{clear}}\n*[[Tinchy Stryder]]\n*[[Mr Hudson]]\n*[[Cover Drive]]}}\n| background = solo_singer\n| website   = {{URL|http://www.thedappy.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Costadinos Contostavlos'''<ref name=\"Costadinos Contostavlos\">{{cite web\n| title = Costadinos Contostavlos\n| url = http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/costadinos-contostavlos/6461349\n| publisher = Artistdirect\n| accessdate = 29 November 2010\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120623220607/http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/costadinos-contostavlos/6461349\n| archive-date = 23 June 2012\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> (born 11 June 1987), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Dappy''', is a British rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer and actor. He is the [[lead singer]] of the [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]]-based [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Grime music|grime]] trio [[N-Dubz]], with his cousin [[Tulisa Contostavlos|Tulisa]], and [[Fazer (rapper)|Fazer]]. He was known for his slightly unusual dress sense and his love for what he describes as \"eye-catching headwear\". His trademark was wearing a selection of woolly [[chullo]]s (sometimes referred to as \"Dappy hats\"), turning up one or both of the ear-flaps of the hat.\n\n==Music career==\n===2000\u201311: N-Dubz era===\n{{main|N-Dubz}}\n\nDappy appeared on the television show ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' on 29 November 2007, on [[Phill Jupitus]]' team, and wore a trademark \"Dappy hat\", also giving one to [[Simon Amstell]] to wear as part of the gag. Despite vowing he would not return to the show he appeared for a second time on the guest team on 4 December 2008 and for a third time, on Phill's team, which was broadcast on 18 November 2009. He is known to be a good friend of [[Chris Moyles]] and also gets on well with [[Kwasi Danquah III|Tinchy Stryder]] after releasing a single together, called \"[[Number 1 (Tinchy Stryder song)|Number 1]]\". Dappy has made cameo appearances on K.I.G's \"Head, Shoulders, Kneez and Toez\" music video, Gracious K's \"Migraine Skank\" music video, and [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]]'s \"[[Chip Diddy Chip]]\" music video, as one of Chipmunk's school friends.\n\n===2011\u201314: Solo projects and ''Bad Intentions''===\nIt was announced on 17 June 2011 that N-Dubz had left their American record deal, amid rumours that the band had split.<ref>Darvill, Josh (Friday, 17 June 2011). [http://xfactor.tellymix.co.uk/judges/35418-n-dubz-to-split-up-following-tulisa-contstavlos-new-x-factor-role.html N-Dubz to split up following Tulisa Contstavlos new X Factor role] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821115436/http://xfactor.tellymix.co.uk/judges/35418-n-dubz-to-split-up-following-tulisa-contstavlos-new-x-factor-role.html |date=21 August 2011 }}. ''xfactor.tellymix.co.uk.''</ref><ref>[http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/06/n-dubz-set-to-split-up/ N-Dubz set to split up] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019053555/http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/06/n-dubz-set-to-split-up/ |date=19 October 2011 }}. ''[[SB.TV]]''. Saturday, 18 June 2011.</ref><ref>Daniels, Colin (Saturday, 13 August 2011). [http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a334894/n-dubz-dropped-by-us-record-label-def-jam.html N-Dubz dropped by US record label Def Jam] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921110809/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a334894/n-dubz-dropped-by-us-record-label-def-jam.html |date=21 September 2011 }}. ''[[Digital Spy]]''.</ref> These rumours began circulating again in August 2011; however, Dappy insisted the band had not split, but were simply taking a break.<ref>Gritt, Emma (Tuesday, 13 September 2011). [http://www.metro.co.uk/music/875305-dappy-forced-to-retract-claims-n-dubz-will-split-within-two-years Dappy forced to retract claims N-Dubz will split within two years]. ''[[Metro (British newspaper)]]''.</ref> As such, during the band's hiatus period, all three members decided to embark upon solo careers. Before the band's split, Dappy signed a contract with [[Takeover Entertainment|Takeover Entertainment Ltd]] that confirmed that if the band ever split or went on hiatus, he would continue as a solo artist. His first taste of solo stardom came as a guest artist on label-mate [[Kwasi Danquah III|Tinchy Stryder]]'s single \"Spaceship\", which was released in June 2011. While deciding upon his debut solo single, Dappy was contacted by Def Jam, asking him what he would like done with the demos of a track N-Dubz had recorded whilst under the label, which remained unreleased. Dappy decided to re-record the track, \"[[No Regrets (Dappy song)|No Regrets]]\", and release it as his debut solo effort. Featuring a cameo appearance from band-mate Fazer, \"No Regrets\" took the charts by storm, peaking at #1 in the UK and Scotland, and at #8 in Ireland.\n\nFollowing the success of \"No Regrets\", Dappy claimed during an interview that: \"With my solo stuff, I really want to earn the respect of an older audience. I don't think there's any shame in trying to write music that will be recognised by people I admire. Bono. I have big goals. I want to have two #1 singles back-to-back as a solo artist.\"<ref>[http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/dappy/view/29120/ N-Dubz star Dappy has \u2018big goals\u2019 for his solo career] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322184412/http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/dappy/view/29120/ |date=22 March 2012 }}. pressparty.com. Thursday, 21 July 2011.</ref> Dappy soon succeeded, gaining praise from Queen guitarist [[Brian May]], who was \"impressed\" with \"No Regrets\". As a result, Dappy invited May for a guest stint on his second single, which co-incidentally was titled \"[[Rockstar (Dappy song)|Rockstar]]\". \"Rockstar\" was released on 26 February 2012. On 29 February, Dappy revealed that the title of his album would be ''[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]'', claiming that the album \"is motivational music for people who believe they can't do nothing, a battle we have with our own mind.\"<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a368456/dappy-wants-rihanna-adele-for-next-single-dare-to-dream.html |title=Dappy wants Rihanna, Adele for next single 'Dare To Dream' - Music News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=1 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303143451/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a368456/dappy-wants-rihanna-adele-for-next-single-dare-to-dream.html |archive-date=3 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The album's third single was \"[[Come with Me (Dappy song)|Come with Me]]\". Subsequently, he revealed that the fourth single will be \"[[Good Intentions (Dappy song)|Good Intentions]]\", and if \"Rockstar\" peaks at #1 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], he will enlist Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] and British superstar [[Adele]], who will both have vocal sections on the single. He claimed that Rihanna contacted him after she was impressed with a demo tape she had heard of his music.<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\"/> Dappy confirmed in September 2011, before the release of \"Rockstar\" and \"[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]\", that the album's final single will be a collaboration with [[The Wanted]], which will be released towards the end of 2012.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2011/09/12/n-dubz-to-split-and-dappy-to-work-with-rihanna-115875-23414098/ N-Dubz to split and Dappy to work with Rihanna] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918092729/http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2011/09/12/n-dubz-to-split-and-dappy-to-work-with-rihanna-115875-23414098/ |date=18 September 2011 }}. [[Daily Mirror]]. 12 September 2011.</ref>{{Update inline|date=December 2013}}\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Eros Apollo'' and singles===\nDappy's single \"Beautiful Me\" was released on 29 March 2015 and reached number 19 in the UK. He followed this up with the promotional release \"100 (Built for This)\" in July, and the full single \"Money Can't Buy\" in September 2015. All three songs were set to be included on his second [[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]] album ''Miracles'' in November 2015, but the album did not eventuate and Dappy has since left [[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]] and released his first independent EP, ''Eros Apollo'', on Christmas Day 2015.\n\nIn 2016, Dappy released the singles \"Hip Hip Hooray\" and \"Kiss\" and a Freestyle called \"Messi\" these songs again were released via an independent label/management partnership called LEX Music Corp\n\nOn 31 July 2017, Dappy released the single Straight Facts\" Again this was part of a new management deal with PlayDirty manager Vash who currently manages [[Krept and Konan]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/straight-facts-single/id1265134614|title=Straight Facts - Single by Dappy on Apple Music|website=iTunes|access-date=31 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127094148/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/straight-facts-single/id1265134614|archive-date=27 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The music video was released the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vM5qY9l5ixM|title=Dappy - Straight Facts (Official Video)|first=|last=TheDappyVEVO|date=30 July 2017|publisher=YouTube|access-date=31 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809040332/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vM5qY9l5ixM|archive-date=9 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2017, Dappy released his second single under the PlayDirty management called \"Spotlight\" this song charted at 56 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nIn 2018, he released his single \"[[Oh My (Dappy song)|Oh My]]\" featuring fellow British rapper Ay Em. It peaked at 23 in the charts. He followed this up with the song \"All We Know\" which peaked at 64 and released an acoustic onto YouTube called \"Count On Me\".\n\nIn 2019, Dappy collaborated with Tory Lanez releasing 'Not Today<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/6/dappy-and-tory-lanez-pace-around-in-the-plug-records-not-today-vido|title=Dappy and Tory Lanez Pace Around in The Plug Records' \"Not Today\" Video|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628173834/https://hypebeast.com/2019/6/dappy-and-tory-lanez-pace-around-in-the-plug-records-not-today-vido|archive-date=28 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>'.\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\nIn mid 2007, Dappy released \"Love for My Slum\" with fellow UK rap artist Baker Trouble, which was number one on Channel U (then Channel AKA, now [[Now 70s]]) for several weeks and was a big hit in the underground urban scene. However, it didn't do as well with the media and was heavily criticized for a scene in which Dappy is standing outside a block of expensive luxury flats with a \"rich kid\" who is trying to look like a gangster. ''The Independent'' wrote, \"His lyrics combine jealousy with anger: 'You got too much to lose / You're in a great position... You wouldn't last a minute where I'm from / You'd go missing / So appreciate what you got / 'cos I'm still wishing.' And then he grabs the rich kid by his coat, pulls him toward him, and punches him in the face. The silent boy falls instantly to the pavement ... Do scenes like these suggest that music videos are encouraging their viewers to indulge in criminality?\".<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/music-video-violence-should-grime-clean-up-its-act-403286.html\n| title = Music video violence: Should grime clean up its act? - Media, News\n| publisher = The Independent\n| date = 24 September 2007\n| accessdate = 4 December 2009\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120202023845/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/music-video-violence-should-grime-clean-up-its-act-403286.html\n| archive-date = 2 February 2012\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Other papers put that he was \"idolising thuggery\". When asked in interviews about the single, following these comments he said \"these people need to listen to the lyrics, they are about showing appreciation to what you've got\".<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.timeout.com/london/music/features/3668/2.html\n| title = N-Dubz: Interview - Time Out London\n| publisher = Timeout.com\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 December 2009\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091214111005/http://www.timeout.com/london/music/features/3668/2.html\n| archive-date = 14 December 2009\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nDappy was convicted of battery in 2007. In December 2008, Dappy pleaded guilty to two accounts of assault at Chelmsford Magistrates Court, [[Essex]] after reportedly spitting in a girl's face while drunk on a night out. Dappy pleaded guilty to the offences and for each count received four weeks' imprisonment, suspended for 12 months, to run concurrently and 100 hours community service. He was also ordered to pay \u00a350 compensation to the girl and her friend and \u00a3300 costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/15/dappy-avoids-jail-over-brawl|title=Dappy avoids jail over petrol station brawl|first=Press|last=Association|date=15 February 2013|publisher=The Guardian|access-date=20 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074855/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/15/dappy-avoids-jail-over-brawl|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2010, Contostavlos appeared on ''[[The Chris Moyles Show]]'' on [[BBC Radio 1]] with Fazer and Tulisa. The show received a text message from a woman in Boston, Lincolnshire, complaining that Dappy was \"vile\" and \"a little boy with a silly hat\" and that N-Dubz were \"losers\". Dappy secretly copied her phone number from the studio console and, the following day, tried calling her and sent threatening messages including: \"Your {{sic}} gonna die. U sent a very bad msg towards Ndubz on The Chris Moyels {{sic}} show yesterday Morning and for that reason u will never be left alone!!! u say sorry I will leave u alone u ****.\" The woman claimed that she continued to receive messages after declining to apologise, one of which said: \"u dum f*********head u can call me names over the radio but when I call u direct u chicken out u punk!nana f******niii, Dappy\").<ref name=\"2010 Guardian\">{{cite news|last=Swash|first=Rosie|title=N-Dubz's Dappy sent death threats to BBC Radio 1 listener|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jan/15/ndubz-dappy-death-threats|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=1 September 2011|date=15 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118104716/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2010/jan/15/ndubz-dappy-death-threats|archive-date=18 January 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that asterisks were presumably added by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', who originally reported the story.</ref> Dappy's management later apologised on his behalf and offered free tickets to one of his concerts, but he has not apologised to the woman personally.<ref>{{cite news\n| url  = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8461267.stm\n| title = BBC News - N-Dubz star Dappy 'sorry' over text message threats\n| publisher = BBC\n| date  = 15 January 2010\n| accessdate = 15 January 2010\n}}</ref> N-Dubz were subsequently dropped from the Government's anti-bullying \"R U Cyber Safe?\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8461267.stm|title=BBC News - N-Dubz star Dappy 'sorry' over text message threats|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, he was found guilty by a jury at Guildford Crown Court of assault and affray and given a suspended sentence of six months imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web\n| url  = http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/ndubz-dappy-arrested-following-brawl-petrol-station\n| title  = N-Dubz Dappy Sentenced to Six Months in Jail\n| publisher  = Glamour\n| date  = 5 December 2017\n| accessdate  = 17 January 2013\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170629185820/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/ndubz-dappy-arrested-following-brawl-petrol-station\n| archive-date  = 29 June 2017\n| url-status  = live\n}}</ref>  In February 2014, Dappy hit a man in [[Chelmsford]] for which, on 19 June 2014, he was convicted of [[common assault]] and fined.<ref name=fined>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27924582|title=Guilty verdict in former N-Dubz singer Dappy slap case|date=19 June 2014|publisher=BBC News|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229210212/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27924582|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  In September of the same year, he was convicted of an assault in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and given a two month suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-avoids-jail-for-nightclub-attack-9845699.html|title=Dappy avoids jail for nightclub attack|date=7 November 2014|website=The Independent|accessdate=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103145659/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-avoids-jail-for-nightclub-attack-9845699.html|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIn 2017, Dappy was convicted of possession of a bladed article in a public place following an altercation with his partner and given a suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2017-06-26/former-n-dubz-rapper-dappy-given-suspended-jail-sentence-following-row-with-partner/|title=Former N-Dubz star Dappy given suspended jail sentence following row with partner|date=12 May 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626224952/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2017-06-26/former-n-dubz-rapper-dappy-given-suspended-jail-sentence-following-row-with-partner/|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDappy is cousin to fellow band member Tulisa. He lives in St Albans<ref name=fined/> with his girlfriend, Kaye Vassell, and their two sons, Gino and Milo.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Second baby on the way for N-Dubz Dappy\n |url=http://itn.co.uk/e6e29e4c7dc5319f35e6ef132270e05b.html\n |work=[[ITN]]\n |date=13 April 2010\n |accessdate=12 December 2010\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522082936/http://itn.co.uk/e6e29e4c7dc5319f35e6ef132270e05b.html\n |archivedate=22 May 2010\n |df=dmy\n }}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Camden Town]], North [[London]], Contostavlos grew up with his parents, [[Byron Contostavlos]] and Zoi Agorou and older brother Spiros. His father had been a member of the group [[Mungo Jerry]]. Byron died on 12 April 2007. He is of [[Greek-Cypriot]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dappy receives huge backlash after trying to defend use of the N-word|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-from-n-dubz-faces-backlash-after-defending-use-of-n-word-a6789441.html|accessdate=11 April 2018|work=The Independent|date=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412012718/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-from-n-dubz-faces-backlash-after-defending-use-of-n-word-a6789441.html|archive-date=12 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDappy and best friend Fazer started making beats together and coming up with lyrics, later asking Dappy's cousin, [[Tulisa Contostavlos|Tulisa]] (who was reluctant at first), to join the band and started to perform in and around Camden Town from the age of thirteen. At the time they were called the Lickle Rinsers Crew and went under the management of Dappy's father Byron, to whom Dappy was the \"inspiration behind the band\". Byron worked at a local barbers shop, putting all the money he had into equipment and resources for the band at their studio. However, Byron died on 12 April 2007 after a heart attack and [[N-Dubz]] wrote the song \"[[Papa Can You Hear Me?|Papa (Can You Hear Me?)]]\", which was played at his funeral and became the group's second biggest hit at #19, and at #17 in the download charts.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nDappy had the words \"RIP Dad\" tattooed on his neck and doesn't like to say his dad's name, instead referring to him as \"B\" or \"Uncle B\", which was also the name of N-Dubz's [[Uncle B|debut album]]. Before Byron died, he said he'd like their album to be called ''Against All Odds'' but, after his death, the group called their debut album ''[[Uncle B]]'' in tribute, with their second album being called ''[[Against All Odds (N-Dubz album)|Against All Odds]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nHe revealed that he is a \"massive\" [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] fan when N-Dubz appeared on ''[[Live from Studio Five]]'', gushing \"it is an honour to sit next to you\" to former Arsenal striker [[Ian Wright]] who was one of three hosts on the show.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.five.tv/programmes/daytime/live-from-studio-five?filter=Clips&page=5\n |title=Live From Studio Five\n |publisher=Five.tv\n |date=\n |accessdate=11 June 2010\n |df=dmy\n}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Dappy endorsed his manager Archie Lamb's father, [[Norman Lamb|Norman]], in the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] [[2015 Liberal Democrats leadership election|leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/14/rapper-dappy-backs-norman-lambs-bid-for-leadership-of-lib-dems|title = Rapper Dappy backs Norman Lamb's bid for leadership of Lib Dems|last = Perraudin|first = Frances|date = 14 May 2015|work = The Guardian|access-date = 18 May 2015|via = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150524194327/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/14/rapper-dappy-backs-norman-lambs-bid-for-leadership-of-lib-dems|archive-date = 24 May 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Dappy discography}}\n{{See also|N-Dubz discography}}\n*''[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]'' (2012)\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Dappy}}\n{{N-Dubz}}\n{{Takeover Entertainment navbox|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dappy}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:Takeover Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2017}}\n{{Tone|date=July 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| birth_name = Costadinos Contostavlos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], [[London]], England\n| image  = Dappy and Tulisa Contostavlos at Tup Tup Palace.jpg\n| caption = Dappy and Tulisa Contostavlos, 2008\n| instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* actor}}\n| genre  = {{Flat list|\n*[[British hip hop]]\n*[[Grime (music genre)|grime]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| years_active  = 2000\u2013present\n| label  = {{Flat list|\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n*[[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]]\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*[[Island Records|Island]]\n*[[Takeover Entertainment|Takeover Entertainment Ltd]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flat list|\n*[[N-Dubz]]\n*[[Richard Rawson]]\n*[[Tulisa Contostavlos]]{{clear}}\n*[[Tinchy Stryder]]\n*[[Mr Hudson]]\n*[[Cover Drive]]}}\n| background = solo_singer\n| website   = {{URL|http://www.thedappy.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Costadinos Contostavlos'''<ref name=\"Costadinos Contostavlos\">{{cite web\n| title = Costadinos Contostavlos\n| url = http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/costadinos-contostavlos/6461349\n| publisher = Artistdirect\n| accessdate = 29 November 2010\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120623220607/http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/costadinos-contostavlos/6461349\n| archive-date = 23 June 2012\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> (born 11 June 1987), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Dappy''', is a British rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer and actor. He is the [[lead singer]] of the [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]]-based [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Grime music|grime]] trio [[N-Dubz]], with his cousin [[Tulisa Contostavlos|Tulisa]], and [[Fazer (rapper)|Fazer]]. He was known for his slightly unusual dress sense and his love for what he describes as \"eye-catching headwear\". His trademark was wearing a selection of woolly [[chullo]]s (sometimes referred to as \"Dappy hats\"), turning up one or both of the ear-flaps of the hat.\n\n==Music career==\n===2000\u201311: N-Dubz era===\n{{main|N-Dubz}}\n\nDappy appeared on the television show ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' on 29 November 2007, on [[Phill Jupitus]]' team, and wore a trademark \"Dappy hat\", also giving one to [[Simon Amstell]] to wear as part of the gag. Despite vowing he would not return to the show he appeared for a second time on the guest team on 4 December 2008 and for a third time, on Phill's team, which was broadcast on 18 November 2009. He is known to be a good friend of [[Chris Moyles]] and also gets on well with [[Kwasi Danquah III|Tinchy Stryder]] after releasing a single together, called \"[[Number 1 (Tinchy Stryder song)|Number 1]]\". Dappy has made cameo appearances on K.I.G's \"Head, Shoulders, Kneez and Toez\" music video, Gracious K's \"Migraine Skank\" music video, and [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]]'s \"[[Chip Diddy Chip]]\" music video, as one of Chipmunk's school friends.\n\n===2011\u201314: Solo projects and ''Bad Intentions''===\nIt was announced on 17 June 2011 that N-Dubz had left their American record deal, amid rumours that the band had split.<ref>Darvill, Josh (Friday, 17 June 2011). [http://xfactor.tellymix.co.uk/judges/35418-n-dubz-to-split-up-following-tulisa-contstavlos-new-x-factor-role.html N-Dubz to split up following Tulisa Contstavlos new X Factor role] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821115436/http://xfactor.tellymix.co.uk/judges/35418-n-dubz-to-split-up-following-tulisa-contstavlos-new-x-factor-role.html |date=21 August 2011 }}. ''xfactor.tellymix.co.uk.''</ref><ref>[http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/06/n-dubz-set-to-split-up/ N-Dubz set to split up] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019053555/http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/06/n-dubz-set-to-split-up/ |date=19 October 2011 }}. ''[[SB.TV]]''. Saturday, 18 June 2011.</ref><ref>Daniels, Colin (Saturday, 13 August 2011). [http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a334894/n-dubz-dropped-by-us-record-label-def-jam.html N-Dubz dropped by US record label Def Jam] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921110809/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a334894/n-dubz-dropped-by-us-record-label-def-jam.html |date=21 September 2011 }}. ''[[Digital Spy]]''.</ref> These rumours began circulating again in August 2011; however, Dappy insisted the band had not split, but were simply taking a break.<ref>Gritt, Emma (Tuesday, 13 September 2011). [http://www.metro.co.uk/music/875305-dappy-forced-to-retract-claims-n-dubz-will-split-within-two-years Dappy forced to retract claims N-Dubz will split within two years]. ''[[Metro (British newspaper)]]''.</ref> As such, during the band's hiatus period, all three members decided to embark upon solo careers. Before the band's split, Dappy signed a contract with [[Takeover Entertainment|Takeover Entertainment Ltd]] that confirmed that if the band ever split or went on hiatus, he would continue as a solo artist. His first taste of solo stardom came as a guest artist on label-mate [[Kwasi Danquah III|Tinchy Stryder]]'s single \"Spaceship\", which was released in June 2011. While deciding upon his debut solo single, Dappy was contacted by Def Jam, asking him what he would like done with the demos of a track N-Dubz had recorded whilst under the label, which remained unreleased. Dappy decided to re-record the track, \"[[No Regrets (Dappy song)|No Regrets]]\", and release it as his debut solo effort. Featuring a cameo appearance from band-mate Fazer, \"No Regrets\" took the charts by storm, peaking at #1 in the UK and Scotland, and at #8 in Ireland.\n\nFollowing the success of \"No Regrets\", Dappy claimed during an interview that: \"With my solo stuff, I really want to earn the respect of an older audience. I don't think there's any shame in trying to write music that will be recognised by people I admire. Bono. I have big goals. I want to have two #1 singles back-to-back as a solo artist.\"<ref>[http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/dappy/view/29120/ N-Dubz star Dappy has \u2018big goals\u2019 for his solo career] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322184412/http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/dappy/view/29120/ |date=22 March 2012 }}. pressparty.com. Thursday, 21 July 2011.</ref> Dappy soon succeeded, gaining praise from Queen guitarist [[Brian May]], who was \"impressed\" with \"No Regrets\". As a result, Dappy invited May for a guest stint on his second single, which co-incidentally was titled \"[[Rockstar (Dappy song)|Rockstar]]\". \"Rockstar\" was released on 26 February 2012. On 29 February, Dappy revealed that the title of his album would be ''[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]'', claiming that the album \"is motivational music for people who believe they can't do nothing, a battle we have with our own mind.\"<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a368456/dappy-wants-rihanna-adele-for-next-single-dare-to-dream.html |title=Dappy wants Rihanna, Adele for next single 'Dare To Dream' - Music News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=1 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303143451/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a368456/dappy-wants-rihanna-adele-for-next-single-dare-to-dream.html |archive-date=3 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The album's third single was \"[[Come with Me (Dappy song)|Come with Me]]\". Subsequently, he revealed that the fourth single will be \"[[Good Intentions (Dappy song)|Good Intentions]]\", and if \"Rockstar\" peaks at #1 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], he will enlist Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] and British superstar [[Adele]], who will both have vocal sections on the single. He claimed that Rihanna contacted him after she was impressed with a demo tape she had heard of his music.<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\"/> Dappy confirmed in September 2011, before the release of \"Rockstar\" and \"[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]\", that the album's final single will be a collaboration with [[The Wanted]], which will be released towards the end of 2012.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2011/09/12/n-dubz-to-split-and-dappy-to-work-with-rihanna-115875-23414098/ N-Dubz to split and Dappy to work with Rihanna] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918092729/http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2011/09/12/n-dubz-to-split-and-dappy-to-work-with-rihanna-115875-23414098/ |date=18 September 2011 }}. [[Daily Mirror]]. 12 September 2011.</ref>{{Update inline|date=December 2013}}\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Eros Apollo'' and singles===\nDappy's single \"Beautiful Me\" was released on 29 March 2015 and reached number 19 in the UK. He followed this up with the promotional release \"100 (Built for This)\" in July, and the full single \"Money Can't Buy\" in September 2015. All three songs were set to be included on his second [[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]] album ''Miracles'' in November 2015, but the album did not eventuate and Dappy has since left [[All Around the World Productions|All Around the World]] and released his first independent EP, ''Eros Apollo'', on Christmas Day 2015.\n\nIn 2016, Dappy released the singles \"Hip Hip Hooray\" and \"Kiss\" and a Freestyle called \"Messi\" these songs again were released via an independent label/management partnership called LEX Music Corp\n\nOn 31 July 2017, Dappy released the single Straight Facts\" Again this was part of a new management deal with PlayDirty manager Vash who currently manages [[Krept and Konan]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/straight-facts-single/id1265134614|title=Straight Facts - Single by Dappy on Apple Music|website=iTunes|access-date=31 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127094148/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/straight-facts-single/id1265134614|archive-date=27 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The music video was released the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vM5qY9l5ixM|title=Dappy - Straight Facts (Official Video)|first=|last=TheDappyVEVO|date=30 July 2017|publisher=YouTube|access-date=31 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809040332/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vM5qY9l5ixM|archive-date=9 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2017, Dappy released his second single under the PlayDirty management called \"Spotlight\" this song charted at 56 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nIn 2018, he released his single \"[[Oh My (Dappy song)|Oh My]]\" featuring fellow British rapper Ay Em. It peaked at 23 in the charts. He followed this up with the song \"All We Know\" which peaked at 64 and released an acoustic onto YouTube called \"Count On Me\".\n\nIn 2019, Dappy collaborated with Tory Lanez releasing 'Not Today<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/6/dappy-and-tory-lanez-pace-around-in-the-plug-records-not-today-vido|title=Dappy and Tory Lanez Pace Around in The Plug Records' \"Not Today\" Video|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628173834/https://hypebeast.com/2019/6/dappy-and-tory-lanez-pace-around-in-the-plug-records-not-today-vido|archive-date=28 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>'.\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\nIn mid 2007, Dappy released \"Love for My Slum\" with fellow UK rap artist Baker Trouble, which was number one on Channel U (then Channel AKA, now [[Now 70s]]) for several weeks and was a big hit in the underground urban scene. However, it didn't do as well with the media and was heavily criticized for a scene in which Dappy is standing outside a block of expensive luxury flats with a \"rich kid\" who is trying to look like a gangster. ''The Independent'' wrote, \"His lyrics combine jealousy with anger: 'You got too much to lose / You're in a great position... You wouldn't last a minute where I'm from / You'd go missing / So appreciate what you got / 'cos I'm still wishing.' And then he grabs the rich kid by his coat, pulls him toward him, and punches him in the face. The silent boy falls instantly to the pavement ... Do scenes like these suggest that music videos are encouraging their viewers to indulge in criminality?\".<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/music-video-violence-should-grime-clean-up-its-act-403286.html\n| title = Music video violence: Should grime clean up its act? - Media, News\n| publisher = The Independent\n| date = 24 September 2007\n| accessdate = 4 December 2009\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120202023845/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/music-video-violence-should-grime-clean-up-its-act-403286.html\n| archive-date = 2 February 2012\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Other papers put that he was \"idolising thuggery\". When asked in interviews about the single, following these comments he said \"these people need to listen to the lyrics, they are about showing appreciation to what you've got\".<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.timeout.com/london/music/features/3668/2.html\n| title = N-Dubz: Interview - Time Out London\n| publisher = Timeout.com\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 December 2009\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091214111005/http://www.timeout.com/london/music/features/3668/2.html\n| archive-date = 14 December 2009\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nDappy was convicted of battery in 2007. During December 2008, Dappy pleaded guilty to two accounts of assault at Chelmsford Magistrates Court, [[Essex]] after reportedly spitting in a girl's face while drunk on a night out. Dappy pleaded guilty to the offences and for each count received four weeks' imprisonment, suspended for 12 months, to run concurrently and 100 hours community service. He was also ordered to pay \u00a350 compensation to the girl and her friend and \u00a3300 costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/15/dappy-avoids-jail-over-brawl|title=Dappy avoids jail over petrol station brawl|first=Press|last=Association|date=15 February 2013|publisher=The Guardian|access-date=20 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074855/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/15/dappy-avoids-jail-over-brawl|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2010, Contostavlos appeared on ''[[The Chris Moyles Show]]'' on [[BBC Radio 1]] with Fazer and Tulisa. The show received a text message from a woman in Boston, Lincolnshire, complaining that Dappy was \"vile\" and \"a little boy with a silly hat\" and that N-Dubz were \"losers\". Dappy secretly copied her phone number from the studio console and, the following day, tried calling her and sent threatening messages including: \"Your {{sic}} gonna die. U sent a very bad msg towards Ndubz on The Chris Moyels {{sic}} show yesterday Morning and for that reason u will never be left alone!!! u say sorry I will leave u alone u ****.\" The woman claimed that she continued to receive messages after declining to apologise, one of which said: \"u dum f*********head u can call me names over the radio but when I call u direct u chicken out u punk!nana f******niii, Dappy\").<ref name=\"2010 Guardian\">{{cite news|last=Swash|first=Rosie|title=N-Dubz's Dappy sent death threats to BBC Radio 1 listener|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jan/15/ndubz-dappy-death-threats|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=1 September 2011|date=15 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118104716/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2010/jan/15/ndubz-dappy-death-threats|archive-date=18 January 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that asterisks were presumably added by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', who originally reported the story.</ref> Dappy's management later apologised on his behalf and offered free tickets to one of his concerts, but he has not apologised to the woman personally.<ref>{{cite news\n| url  = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8461267.stm\n| title = BBC News - N-Dubz star Dappy 'sorry' over text message threats\n| publisher = BBC\n| date  = 15 January 2010\n| accessdate = 15 January 2010\n}}</ref> N-Dubz were subsequently dropped from the Government's anti-bullying \"R U Cyber Safe?\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8461267.stm|title=BBC News - N-Dubz star Dappy 'sorry' over text message threats|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, he was found guilty by a jury at Guildford Crown Court of assault and affray and given a suspended sentence of six months imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web\n| url  = http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/ndubz-dappy-arrested-following-brawl-petrol-station\n| title  = N-Dubz Dappy Sentenced to Six Months in Jail\n| publisher  = Glamour\n| date  = 5 December 2017\n| accessdate  = 17 January 2013\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170629185820/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/ndubz-dappy-arrested-following-brawl-petrol-station\n| archive-date  = 29 June 2017\n| url-status  = live\n}}</ref>  In February 2014, Dappy hit a man in [[Chelmsford]] for which, on 19 June 2014, he was convicted of [[common assault]] and fined.<ref name=fined>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27924582|title=Guilty verdict in former N-Dubz singer Dappy slap case|date=19 June 2014|publisher=BBC News|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229210212/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27924582|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  In September of the same year, he was convicted of an assault in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and given a two month suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-avoids-jail-for-nightclub-attack-9845699.html|title=Dappy avoids jail for nightclub attack|date=7 November 2014|website=The Independent|accessdate=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103145659/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-avoids-jail-for-nightclub-attack-9845699.html|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIn 2017, Dappy was convicted of possession of a bladed article in a public place following an altercation with his partner and given a suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2017-06-26/former-n-dubz-rapper-dappy-given-suspended-jail-sentence-following-row-with-partner/|title=Former N-Dubz star Dappy given suspended jail sentence following row with partner|date=12 May 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626224952/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2017-06-26/former-n-dubz-rapper-dappy-given-suspended-jail-sentence-following-row-with-partner/|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDappy is cousin to fellow band member Tulisa. He lives in St Albans<ref name=fined/> with his girlfriend, Kaye Vassell, and their two sons, Gino and Milo.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Second baby on the way for N-Dubz Dappy\n |url=http://itn.co.uk/e6e29e4c7dc5319f35e6ef132270e05b.html\n |work=[[ITN]]\n |date=13 April 2010\n |accessdate=12 December 2010\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522082936/http://itn.co.uk/e6e29e4c7dc5319f35e6ef132270e05b.html\n |archivedate=22 May 2010\n |df=dmy\n }}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Camden Town]], North [[London]], Contostavlos grew up with his parents, [[Byron Contostavlos]] and Zoi Agorou and older brother Spiros. His father had been a member of the group [[Mungo Jerry]]. Byron died on 12 April 2007. He is of [[Greek-Cypriot]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dappy receives huge backlash after trying to defend use of the N-word|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-from-n-dubz-faces-backlash-after-defending-use-of-n-word-a6789441.html|accessdate=11 April 2018|work=The Independent|date=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412012718/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dappy-from-n-dubz-faces-backlash-after-defending-use-of-n-word-a6789441.html|archive-date=12 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDappy and best friend Fazer started making beats together and coming up with lyrics, later asking Dappy's cousin, [[Tulisa Contostavlos|Tulisa]] (who was reluctant at first), to join the band and started to perform in and around Camden Town from the age of thirteen. At the time they were called the Lickle Rinsers Crew and went under the management of Dappy's father Byron, to whom Dappy was the \"inspiration behind the band\". Byron worked at a local barbers shop, putting all the money he had into equipment and resources for the band at their studio. However, Byron died on 12 April 2007 after a heart attack and [[N-Dubz]] wrote the song \"[[Papa Can You Hear Me?|Papa (Can You Hear Me?)]]\", which was played at his funeral and became the group's second biggest hit at #19, and at #17 in the download charts.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nDappy had the words \"RIP Dad\" tattooed on his neck and doesn't like to say his dad's name, instead referring to him as \"B\" or \"Uncle B\", which was also the name of N-Dubz's [[Uncle B|debut album]]. Before Byron died, he said he'd like their album to be called ''Against All Odds'' but, after his death, the group called their debut album ''[[Uncle B]]'' in tribute, with their second album being called ''[[Against All Odds (N-Dubz album)|Against All Odds]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nHe revealed that he is a \"massive\" [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] fan when N-Dubz appeared on ''[[Live from Studio Five]]'', gushing \"it is an honour to sit next to you\" to former Arsenal striker [[Ian Wright]] who was one of three hosts on the show.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.five.tv/programmes/daytime/live-from-studio-five?filter=Clips&page=5\n |title=Live From Studio Five\n |publisher=Five.tv\n |date=\n |accessdate=11 June 2010\n |df=dmy\n}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Dappy endorsed his manager Archie Lamb's father, [[Norman Lamb|Norman]], in the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] [[2015 Liberal Democrats leadership election|leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/14/rapper-dappy-backs-norman-lambs-bid-for-leadership-of-lib-dems|title = Rapper Dappy backs Norman Lamb's bid for leadership of Lib Dems|last = Perraudin|first = Frances|date = 14 May 2015|work = The Guardian|access-date = 18 May 2015|via = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150524194327/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/14/rapper-dappy-backs-norman-lambs-bid-for-leadership-of-lib-dems|archive-date = 24 May 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Dappy discography}}\n{{See also|N-Dubz discography}}\n*''[[Bad Intentions (album)|Bad Intentions]]'' (2012)\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Dappy}}\n{{N-Dubz}}\n{{Takeover Entertainment navbox|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dappy}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:Takeover Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriticism and controversy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dappy"}
{"title_page": "Robert E. Murray", "text_new": "{{Other people|Robert Murray or Bob Murray|Robert Murray (disambiguation){{!}}Robert Murray}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|American mining businessman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Robert E. Murray\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1940|1|13}}\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  =\n| religion     =\n| ethnicity    =\n| residence    = [[Moreland Hills, Ohio]], U.S.\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = [[Ohio State University]]\n| occupation   = Business executive\n| party =\n| salary       =\n| networth     =\n| spouse       = Brenda Lou Moore\n| parents      =\n| children     = 3\n| relatives    =\n| website      =\n}}\n'''Robert E. Murray''' (born January 13, 1940){{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} is an American mining engineer,businessman and an accused Zodiac Killer. He founded and was the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Murray Energy]], a mining corporation based in [[St. Clairsville, Ohio]], until it filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.murrayenergycorp.com/message-from-the-founder-ceo/|title=A Message from our Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer|last=Murray|first=Bob|publisher=[[Murray Energy Corporation]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111231214/http://www.murrayenergycorp.com/message-from-the-founder-ceo/|archive-date=November 11, 2017|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> Murray has received attention for his [[climate change denial|denial of climate change]],<ref name=\"LAVELLE\">{{cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/11102017/climate-denial-coal-industry-global-warming-robert-murray-energy|title=Coal Boss Takes Climate Change Denial to the Extreme|last1=Lavelle|first1=Marianne|date=October 11, 2017|work=[[InsideClimate News]]|accessdate=November 16, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325223457/https://insideclimatenews.org/news/11102017/climate-denial-coal-industry-global-warming-robert-murray-energy|archive-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> his actions following the [[Crandall Canyon Mine|Crandall Canyon Mine collapse]], consistent support of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and regularly filing lawsuits against media coverage he finds unflattering.<ref name=slate/><ref name=guardian/><ref name=youtube/>\n\n==Early life==\nMurray was born in 1940.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Murray claims to have lied about his age so he could work in a coal mine at the age of 16 and provide for his family.<ref name=\"apbio\">{{cite news|url=https://archive.triblive.com/news/utah-mine-disaster-yields-frenetic-frontman/|title=Utah mine disaster yields frenetic frontman|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|accessdate=August 9, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629012916/http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_521294.html|archive-date=June 29, 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> He alleges he experienced multiple mining accidents including a head injury involving a large beam.<ref name=\"apbio\"/> Murray says he has one scar running from his head down his back from a separate accident and at one time was trapped in a dark mine for 12 hours before being rescued.<ref name=\"apbio\"/>\n\nMurray was the valedictorian of the [[Bethesda, Ohio|Bethesda]] High School class of 1957.<ref name=\"st141221\">{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/coal-baron-robert-murray-is-still-fired-up-in-person/|title=Coal baron Robert Murray is still fired up|last1=Loth|first1=Tim|date=December 21, 2014|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=August 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151214092244/https://www.seattletimes.com/business/coal-baron-robert-murray-is-still-fired-up-in-person/|archive-date=December 14, 2015}}</ref> Murray received a [[Bachelor of Engineering]] in Mining from [[Ohio State University]]. Thereafter, he attended a six-week management program at [[Harvard Business School]].<ref name = bloombergprof>{{cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=25618338&privcapId=22595942| title = Executive Profile Robert Edward Murray | publisher = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate = August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMurray began his mining career at the [[North American Coal Corporation]] (NACC). He served in a variety of capacities at NACC, winning election to vice president of operations in 1969. From 1974 to 1983, Murray was president of NACC's Western Division and presided over four of its subsidiaries in [[North Dakota]]. In 1974, a strike took place at the Indian Head Mine in [[Zap, North Dakota|Zap]], which North American was attempting to close.<ref name=\"bismarck\">{{cite news|url=https://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/utah-mine-owner-operated-in-north-dakota-mines/article_24f1c7a4-a4bc-501f-b4e9-1c9c1b2e88d5.html|title=Utah mine owner operated in North Dakota mines|last1=Donovan|first1=Lauren|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|accessdate=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827181045/https://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/utah-mine-owner-operated-in-north-dakota-mines/article_24f1c7a4-a4bc-501f-b4e9-1c9c1b2e88d5.html|archive-date=August 27, 2017}}</ref> In 1983, he became president and [[CEO]] of North American.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMurray is a member of the boards of directors of the [[National Mining Association]], American Coal Foundation, National Coal Council, Ohio Coal Association, and Pennsylvania Coal Association. He is a trustee and former president of the [[American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical, and Petroleum Engineers]], Inc., and the Society for Mining, Metallurgy and Exploration, Inc., as well as past president of The Rocky Mountain Coal Mining Institute.<ref name=\"MECWeb\">Murray Energy Corporation Web site</ref>\n\n===Murray Energy===\nMurray started his company in 1988 with the purchase of a single [[continuous mining]] operation with an annual output of one million tons per year. Murray Energy Corporation's strategy involves acquiring high sulfur coal reserves and aiming to be the low-cost producer in primary coal-sourcing regions of the United States. This strategy was based on Murray's belief that the transportation of low-sulfur coal thousands of miles from the [[Powder River Basin]] to meet the growing demand for electricity in some parts of the country was not a viable long-term solution.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Murray also claimed to be inspired to open the mine when a squirrel told him: \"Bob Murray, you should be operating your very own mines.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=July\u2013August 2001|title=Promises Made, Promises Broken Exposing the Real Robert Murray|journal=[[United Mine Workers of America|United Mine Workers Journal]]|volume=112|issue=4}}</ref> At the helm of Murray Energy, he began accumulating reserves that were strategically located near customers, near favorable transportation, and high in energy content (BTU per pound).{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMurray told the [[White House]] in a letter dated August 4, 2017, that without an emergency order to restart coal-fired electrical generating plants, his company and a major customer, power plant operator [[FirstEnergy]] Solutions, would declare bankruptcy.<ref name=\"cnn170822\">{{cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/22/investing/coal-rescue-trump-murray-energy/index.html|title=Trump rejects cry for help from coal execs|last1=Egan|first1=Matt|date=August 22, 2017|accessdate=August 22, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629101902/https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/22/investing/coal-rescue-trump-murray-energy/index.html|archive-date=June 29, 2018|publisher=[[CNN Money]]}}</ref>\n\nMurray Energy Holdings, Co. filed bankruptcy in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio]] on October 29, 2019, as case number 19-56885.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/bankruptcy-case/MURRAY-ENERGY-HOLDINGS|title=Murray Energy Holdings Co. Bankruptcy Filing|work=BankruptcyObserver.com|url-status=live|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Murray was replaced as CEO the same day, although he remains chairman of the board of the new entity, Murray NewCo, while his nephew Robert D. Moore will be president and CEO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfo.com/bankruptcy/2019/10/murray-energy-files-for-chapter-11/|title=Murray Energy Files for Chapter 11|last=Sprouse|first=William|date=October 29, 2019|website=[[CFO (magazine)|CFO]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205031142/https://www.cfo.com/bankruptcy/2019/10/murray-energy-files-for-chapter-11/|archive-date=December 5, 2019|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191029005501/en/|title=Murray Energy Holdings Co. Enters Into Restructuring Support Agreement With Members of Ad Hoc Lender Group and Files Chapter 11 to Access $350 Million in New Money DIP Financing|access-date=October 30, 2019|publisher=[[Murray Energy|Murray Energy Holdings Co.]]|via=[[BusinessWire]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030204753/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191029005501/en/|archive-date=October 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wvgazettemail.com/business/murray-energy-wv-s-largest-coal-producer-seeks-bankruptcy-protection/article_081c0467-5802-5672-9f03-1b474178cfeb.html|title=Murray Energy, WV's largest coal producer, seeks bankruptcy protection|date=October 29, 2019|work=[[Charleston Gazette-Mail]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105014149/https://www.wvgazettemail.com/business/murray-energy-wv-s-largest-coal-producer-seeks-bankruptcy-protection/article_081c0467-5802-5672-9f03-1b474178cfeb.html|archive-date=November 5, 2019|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> Employees expressed concern about losing their pensions and/or medical benefits. Murray is the last major coal contributor to the [[United Mine Workers of America]]'s pension plan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/01/business/murray-energy-coal-bankruptcy-pension/index.html|title='Nervous and scared.' Coal workers fear for pensions after Murray Energy bankruptcy|author=Egan|first=Matt|date=November 1, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109165012/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/01/business/murray-energy-coal-bankruptcy-pension/index.html|archive-date=November 9, 2019|publisher=[[CNN Business]]}}</ref>\n\n===Crandall Canyon Mine collapse===\n{{Main|Crandall Canyon Mine}}\nIn August 2007, six miners were trapped at the Crandall Canyon Mine in [[Utah]], of which [[Murray Energy]] independent operating subsidiary [[UtahAmerican Energy]] had been a part-owner for 12 months. Prior to the collapse, the [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] had received 64 violations and $12,000 in fines.<ref name=\"conferenceslc\"/><ref name=\"sltrib\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_6589559|title=Murray's Illinois mine has 2,787 violations since 2005|last=Gehrke|first=Robert|date=August 10, 2007|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/Plr8i|archive-date=February 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman\">{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=3456428|title=Mine Owner Faces Old Foes After Collapse|last=Russell|first=Goldman|date=August 8, 2007|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112215049/https://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=3456428|archive-date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n\nMurray himself claims that the Crandall Canyon Mine collapse was triggered by a natural 3.9 magnitude [[earthquake]],<ref name=\"boston\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/national/west/view.bg?articleid=1016033|title=Owner of Utah mine is a famously combative figure|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[Boston Herald]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> and that the practice of [[retreat mining]] was not responsible.<ref name=\"seattle1\">{{Cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003828109_mineowner09.html|title=Utah mine owner candid, combative|last=Arrillaga|first=Pauline|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511123531/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003828109_mineowner09.html|archive-date=May 11, 2009}}</ref> Responding to reports of retreat mining, Murray said: \"I wish you would take the word retreat mining out of your vocabulary. Those were words invented by [[Davitt McAteer]], [[Tony Oppegard|Oppegard]], who are lackies for the [[United Mine Workers]], and officials at the United Mine Workers, who would like to organize this coal mine.\"<ref name=\"npr._Utah\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12623050|title=Utah Mine Owner Defends Safety Process|author=Langfitt|first=Frank|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[Morning Edition]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530015528/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12623050|archive-date=June 30, 2012|publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\nHowever, expert [[seismologists]] and government officials dispute this claim, stating that the mine collapse was the cause of a [[coal mine bump]]<ref name=\"boston\"/> caused by the mine's use of retreat mining.<ref name=seattle1/> [[Dick Stickler|Richard E. Stickler]], the government's top mine safety official, said: \"It was not\u2014and I repeat, it was not\u2014a natural occurring earthquake.\"<ref name = \"blameoperator\"/> An analysis by seismologists at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] demonstrated that the seismic event was \"consistent with an underground collapse\".<ref name=\"yearafter\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/26050043|title=Year after mine collapse, many failures clear|date=August 6, 2008|access-date=August 6, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413221038/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/26050043/|archive-date=April 13, 2018|publisher=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dreger|first=Douglas S.|last2=Ford|first2=Sean R.|last3=Walter|first3=William R.|date=July 11, 2008|title=Source Analysis of the Crandall Canyon, Utah, Mine Collapse|url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~sean/Docs/Dreger08_Science.pdf|url-status=live|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|volume=321|issue=5886|pages=217|doi=10.1126/science.1157392|pmid=18621662|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809112359/http://seismo.berkeley.edu/~sean/Docs/Dreger08_Science.pdf|archive-date=August 9, 2017|access-date=January 13, 2020|via=the UC Berkeley Seismology Lab}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/%7Epeggy/Utah20070806.htm|title=Seismic Moment Tensor Report for the 06 Aug 2007, M3.9 Seismic event in central Utah|last=Ford|first=Sean|last2=Dreger|first2=Douglas|date=August 11, 2007|publisher=Berkeley Seismological Laboratory|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626202433/https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~peggy/Utah20070806.htm|archive-date=June 26, 2017|access-date=January 13, 2020|last3=Walter|first3=William|last4=Hellweg|first4=Margaret|last5=Uhrhammer|first5=Robert}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|title=Seismologists confirm Utah mine collapse probably caused temblor|date=August 9, 2007|first1=Robert|last1=Sanders|publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]]|url=https://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/08/09_minecollapse.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109104147/https://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/08/09_minecollapse.shtml|archive-date=January 9, 2018|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Researchers at the University of Utah also confirmed that the tremor was not triggered by an earthquake as Murray had claimed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/28864-earthquakes-explain-crandall-canyon-collapse.html|title=Mine Disaster CSI: Earthquakes Shed New Light on Utah Collapse|last=Oskin|first=Becky|date=April 19, 2013|website=[[Live Science]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004021949/https://www.livescience.com/28864-earthquakes-explain-crandall-canyon-collapse.html|archive-date=October 4, 2014|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2008, the U.S. government's [[Mine Safety and Health Administration]] (MSHA) announced its highest penalty for coal mine safety violations, $1.85 million, for the collapse. The government fined [[Genwal Resources]] $1.34 million \"for violations that directly contributed to the deaths of six miners last year,\" plus nearly $300,000 for other violations. The government also levied a $220,000 fine against a mining consultant, Agapito Associates, \"for faulty analysis of the mine's design.\"<ref name = \"blameoperator\">{{cite news\n| date = July 24, 2008\n| title = Feds blame mine operator for fatal collapse\n| publisher = [[CNN]]\n| url = http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/07/24/mine.collapse/index.html\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130113202428/http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/07/24/mine.collapse/index.html\n| archive-date = January 13, 2013\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\nRobert Murray was heavily criticized for his actions during the rescue attempt. The MSHA cited his volatile behavior, especially at daily briefings for family members. MSHA reported that he \"frequently became very irate and would start yelling,\" even making young children cry. He told family members that \"the media is telling you lies\" and \"the union is your enemy.\"<ref name=\"yearafter\"/>\n\n==Political activity==\nFrom 2005 to 2007, the Murray Energy PAC donated over $150,000 to [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] candidates, including donations totaling $30,000 to Senate candidates such as [[George Allen (U.S. politician)|George Allen]], [[Sam Brownback]], and [[Katherine Harris]].<ref name=\"cbs1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mine-collapse-spotlight-on-murray-energy/|title=Mine Collapse: Spotlight On Murray Energy|date=August 8, 2007|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812113618/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mine-collapse-spotlight-on-murray-energy/|archive-date=August 12, 2018|publisher=[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Donations to Republicans surpassed $1 million from 2005 to 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pacs/lookup2.php?strID=C00410985|title=Murray Energy Summary {{!}} OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> The Ohio Valley Coal PAC, another group affiliated with Murray Energy, donated $10,000 for [[George W. Bush 2000 presidential campaign|George W. Bush's 2000 Presidential campaign]].<ref name=cbs1/>\n\nIn addition to serving on the board of directors of the [[National Mining Association]] (NMA), Murray actively lobbies for pro-industry legislation through his company's [[political action committee]]. In 2001, he testified on behalf of the NMA before a [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means]] subcommittee in favor of proposed tax cuts.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn the wake of 2006's [[Sago Mine disaster]], lawmakers in [[West Virginia]] and [[Ohio]] proposed legislation requiring mine workers to wear emergency tracking devices. Murray lobbied against the laws, calling them \"extremely misguided.\"<ref name=goldman/> He said that politicians were rushing to pass laws and thus \"playing politics with the safety of my employees.\" Murray said that rather than create \"knee-jerk\" state laws after the disaster, such as in the case of West Virginia, which passed the law in less than one day after it was proposed, the federal government should host a panel which would study the industry and make recommendations for safety measures.<ref name=\"craincleveland\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.crainscleveland.com/assets/pdf/CC4331127.PDF|title=Mining for Answers|last=Bennett|first=David|date=January 30 \u2013 February 5, 2005|work=[[Crain's Cleveland Business]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113214450/https://www.crainscleveland.com/assets/pdf/CC4331127.PDF|archive-date=January 13, 2020|issue=6|volume=27|pages=1, 19}}</ref>\n\nMurray claimed that the federal government should be involved for uniform standards and because tension between unions and companies created difficulty in reaching private agreement on safety standards. Murray maintained that the personal tracking devices to be mandated in the state laws, called PEDs, did not work under certain common mining conditions (such as below {{convert|600|ft|m}} in depth), and better devices needed to be developed in order to effectively guard miners in case of accident. He said: \"The will is there. Unfortunately, the technology isn't.\"<ref name=\"craincleveland\"/>\n\nMurray has stated that he supported federal mandates for [[drug test]]ing and fire prevention.<ref name=\"craincleveland\"/>\n\nOn August 14, 2012, Murray hosted [[Mitt Romney]] at Murray Energy's Century coal mine in [[Beallsville, Ohio]]. Several miners contacted a nearby morning talk radio host, David Blomquist, to complain that they were forced to attend the rally without pay. Murray chief operating officer Robert Moore said: \"Attendance was mandatory but no one was forced to attend the event.\" Murray closed the mine the day of the rally and suspended pay to workers, arguing that the rally was important to the coal industry and that attending was in the workers' \"best interest.\" Murray and his corporation were a major donor to Romney and other Republicans, and employees report frequent instances of political pressure from management.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-xpm-2012-aug-29-la-pn-miners-romney-rally-20120829-story.html|title=Ohio miners say they were forced to attend Romney rally|last=Banerjee|first=Neela|date=August 29, 2012|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=September 2, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530204336/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/29/news/la-pn-miners-romney-rally-20120829|archive-date=May 30, 2013|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, the non-profit group [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] filed a complaint with the [[Federal Election Commission]] against Murray and his company alleging violations of federal campaign law in which employees of Murray Energy were required to give one percent of their salary to the company's political action committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/10/crew-files-fec-complaint-over-coal-companys-coerced-campaign-donations|title=CREW Files FEC Complaint Over Coal Company's Coerced Campaign Donations|last=Sheppard|first=Kate|date=October 9, 2012|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=October 13, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029194122/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/10/crew-files-fec-complaint-over-coal-companys-coerced-campaign-donations/|archive-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, 2012, three days following the [[2012 United States presidential election|presidential election]], Murray laid off 156 workers, citing a supposed \"war on coal\" by [[Obama Admininstration|the Obama administration]] as the reason for his decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/after-obama-re-election-ceo-reads-prayer-to-staff-announces-layoffs/2012/11/09/e9bca204-2a63-11e2-bab2-eda299503684_story.html|title=After Obama reelection, Murray Energy CEO reads prayer, announces layoffs|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=November 9, 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HjhWc|archive-date=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 American presidential election]], Murray Energy donated over $300,000 towards candidate [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] inaguration. A memo from Robert Murray itemized a list of 16 energy actions he desired, including giving subsidies to [[Nuclear power plant|nuclear]] and [[coal plant]]s, reducing mine safety regulations, and reducing environmental oversight. The memo was given to Vice President [[Mike Pence]], a similar memo was given to [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] head [[Rick Perry]], and Murray said he gave the memo to Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|title=Murray Energy GOP Donations 2016|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pacs/lookup2.php?strID=C00410985&cycle=2016|website=Open Secrets|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nyti_Howa\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/09/climate/coal-murray-trump-memo.html|title=How a Coal Baron's Wish List Became President Trump's To-Do List|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/rkAHJ|archive-date=April 22, 2018|quote=The memo was written by Robert E. Murray, a longtime Trump supporter who donated $300,000 to the president\u2019s inauguration. In it, Murray, the head of Murray Energy, presented Trump with a wish list of environmental rollbacks just weeks after the inauguration.|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nMurray has continued to actively lobby on energy matters at both the state and national levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/29102019/coal-bankruptcy-bob-murray-energy-chapter-11-trump-regulations-rollback|title=Coal Giant Murray Energy Files for Bankruptcy Despite Trump's Support|last=Gearino|first=Dan|date=October 29, 2019|work=[[InsideClimate News]]|access-date=November 2, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218081751/https://insideclimatenews.org/news/29102019/coal-bankruptcy-bob-murray-energy-chapter-11-trump-regulations-rollback|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/07/775764520/despite-bankruptcy-and-illness-bob-murray-remains-a-loud-voice-for-coal|title=Despite Bankruptcy And Illness, Bob Murray Remains A Loud Voice For Coal|last=Brady|first=Jeff|date=November 7, 2019|work=[[Morning Edition]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108002649/https://www.npr.org/2019/11/07/775764520/despite-bankruptcy-and-illness-bob-murray-remains-a-loud-voice-for-coal|archive-date=January 8, 2020|publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuits==\n=== Journalists and the press ===\nMurray has filed over a dozen defamation lawsuits against journalists and newspapers, none of which reached judgment in his favor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/murray_energy_defamation_lawsuits_huffington_post.php|title=A coal magnate's latest lawsuit was tossed\u2014but Ohio can do more to defend free expression|last=Peters|first=Jonathan|date=May 28, 2014|work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829014718/https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/murray_energy_defamation_lawsuits_huffington_post.php|archive-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref> As an example of the repeated lawsuits against journalists, Robert Murray and Murray Energy filed a lawsuit on August 27, 2012, against environment reporter [[Ken Ward Jr.]] and ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]''.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/104553080/Murray-Energy-vs-WV-Gazette|title=Murray Energy vs. WV Gazette|date=October 30, 2012|publisher=Belmont County Common Pleas Court|via=Scribd|id=Case No. 12 CV 341|url-status=live|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Last Week Tonight'' ===\nIn June 2017, Murray Energy issued a [[cease and desist]] letter to the television show ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Last Week Tonight]]'' following the show's attempt to obtain comment about the coal industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/4823166/john-oliver-coal-last-week-tonight/|title=John Oliver and a Giant Squirrel Picked a Fight with the Coal Industry on Last Week Tonight|author=Locker|first=Melissa|date=June 18, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/RlGRB|archive-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The show went ahead with the episode (June 18),<ref name=\"LWT2017\">{{Cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8|title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|date=June 18, 2017|last=Oliver|first=John|publisher=[[Last Week Tonight]]|via=YouTube}}</ref> in which host [[John Oliver]] discussed the [[#Crandall Canyon Mine collapse|Crandall Canyon Mine collapse]] and expressed the opinion that Murray did not do enough to protect his miners' safety. Three days later, Murray and his companies brought suit against Oliver, the show's writers, [[HBO]], and [[Time Warner]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|title=Republican Coal King Sues HBO Over John Oliver's Show|last=Woodruff|first=Betsy|date=June 21, 2017|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=June 21, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618145641/http://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> The lawsuit alleged that, in the ''Last Week Tonight'' show, Oliver \"incited viewers to do harm to Mr. Murray and his companies.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/06/22/murray-energy-sues-hbo-oliver-over-coal-story-from-last-week-tonight/103105860/|title=Murray Energy sues John Oliver, HBO over coal-industry story|last=Puente|first=Maria|date=June 22, 2017|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720135557/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/06/22/murray-energy-sues-hbo-oliver-over-coal-story-from-last-week-tonight/103105860/|archive-date=July 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/22/media/john-oliver-coal-king-murray-lawsuit/index.html|title=John Oliver sued by coal CEO claiming 'character assassination'|last=Egan|first=Matt|date=June 22, 2017|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429060701/https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/22/media/john-oliver-coal-king-murray-lawsuit/index.html|archive-date=April 29, 2018|publisher=[[CNN Money]]}}</ref> The [[ACLU]] filed an [[amicus brief]] in support of HBO in the case; the brief has been described as \"hilarious,\" and the \"snarkiest legal brief ever.\"<ref name=\"WEISS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/snarky_aclu_brief_filed_on_behalf_of_john_oliver_tells_ceo_anyone_can_legal/|title=Snarky, profane ACLU brief supports John Oliver against coal company CEO|last1=Weiss|first1=Debra Cassens|date=August 3, 2017|work=[[ABA Journal]]|publisher=[[American Bar Association]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114034829/http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/snarky_aclu_brief_filed_on_behalf_of_john_oliver_tells_ceo_anyone_can_legal/|archive-date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref> The brief also included a comparison of Murray with the fictional character [[Dr. Evil]] that was used in the Oliver show, with the explanation that \"it should be remembered that truth is an absolute defense to a claim of defamation.\"<ref>{{cite court|litigants=The Marshall County Coal Company, The Marion County Coal Company, The Harrison County Coal Company, The Ohio County Coal Company, Murray Energy Corporation, And Robert E. Murray, Plaintiffs, V. John Oliver, Charles Wilson, Partially Important Productions, LLC, Home Box Office, Inc., Time Warner Inc., And Does 1through 10|court=United States District Court for the Northern District Of West Virginia |date=January 8, 2017 |url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3911409/Wvnd-19902323086.pdf |access-date=November 16, 2019|quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2017 a federal district court judge ruled that Murray Energy suits against ''[[The New York Times]]'' and HBO could each proceed in a lower state court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/john-oliver-hbo-lose-court-round-to-coal-exec-bob-murray-in-defamation-case|title=John Oliver, HBO lose court round to coal exec Bob Murray in defamation case|last=Siciliano|first=John|date=August 11, 2017|work=[[Washington Examiner]]|accessdate=August 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824183415/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/john-oliver-hbo-lose-court-round-to-coal-exec-bob-murray-in-defamation-case|archive-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The suit against HBO was dismissed with prejudice on February 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawfulmasses.com/breaking-murray-energy-lawsuit-against-john-oliver-dismissed/|title=Murray Energy lawsuit against John Oliver DISMISSED|last=French|first=Leonard|date=February 23, 2018|website=Lawful Masses|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103152225/https://lawfulmasses.com/breaking-murray-energy-lawsuit-against-john-oliver-dismissed/|archive-date=January 3, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, John Oliver discussed the implications of the lawsuit on his show after Murray dropped the suit.<ref name=\"youtube\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UN8bJb8biZU|title=SLAPP Suits: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|date=November 10, 2019|last=Oliver|first=John|publisher=[[Last Week Tonight]]|accessdate=November 10, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Oliver noted that Murray was able to incur little risk to himself by filing his lawsuit in West Virginia, a jurisdiction that neither Oliver nor Murray lived in and that did not have any [[anti-SLAPP]] legislation.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|author=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=November 10, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106154317/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|archive-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=youtube/> HBO was forced to cover $200,000 in legal fees, which smaller media outlets would not be able to absorb, discouraging negative coverage of Murray.<ref name=slate/> Murray's reputation for litigiousness may have deterred other media outlets from covering him, including sexual harassment charges against him.<ref name=\"slate\" /><ref name=youtube/>\n\nThe 2019 episode ended with a [[musical number]], led by Oliver, telling Murray to \"eat shit\", in which a series of intentionally outlandish and obviously false accusations were leveled at Murray, citing a statement by Jeffrey D. Cramer \u2013 the circuit court judge in the case between Murray and Oliver \u2013 noting that the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] has long upheld \"'loose, figurative' language that cannot reasonably be understood to convey facts\" as protected speech.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-takes-aim-at-coal-tycoon-bob-murray-1253803|title=\"Eat S***, Bob!\": John Oliver Takes Aim at Coal Tycoon Bob Murray With Musical Number, Fiery Segment|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=November 11, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217055748/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-takes-aim-at-coal-tycoon-bob-murray-1253803|archive-date=December 17, 2019|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The song's telling Murray to \"eat shit\" was a reference to a 2015 incident where, in response to a bonus program implemented at one of Murray's mines which union members feared would undermine safety, a miner voided his bonus check, wrote \"Eat Shit Bob\" on the back of it, and returned it to management,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-bob_n_7757604|title=\u2018Kiss My Ass, Bob\u2019: A Miner Challenged Coal Magnate Bob Murray. Now He\u2019s Fighting For His Job.|last=Jamieson|first=Dave|date=July 9, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611174015/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-bob_n_7757604|archive-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-miners_n_5706c643e4b0537661892e6c|title=How To Tell Your Boss To Kiss Your Ass, And Get Away With It|last=Jamieson|first=Dave|date=April 7, 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030203414/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-miners_n_5706c643e4b0537661892e6c|archive-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> which Oliver covered in his original 2017 episode on the coal industry.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref name=\"LWT2017\" />\n\n=== Workplace harassment ===\nIn 2019, two lawsuits were filed against Murray for sexual harassment and misconduct against his employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/john-oliver-gloriously-demonstrates-why-rich-assholes-r-1839770568|title=John Oliver gloriously demonstrates why rich assholes really shouldn't sue John Oliver|last=Perkins|first=Dennis|date=November 11, 2019|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/WxerY|archive-date=January 12, 2020|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> In one of the corroborated claims, Murray asked a female assistant to search for the [[kidney stone]] he passed.<ref name=slate/><ref name=youtube/> Murray denied the allegations.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/11/john-oliver-coal-baron-squirrel-slapp-lawsuit-bob-murray.html|title=John Oliver Taunts Coal Baron Enraged by Giant Talking Squirrel With Giant ''Singing'' Squirrels|last=Martinelli|first=Marissa|date=November 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|access-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221080433/https://slate.com/culture/2019/11/john-oliver-coal-baron-squirrel-slapp-lawsuit-bob-murray.html|archive-date=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Global warming==\nIn June 2007, Murray told the [[United States Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works]] that \"the science of [[global warming]] is suspect.\" He also wrote in a May 2007 [[MarketWatch]] editorial: \"The actual environmental risk associated with [[Carbon dioxide in the Earth's atmosphere|carbon emissions]] is highly speculative.\"<ref name=goldman/>\n\nIn a 2007 speech to the New York Coal Trade Association, Murray called [[Al Gore]] \"the [[shaman]] of global gloom and doom\" and added: \"he is more dangerous than his global warming.\"<ref name=\"deseret\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseret.com/2007/8/8/20034086/heated-defense-of-mining-not-odd-for-owner-murray|title=Heated defense of mining not odd for owner Murray|last=Romboy|first=Dennis|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[Deseret News]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119174650/https://www.deseret.com/2007/8/8/20034086/heated-defense-of-mining-not-odd-for-owner-murray|archive-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMurray is a particular opponent of proposed global warming legislation in Congress, saying:\n\n<blockquote>We produce a product that is essential to the standard of living of every American, because our coal produces 52% of the energy in America today, and it is the lowest cost energy, costing one-third to one-fourth the cost of energy from [[natural gas]], [[nuclear power|nuclear]] and [[renewable energy]] resources. And without coal to manufacture electricity, our products will not compete in the global marketplace against foreign countries, because our manufacturers depend on coal, low-cost electricity and people on fixed incomes will not be able to pay their electric bills. Every one of those global warming bills that have been introduced into Congress today eliminates the coal industry and will increase your electric rates, four to five fold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0708/07/cnr.02.html|title=Briefing on Rescue Attempts for Six Trapped Utah Miners {{!}} Transcript|date=August 7, 2007|work=[[CNN Newsroom]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720074919/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0708/07/cnr.02.html|archive-date=July 20, 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nFollowing the presidential election in November 2016, Murray pressed for [[Donald Trump]] to withdraw the United States from all international agreements on climate change and stated: \"so-called global warming is a total hoax.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-10/trump-may-dig-coal-but-industry-s-outlook-is-flat-at-best|title=Trump May 'Dig' Coal, But Industry's Outlook Is Flat at Best|last=Loh|first=Tim|date=November 10, 2016|accessdate=April 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/Nh92d|archive-date=September 1, 2017|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> These claims were made in spite of [[Scientific consensus on climate change|near-universal agreement in the scientific community]] that climate change is a real, progressing, and primarily human-caused phenomenon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.nasa.gov/causes/|title=The Causes of Climate Change|publisher=[[NASA]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMurray resides in [[Moreland Hills, Ohio]] with his wife, Brenda Lou Moore. They have three children.<ref name=\"conferenceslc\">{{Cite news|url=http://origin.sltrib.com/ci_6570325|title=Murray's meltdown: Angry, rambling briefing draws rebukes|last=Gehrke|first=Robert|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|access-date=August 14, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/ZkZ4m|archive-date=February 2, 2013|last2=Beebe|first2=Robert}}</ref><ref name=det>Tizon, Thomas Alex (August 9, 2007). [http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070809/NATION/708090343/1020/rss09 \"Mine's part-owner sings praises of the work as he reports on collapse that has trapped six\"]. ''The Detroit News''. Retrieved on August 10, 2007. {{dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\nMurray has stated that he suffers from [[idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|title=Republican Coal King Sues HBO Over John Oliver's Show|last1=Woodruff|first1=Betsy|date=June 22, 2017|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=June 22, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319205320/https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|archive-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> a scarring of the lung tissue leading to shortness of breath.\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2009, Murray Energy donated $20,000 to support the development of a state-of-the-art mine training facility at [[West Virginia University]]<ref>October 21, 2009; WVU dedicates new coal mining simulator; SNL Energy Daily Coal Report. Retrieved November 2, 2009.</ref> and $10,000 to support the construction of a similar facility at [[Southeastern Illinois College]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Local mine donates to training operation|date=September 11, 2009|work=[[The Daily Register]]|url-status=live|location=[[Harrisburg, Illinois]]}}</ref> Murray also made a personal gift of $1 million to the West Virginia University Research Trust Fund\u2014the largest single donation in the fund's history\u2014and the university established the Robert E. Murray Chairmanship of Mining Engineering in his honor.<ref>October 2009; Robert E. Murray Chairmanship in Mining Engineering established at WVU; Coal News. Retrieved November 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Murray donated over $1.2 million to a project to construct a new building at the [[East Richland Christian Schools|East Richland Christian School]].<ref name=\"ickesfam\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timesleaderonline.com/news/community/2018/07/december-finish-expected-for-new-ickes-family-life-center/|title=December finish expected for new Ickes Family Life Center|last1=Hanson|first1=Shelley|date=July 29, 2018|work=[[Martins Ferry Times Leader|The Times Leader]]|accessdate=March 27, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204031419/https://www.timesleaderonline.com/news/community/2018/07/december-finish-expected-for-new-ickes-family-life-center/|archive-date=December 4, 2018|location=[[Martins Ferry, Ohio]]}}</ref> The 28,000 square foot centre is planned to house a gymnasium, kitchen, and classrooms for use by the school, local church, and wider community.<ref name=\"ickesfam\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071005065054/http://www.newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Robert_Murray.php Robert E. Murray's federal campaign contribution report]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/after-obama-re-election-ceo-reads-prayer-to-staff-announces-layoffs/2012/11/09/e9bca204-2a63-11e2-bab2-eda299503684_story.html?tid=pm_pop After Obama reelection coal company CEO reads prayer to staff, announces layoffs], from ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n*[https://archive.is/oWDqI Coal Man], from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Robert E.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cuyahoga County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:Environmental skepticism]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School Advanced Management Program attendees]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Buffalo Award]]\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Robert Murray or Bob Murray|Robert Murray (disambiguation){{!}}Robert Murray}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|American mining businessman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Robert E. Murray\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1940|1|13}}\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  =\n| religion     =\n| ethnicity    =\n| residence    = [[Moreland Hills, Ohio]], U.S.\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = [[Ohio State University]]\n| occupation   = Business executive\n| party =\n| salary       =\n| networth     =\n| spouse       = Brenda Lou Moore\n| parents      =\n| children     = 3\n| relatives    =\n| website      =\n}}\n'''Robert E. Murray''' (born January 13, 1940){{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} is an American mining engineer and businessman. He founded and was the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Murray Energy]], a mining corporation based in [[St. Clairsville, Ohio]], until it filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.murrayenergycorp.com/message-from-the-founder-ceo/|title=A Message from our Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer|last=Murray|first=Bob|publisher=[[Murray Energy Corporation]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111231214/http://www.murrayenergycorp.com/message-from-the-founder-ceo/|archive-date=November 11, 2017|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> Murray has received attention for his [[climate change denial|denial of climate change]],<ref name=\"LAVELLE\">{{cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/11102017/climate-denial-coal-industry-global-warming-robert-murray-energy|title=Coal Boss Takes Climate Change Denial to the Extreme|last1=Lavelle|first1=Marianne|date=October 11, 2017|work=[[InsideClimate News]]|accessdate=November 16, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325223457/https://insideclimatenews.org/news/11102017/climate-denial-coal-industry-global-warming-robert-murray-energy|archive-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> his actions following the [[Crandall Canyon Mine|Crandall Canyon Mine collapse]], consistent support of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and regularly filing lawsuits against media coverage he finds unflattering.<ref name=slate/><ref name=guardian/><ref name=youtube/>\n\n==Early life==\nMurray was born in 1940.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Murray claims to have lied about his age so he could work in a coal mine at the age of 16 and provide for his family.<ref name=\"apbio\">{{cite news|url=https://archive.triblive.com/news/utah-mine-disaster-yields-frenetic-frontman/|title=Utah mine disaster yields frenetic frontman|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|accessdate=August 9, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629012916/http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_521294.html|archive-date=June 29, 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> He alleges he experienced multiple mining accidents including a head injury involving a large beam.<ref name=\"apbio\"/> Murray says he has one scar running from his head down his back from a separate accident and at one time was trapped in a dark mine for 12 hours before being rescued.<ref name=\"apbio\"/>\n\nMurray was the valedictorian of the [[Bethesda, Ohio|Bethesda]] High School class of 1957.<ref name=\"st141221\">{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/coal-baron-robert-murray-is-still-fired-up-in-person/|title=Coal baron Robert Murray is still fired up|last1=Loth|first1=Tim|date=December 21, 2014|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=August 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151214092244/https://www.seattletimes.com/business/coal-baron-robert-murray-is-still-fired-up-in-person/|archive-date=December 14, 2015}}</ref> Murray received a [[Bachelor of Engineering]] in Mining from [[Ohio State University]]. Thereafter, he attended a six-week management program at [[Harvard Business School]].<ref name = bloombergprof>{{cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=25618338&privcapId=22595942| title = Executive Profile Robert Edward Murray | publisher = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate = August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMurray began his mining career at the [[North American Coal Corporation]] (NACC). He served in a variety of capacities at NACC, winning election to vice president of operations in 1969. From 1974 to 1983, Murray was president of NACC's Western Division and presided over four of its subsidiaries in [[North Dakota]]. In 1974, a strike took place at the Indian Head Mine in [[Zap, North Dakota|Zap]], which North American was attempting to close.<ref name=\"bismarck\">{{cite news|url=https://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/utah-mine-owner-operated-in-north-dakota-mines/article_24f1c7a4-a4bc-501f-b4e9-1c9c1b2e88d5.html|title=Utah mine owner operated in North Dakota mines|last1=Donovan|first1=Lauren|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|accessdate=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827181045/https://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/utah-mine-owner-operated-in-north-dakota-mines/article_24f1c7a4-a4bc-501f-b4e9-1c9c1b2e88d5.html|archive-date=August 27, 2017}}</ref> In 1983, he became president and [[CEO]] of North American.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMurray is a member of the boards of directors of the [[National Mining Association]], American Coal Foundation, National Coal Council, Ohio Coal Association, and Pennsylvania Coal Association. He is a trustee and former president of the [[American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical, and Petroleum Engineers]], Inc., and the Society for Mining, Metallurgy and Exploration, Inc., as well as past president of The Rocky Mountain Coal Mining Institute.<ref name=\"MECWeb\">Murray Energy Corporation Web site</ref>\n\n===Murray Energy===\nMurray started his company in 1988 with the purchase of a single [[continuous mining]] operation with an annual output of one million tons per year. Murray Energy Corporation's strategy involves acquiring high sulfur coal reserves and aiming to be the low-cost producer in primary coal-sourcing regions of the United States. This strategy was based on Murray's belief that the transportation of low-sulfur coal thousands of miles from the [[Powder River Basin]] to meet the growing demand for electricity in some parts of the country was not a viable long-term solution.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Murray also claimed to be inspired to open the mine when a squirrel told him: \"Bob Murray, you should be operating your very own mines.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=July\u2013August 2001|title=Promises Made, Promises Broken Exposing the Real Robert Murray|journal=[[United Mine Workers of America|United Mine Workers Journal]]|volume=112|issue=4}}</ref> At the helm of Murray Energy, he began accumulating reserves that were strategically located near customers, near favorable transportation, and high in energy content (BTU per pound).{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMurray told the [[White House]] in a letter dated August 4, 2017, that without an emergency order to restart coal-fired electrical generating plants, his company and a major customer, power plant operator [[FirstEnergy]] Solutions, would declare bankruptcy.<ref name=\"cnn170822\">{{cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/22/investing/coal-rescue-trump-murray-energy/index.html|title=Trump rejects cry for help from coal execs|last1=Egan|first1=Matt|date=August 22, 2017|accessdate=August 22, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629101902/https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/22/investing/coal-rescue-trump-murray-energy/index.html|archive-date=June 29, 2018|publisher=[[CNN Money]]}}</ref>\n\nMurray Energy Holdings, Co. filed bankruptcy in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio]] on October 29, 2019, as case number 19-56885.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/bankruptcy-case/MURRAY-ENERGY-HOLDINGS|title=Murray Energy Holdings Co. Bankruptcy Filing|work=BankruptcyObserver.com|url-status=live|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Murray was replaced as CEO the same day, although he remains chairman of the board of the new entity, Murray NewCo, while his nephew Robert D. Moore will be president and CEO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfo.com/bankruptcy/2019/10/murray-energy-files-for-chapter-11/|title=Murray Energy Files for Chapter 11|last=Sprouse|first=William|date=October 29, 2019|website=[[CFO (magazine)|CFO]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205031142/https://www.cfo.com/bankruptcy/2019/10/murray-energy-files-for-chapter-11/|archive-date=December 5, 2019|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191029005501/en/|title=Murray Energy Holdings Co. Enters Into Restructuring Support Agreement With Members of Ad Hoc Lender Group and Files Chapter 11 to Access $350 Million in New Money DIP Financing|access-date=October 30, 2019|publisher=[[Murray Energy|Murray Energy Holdings Co.]]|via=[[BusinessWire]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030204753/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191029005501/en/|archive-date=October 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wvgazettemail.com/business/murray-energy-wv-s-largest-coal-producer-seeks-bankruptcy-protection/article_081c0467-5802-5672-9f03-1b474178cfeb.html|title=Murray Energy, WV's largest coal producer, seeks bankruptcy protection|date=October 29, 2019|work=[[Charleston Gazette-Mail]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105014149/https://www.wvgazettemail.com/business/murray-energy-wv-s-largest-coal-producer-seeks-bankruptcy-protection/article_081c0467-5802-5672-9f03-1b474178cfeb.html|archive-date=November 5, 2019|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> Employees expressed concern about losing their pensions and/or medical benefits. Murray is the last major coal contributor to the [[United Mine Workers of America]]'s pension plan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/01/business/murray-energy-coal-bankruptcy-pension/index.html|title='Nervous and scared.' Coal workers fear for pensions after Murray Energy bankruptcy|author=Egan|first=Matt|date=November 1, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109165012/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/01/business/murray-energy-coal-bankruptcy-pension/index.html|archive-date=November 9, 2019|publisher=[[CNN Business]]}}</ref>\n\n===Crandall Canyon Mine collapse===\n{{Main|Crandall Canyon Mine}}\nIn August 2007, six miners were trapped at the Crandall Canyon Mine in [[Utah]], of which [[Murray Energy]] independent operating subsidiary [[UtahAmerican Energy]] had been a part-owner for 12 months. Prior to the collapse, the [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] had received 64 violations and $12,000 in fines.<ref name=\"conferenceslc\"/><ref name=\"sltrib\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_6589559|title=Murray's Illinois mine has 2,787 violations since 2005|last=Gehrke|first=Robert|date=August 10, 2007|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/Plr8i|archive-date=February 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman\">{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=3456428|title=Mine Owner Faces Old Foes After Collapse|last=Russell|first=Goldman|date=August 8, 2007|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112215049/https://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=3456428|archive-date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n\nMurray himself claims that the Crandall Canyon Mine collapse was triggered by a natural 3.9 magnitude [[earthquake]],<ref name=\"boston\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/national/west/view.bg?articleid=1016033|title=Owner of Utah mine is a famously combative figure|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[Boston Herald]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> and that the practice of [[retreat mining]] was not responsible.<ref name=\"seattle1\">{{Cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003828109_mineowner09.html|title=Utah mine owner candid, combative|last=Arrillaga|first=Pauline|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511123531/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003828109_mineowner09.html|archive-date=May 11, 2009}}</ref> Responding to reports of retreat mining, Murray said: \"I wish you would take the word retreat mining out of your vocabulary. Those were words invented by [[Davitt McAteer]], [[Tony Oppegard|Oppegard]], who are lackies for the [[United Mine Workers]], and officials at the United Mine Workers, who would like to organize this coal mine.\"<ref name=\"npr._Utah\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12623050|title=Utah Mine Owner Defends Safety Process|author=Langfitt|first=Frank|date=August 9, 2007|work=[[Morning Edition]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530015528/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12623050|archive-date=June 30, 2012|publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\nHowever, expert [[seismologists]] and government officials dispute this claim, stating that the mine collapse was the cause of a [[coal mine bump]]<ref name=\"boston\"/> caused by the mine's use of retreat mining.<ref name=seattle1/> [[Dick Stickler|Richard E. Stickler]], the government's top mine safety official, said: \"It was not\u2014and I repeat, it was not\u2014a natural occurring earthquake.\"<ref name = \"blameoperator\"/> An analysis by seismologists at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] demonstrated that the seismic event was \"consistent with an underground collapse\".<ref name=\"yearafter\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/26050043|title=Year after mine collapse, many failures clear|date=August 6, 2008|access-date=August 6, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413221038/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/26050043/|archive-date=April 13, 2018|publisher=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dreger|first=Douglas S.|last2=Ford|first2=Sean R.|last3=Walter|first3=William R.|date=July 11, 2008|title=Source Analysis of the Crandall Canyon, Utah, Mine Collapse|url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~sean/Docs/Dreger08_Science.pdf|url-status=live|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|volume=321|issue=5886|pages=217|doi=10.1126/science.1157392|pmid=18621662|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809112359/http://seismo.berkeley.edu/~sean/Docs/Dreger08_Science.pdf|archive-date=August 9, 2017|access-date=January 13, 2020|via=the UC Berkeley Seismology Lab}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/%7Epeggy/Utah20070806.htm|title=Seismic Moment Tensor Report for the 06 Aug 2007, M3.9 Seismic event in central Utah|last=Ford|first=Sean|last2=Dreger|first2=Douglas|date=August 11, 2007|publisher=Berkeley Seismological Laboratory|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626202433/https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~peggy/Utah20070806.htm|archive-date=June 26, 2017|access-date=January 13, 2020|last3=Walter|first3=William|last4=Hellweg|first4=Margaret|last5=Uhrhammer|first5=Robert}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|title=Seismologists confirm Utah mine collapse probably caused temblor|date=August 9, 2007|first1=Robert|last1=Sanders|publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]]|url=https://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/08/09_minecollapse.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109104147/https://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/08/09_minecollapse.shtml|archive-date=January 9, 2018|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Researchers at the University of Utah also confirmed that the tremor was not triggered by an earthquake as Murray had claimed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/28864-earthquakes-explain-crandall-canyon-collapse.html|title=Mine Disaster CSI: Earthquakes Shed New Light on Utah Collapse|last=Oskin|first=Becky|date=April 19, 2013|website=[[Live Science]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004021949/https://www.livescience.com/28864-earthquakes-explain-crandall-canyon-collapse.html|archive-date=October 4, 2014|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2008, the U.S. government's [[Mine Safety and Health Administration]] (MSHA) announced its highest penalty for coal mine safety violations, $1.85 million, for the collapse. The government fined [[Genwal Resources]] $1.34 million \"for violations that directly contributed to the deaths of six miners last year,\" plus nearly $300,000 for other violations. The government also levied a $220,000 fine against a mining consultant, Agapito Associates, \"for faulty analysis of the mine's design.\"<ref name = \"blameoperator\">{{cite news\n| date = July 24, 2008\n| title = Feds blame mine operator for fatal collapse\n| publisher = [[CNN]]\n| url = http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/07/24/mine.collapse/index.html\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130113202428/http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/07/24/mine.collapse/index.html\n| archive-date = January 13, 2013\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\nRobert Murray was heavily criticized for his actions during the rescue attempt. The MSHA cited his volatile behavior, especially at daily briefings for family members. MSHA reported that he \"frequently became very irate and would start yelling,\" even making young children cry. He told family members that \"the media is telling you lies\" and \"the union is your enemy.\"<ref name=\"yearafter\"/>\n\n==Political activity==\nFrom 2005 to 2007, the Murray Energy PAC donated over $150,000 to [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] candidates, including donations totaling $30,000 to Senate candidates such as [[George Allen (U.S. politician)|George Allen]], [[Sam Brownback]], and [[Katherine Harris]].<ref name=\"cbs1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mine-collapse-spotlight-on-murray-energy/|title=Mine Collapse: Spotlight On Murray Energy|date=August 8, 2007|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812113618/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mine-collapse-spotlight-on-murray-energy/|archive-date=August 12, 2018|publisher=[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Donations to Republicans surpassed $1 million from 2005 to 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pacs/lookup2.php?strID=C00410985|title=Murray Energy Summary {{!}} OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> The Ohio Valley Coal PAC, another group affiliated with Murray Energy, donated $10,000 for [[George W. Bush 2000 presidential campaign|George W. Bush's 2000 Presidential campaign]].<ref name=cbs1/>\n\nIn addition to serving on the board of directors of the [[National Mining Association]] (NMA), Murray actively lobbies for pro-industry legislation through his company's [[political action committee]]. In 2001, he testified on behalf of the NMA before a [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means]] subcommittee in favor of proposed tax cuts.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn the wake of 2006's [[Sago Mine disaster]], lawmakers in [[West Virginia]] and [[Ohio]] proposed legislation requiring mine workers to wear emergency tracking devices. Murray lobbied against the laws, calling them \"extremely misguided.\"<ref name=goldman/> He said that politicians were rushing to pass laws and thus \"playing politics with the safety of my employees.\" Murray said that rather than create \"knee-jerk\" state laws after the disaster, such as in the case of West Virginia, which passed the law in less than one day after it was proposed, the federal government should host a panel which would study the industry and make recommendations for safety measures.<ref name=\"craincleveland\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.crainscleveland.com/assets/pdf/CC4331127.PDF|title=Mining for Answers|last=Bennett|first=David|date=January 30 \u2013 February 5, 2005|work=[[Crain's Cleveland Business]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113214450/https://www.crainscleveland.com/assets/pdf/CC4331127.PDF|archive-date=January 13, 2020|issue=6|volume=27|pages=1, 19}}</ref>\n\nMurray claimed that the federal government should be involved for uniform standards and because tension between unions and companies created difficulty in reaching private agreement on safety standards. Murray maintained that the personal tracking devices to be mandated in the state laws, called PEDs, did not work under certain common mining conditions (such as below {{convert|600|ft|m}} in depth), and better devices needed to be developed in order to effectively guard miners in case of accident. He said: \"The will is there. Unfortunately, the technology isn't.\"<ref name=\"craincleveland\"/>\n\nMurray has stated that he supported federal mandates for [[drug test]]ing and fire prevention.<ref name=\"craincleveland\"/>\n\nOn August 14, 2012, Murray hosted [[Mitt Romney]] at Murray Energy's Century coal mine in [[Beallsville, Ohio]]. Several miners contacted a nearby morning talk radio host, David Blomquist, to complain that they were forced to attend the rally without pay. Murray chief operating officer Robert Moore said: \"Attendance was mandatory but no one was forced to attend the event.\" Murray closed the mine the day of the rally and suspended pay to workers, arguing that the rally was important to the coal industry and that attending was in the workers' \"best interest.\" Murray and his corporation were a major donor to Romney and other Republicans, and employees report frequent instances of political pressure from management.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-xpm-2012-aug-29-la-pn-miners-romney-rally-20120829-story.html|title=Ohio miners say they were forced to attend Romney rally|last=Banerjee|first=Neela|date=August 29, 2012|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=September 2, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530204336/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/29/news/la-pn-miners-romney-rally-20120829|archive-date=May 30, 2013|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, the non-profit group [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] filed a complaint with the [[Federal Election Commission]] against Murray and his company alleging violations of federal campaign law in which employees of Murray Energy were required to give one percent of their salary to the company's political action committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/10/crew-files-fec-complaint-over-coal-companys-coerced-campaign-donations|title=CREW Files FEC Complaint Over Coal Company's Coerced Campaign Donations|last=Sheppard|first=Kate|date=October 9, 2012|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=October 13, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029194122/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/10/crew-files-fec-complaint-over-coal-companys-coerced-campaign-donations/|archive-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, 2012, three days following the [[2012 United States presidential election|presidential election]], Murray laid off 156 workers, citing a supposed \"war on coal\" by [[Obama Admininstration|the Obama administration]] as the reason for his decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/after-obama-re-election-ceo-reads-prayer-to-staff-announces-layoffs/2012/11/09/e9bca204-2a63-11e2-bab2-eda299503684_story.html|title=After Obama reelection, Murray Energy CEO reads prayer, announces layoffs|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=November 9, 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HjhWc|archive-date=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 American presidential election]], Murray Energy donated over $300,000 towards candidate [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] inaguration. A memo from Robert Murray itemized a list of 16 energy actions he desired, including giving subsidies to [[Nuclear power plant|nuclear]] and [[coal plant]]s, reducing mine safety regulations, and reducing environmental oversight. The memo was given to Vice President [[Mike Pence]], a similar memo was given to [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] head [[Rick Perry]], and Murray said he gave the memo to Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|title=Murray Energy GOP Donations 2016|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pacs/lookup2.php?strID=C00410985&cycle=2016|website=Open Secrets|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nyti_Howa\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/09/climate/coal-murray-trump-memo.html|title=How a Coal Baron's Wish List Became President Trump's To-Do List|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/rkAHJ|archive-date=April 22, 2018|quote=The memo was written by Robert E. Murray, a longtime Trump supporter who donated $300,000 to the president\u2019s inauguration. In it, Murray, the head of Murray Energy, presented Trump with a wish list of environmental rollbacks just weeks after the inauguration.|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nMurray has continued to actively lobby on energy matters at both the state and national levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/29102019/coal-bankruptcy-bob-murray-energy-chapter-11-trump-regulations-rollback|title=Coal Giant Murray Energy Files for Bankruptcy Despite Trump's Support|last=Gearino|first=Dan|date=October 29, 2019|work=[[InsideClimate News]]|access-date=November 2, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218081751/https://insideclimatenews.org/news/29102019/coal-bankruptcy-bob-murray-energy-chapter-11-trump-regulations-rollback|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/07/775764520/despite-bankruptcy-and-illness-bob-murray-remains-a-loud-voice-for-coal|title=Despite Bankruptcy And Illness, Bob Murray Remains A Loud Voice For Coal|last=Brady|first=Jeff|date=November 7, 2019|work=[[Morning Edition]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108002649/https://www.npr.org/2019/11/07/775764520/despite-bankruptcy-and-illness-bob-murray-remains-a-loud-voice-for-coal|archive-date=January 8, 2020|publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuits==\n=== Journalists and the press ===\nMurray has filed over a dozen defamation lawsuits against journalists and newspapers, none of which reached judgment in his favor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/murray_energy_defamation_lawsuits_huffington_post.php|title=A coal magnate's latest lawsuit was tossed\u2014but Ohio can do more to defend free expression|last=Peters|first=Jonathan|date=May 28, 2014|work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829014718/https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/murray_energy_defamation_lawsuits_huffington_post.php|archive-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref> As an example of the repeated lawsuits against journalists, Robert Murray and Murray Energy filed a lawsuit on August 27, 2012, against environment reporter [[Ken Ward Jr.]] and ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]''.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/104553080/Murray-Energy-vs-WV-Gazette|title=Murray Energy vs. WV Gazette|date=October 30, 2012|publisher=Belmont County Common Pleas Court|via=Scribd|id=Case No. 12 CV 341|url-status=live|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Last Week Tonight'' ===\nIn June 2017, Murray Energy issued a [[cease and desist]] letter to the television show ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Last Week Tonight]]'' following the show's attempt to obtain comment about the coal industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/4823166/john-oliver-coal-last-week-tonight/|title=John Oliver and a Giant Squirrel Picked a Fight with the Coal Industry on Last Week Tonight|author=Locker|first=Melissa|date=June 18, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/RlGRB|archive-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The show went ahead with the episode (June 18),<ref name=\"LWT2017\">{{Cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8|title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|date=June 18, 2017|last=Oliver|first=John|publisher=[[Last Week Tonight]]|via=YouTube}}</ref> in which host [[John Oliver]] discussed the [[#Crandall Canyon Mine collapse|Crandall Canyon Mine collapse]] and expressed the opinion that Murray did not do enough to protect his miners' safety. Three days later, Murray and his companies brought suit against Oliver, the show's writers, [[HBO]], and [[Time Warner]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|title=Republican Coal King Sues HBO Over John Oliver's Show|last=Woodruff|first=Betsy|date=June 21, 2017|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=June 21, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618145641/http://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> The lawsuit alleged that, in the ''Last Week Tonight'' show, Oliver \"incited viewers to do harm to Mr. Murray and his companies.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/06/22/murray-energy-sues-hbo-oliver-over-coal-story-from-last-week-tonight/103105860/|title=Murray Energy sues John Oliver, HBO over coal-industry story|last=Puente|first=Maria|date=June 22, 2017|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720135557/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/06/22/murray-energy-sues-hbo-oliver-over-coal-story-from-last-week-tonight/103105860/|archive-date=July 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/22/media/john-oliver-coal-king-murray-lawsuit/index.html|title=John Oliver sued by coal CEO claiming 'character assassination'|last=Egan|first=Matt|date=June 22, 2017|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429060701/https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/22/media/john-oliver-coal-king-murray-lawsuit/index.html|archive-date=April 29, 2018|publisher=[[CNN Money]]}}</ref> The [[ACLU]] filed an [[amicus brief]] in support of HBO in the case; the brief has been described as \"hilarious,\" and the \"snarkiest legal brief ever.\"<ref name=\"WEISS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/snarky_aclu_brief_filed_on_behalf_of_john_oliver_tells_ceo_anyone_can_legal/|title=Snarky, profane ACLU brief supports John Oliver against coal company CEO|last1=Weiss|first1=Debra Cassens|date=August 3, 2017|work=[[ABA Journal]]|publisher=[[American Bar Association]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114034829/http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/snarky_aclu_brief_filed_on_behalf_of_john_oliver_tells_ceo_anyone_can_legal/|archive-date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref> The brief also included a comparison of Murray with the fictional character [[Dr. Evil]] that was used in the Oliver show, with the explanation that \"it should be remembered that truth is an absolute defense to a claim of defamation.\"<ref>{{cite court|litigants=The Marshall County Coal Company, The Marion County Coal Company, The Harrison County Coal Company, The Ohio County Coal Company, Murray Energy Corporation, And Robert E. Murray, Plaintiffs, V. John Oliver, Charles Wilson, Partially Important Productions, LLC, Home Box Office, Inc., Time Warner Inc., And Does 1through 10|court=United States District Court for the Northern District Of West Virginia |date=January 8, 2017 |url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3911409/Wvnd-19902323086.pdf |access-date=November 16, 2019|quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2017 a federal district court judge ruled that Murray Energy suits against ''[[The New York Times]]'' and HBO could each proceed in a lower state court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/john-oliver-hbo-lose-court-round-to-coal-exec-bob-murray-in-defamation-case|title=John Oliver, HBO lose court round to coal exec Bob Murray in defamation case|last=Siciliano|first=John|date=August 11, 2017|work=[[Washington Examiner]]|accessdate=August 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824183415/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/john-oliver-hbo-lose-court-round-to-coal-exec-bob-murray-in-defamation-case|archive-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The suit against HBO was dismissed with prejudice on February 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawfulmasses.com/breaking-murray-energy-lawsuit-against-john-oliver-dismissed/|title=Murray Energy lawsuit against John Oliver DISMISSED|last=French|first=Leonard|date=February 23, 2018|website=Lawful Masses|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103152225/https://lawfulmasses.com/breaking-murray-energy-lawsuit-against-john-oliver-dismissed/|archive-date=January 3, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, John Oliver discussed the implications of the lawsuit on his show after Murray dropped the suit.<ref name=\"youtube\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UN8bJb8biZU|title=SLAPP Suits: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|date=November 10, 2019|last=Oliver|first=John|publisher=[[Last Week Tonight]]|accessdate=November 10, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Oliver noted that Murray was able to incur little risk to himself by filing his lawsuit in West Virginia, a jurisdiction that neither Oliver nor Murray lived in and that did not have any [[anti-SLAPP]] legislation.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|author=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=November 10, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106154317/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|archive-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=youtube/> HBO was forced to cover $200,000 in legal fees, which smaller media outlets would not be able to absorb, discouraging negative coverage of Murray.<ref name=slate/> Murray's reputation for litigiousness may have deterred other media outlets from covering him, including sexual harassment charges against him.<ref name=\"slate\" /><ref name=youtube/>\n\nThe 2019 episode ended with a [[musical number]], led by Oliver, telling Murray to \"eat shit\", in which a series of intentionally outlandish and obviously false accusations were leveled at Murray, citing a statement by Jeffrey D. Cramer \u2013 the circuit court judge in the case between Murray and Oliver \u2013 noting that the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] has long upheld \"'loose, figurative' language that cannot reasonably be understood to convey facts\" as protected speech.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-takes-aim-at-coal-tycoon-bob-murray-1253803|title=\"Eat S***, Bob!\": John Oliver Takes Aim at Coal Tycoon Bob Murray With Musical Number, Fiery Segment|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=November 11, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217055748/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-takes-aim-at-coal-tycoon-bob-murray-1253803|archive-date=December 17, 2019|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The song's telling Murray to \"eat shit\" was a reference to a 2015 incident where, in response to a bonus program implemented at one of Murray's mines which union members feared would undermine safety, a miner voided his bonus check, wrote \"Eat Shit Bob\" on the back of it, and returned it to management,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-bob_n_7757604|title=\u2018Kiss My Ass, Bob\u2019: A Miner Challenged Coal Magnate Bob Murray. Now He\u2019s Fighting For His Job.|last=Jamieson|first=Dave|date=July 9, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611174015/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-bob_n_7757604|archive-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-miners_n_5706c643e4b0537661892e6c|title=How To Tell Your Boss To Kiss Your Ass, And Get Away With It|last=Jamieson|first=Dave|date=April 7, 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030203414/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/kiss-my-ass-miners_n_5706c643e4b0537661892e6c|archive-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> which Oliver covered in his original 2017 episode on the coal industry.<ref name=\"youtube\" /><ref name=\"LWT2017\" />\n\n=== Workplace harassment ===\nIn 2019, two lawsuits were filed against Murray for sexual harassment and misconduct against his employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/john-oliver-gloriously-demonstrates-why-rich-assholes-r-1839770568|title=John Oliver gloriously demonstrates why rich assholes really shouldn't sue John Oliver|last=Perkins|first=Dennis|date=November 11, 2019|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/WxerY|archive-date=January 12, 2020|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> In one of the corroborated claims, Murray asked a female assistant to search for the [[kidney stone]] he passed.<ref name=slate/><ref name=youtube/> Murray denied the allegations.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/11/john-oliver-coal-baron-squirrel-slapp-lawsuit-bob-murray.html|title=John Oliver Taunts Coal Baron Enraged by Giant Talking Squirrel With Giant ''Singing'' Squirrels|last=Martinelli|first=Marissa|date=November 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|access-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221080433/https://slate.com/culture/2019/11/john-oliver-coal-baron-squirrel-slapp-lawsuit-bob-murray.html|archive-date=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Global warming==\nIn June 2007, Murray told the [[United States Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works]] that \"the science of [[global warming]] is suspect.\" He also wrote in a May 2007 [[MarketWatch]] editorial: \"The actual environmental risk associated with [[Carbon dioxide in the Earth's atmosphere|carbon emissions]] is highly speculative.\"<ref name=goldman/>\n\nIn a 2007 speech to the New York Coal Trade Association, Murray called [[Al Gore]] \"the [[shaman]] of global gloom and doom\" and added: \"he is more dangerous than his global warming.\"<ref name=\"deseret\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseret.com/2007/8/8/20034086/heated-defense-of-mining-not-odd-for-owner-murray|title=Heated defense of mining not odd for owner Murray|last=Romboy|first=Dennis|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[Deseret News]]|access-date=August 10, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119174650/https://www.deseret.com/2007/8/8/20034086/heated-defense-of-mining-not-odd-for-owner-murray|archive-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMurray is a particular opponent of proposed global warming legislation in Congress, saying:\n\n<blockquote>We produce a product that is essential to the standard of living of every American, because our coal produces 52% of the energy in America today, and it is the lowest cost energy, costing one-third to one-fourth the cost of energy from [[natural gas]], [[nuclear power|nuclear]] and [[renewable energy]] resources. And without coal to manufacture electricity, our products will not compete in the global marketplace against foreign countries, because our manufacturers depend on coal, low-cost electricity and people on fixed incomes will not be able to pay their electric bills. Every one of those global warming bills that have been introduced into Congress today eliminates the coal industry and will increase your electric rates, four to five fold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0708/07/cnr.02.html|title=Briefing on Rescue Attempts for Six Trapped Utah Miners {{!}} Transcript|date=August 7, 2007|work=[[CNN Newsroom]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720074919/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0708/07/cnr.02.html|archive-date=July 20, 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nFollowing the presidential election in November 2016, Murray pressed for [[Donald Trump]] to withdraw the United States from all international agreements on climate change and stated: \"so-called global warming is a total hoax.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-10/trump-may-dig-coal-but-industry-s-outlook-is-flat-at-best|title=Trump May 'Dig' Coal, But Industry's Outlook Is Flat at Best|last=Loh|first=Tim|date=November 10, 2016|accessdate=April 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/Nh92d|archive-date=September 1, 2017|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> These claims were made in spite of [[Scientific consensus on climate change|near-universal agreement in the scientific community]] that climate change is a real, progressing, and primarily human-caused phenomenon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.nasa.gov/causes/|title=The Causes of Climate Change|publisher=[[NASA]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMurray resides in [[Moreland Hills, Ohio]] with his wife, Brenda Lou Moore. They have three children.<ref name=\"conferenceslc\">{{Cite news|url=http://origin.sltrib.com/ci_6570325|title=Murray's meltdown: Angry, rambling briefing draws rebukes|last=Gehrke|first=Robert|date=August 8, 2007|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|access-date=August 14, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/ZkZ4m|archive-date=February 2, 2013|last2=Beebe|first2=Robert}}</ref><ref name=det>Tizon, Thomas Alex (August 9, 2007). [http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070809/NATION/708090343/1020/rss09 \"Mine's part-owner sings praises of the work as he reports on collapse that has trapped six\"]. ''The Detroit News''. Retrieved on August 10, 2007. {{dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\nMurray has stated that he suffers from [[idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|title=Republican Coal King Sues HBO Over John Oliver's Show|last1=Woodruff|first1=Betsy|date=June 22, 2017|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=June 22, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319205320/https://www.thedailybeast.com/coal-king-sues-hbo-over-john-olivers-show|archive-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> a scarring of the lung tissue leading to shortness of breath.\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2009, Murray Energy donated $20,000 to support the development of a state-of-the-art mine training facility at [[West Virginia University]]<ref>October 21, 2009; WVU dedicates new coal mining simulator; SNL Energy Daily Coal Report. Retrieved November 2, 2009.</ref> and $10,000 to support the construction of a similar facility at [[Southeastern Illinois College]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Local mine donates to training operation|date=September 11, 2009|work=[[The Daily Register]]|url-status=live|location=[[Harrisburg, Illinois]]}}</ref> Murray also made a personal gift of $1 million to the West Virginia University Research Trust Fund\u2014the largest single donation in the fund's history\u2014and the university established the Robert E. Murray Chairmanship of Mining Engineering in his honor.<ref>October 2009; Robert E. Murray Chairmanship in Mining Engineering established at WVU; Coal News. Retrieved November 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Murray donated over $1.2 million to a project to construct a new building at the [[East Richland Christian Schools|East Richland Christian School]].<ref name=\"ickesfam\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timesleaderonline.com/news/community/2018/07/december-finish-expected-for-new-ickes-family-life-center/|title=December finish expected for new Ickes Family Life Center|last1=Hanson|first1=Shelley|date=July 29, 2018|work=[[Martins Ferry Times Leader|The Times Leader]]|accessdate=March 27, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204031419/https://www.timesleaderonline.com/news/community/2018/07/december-finish-expected-for-new-ickes-family-life-center/|archive-date=December 4, 2018|location=[[Martins Ferry, Ohio]]}}</ref> The 28,000 square foot centre is planned to house a gymnasium, kitchen, and classrooms for use by the school, local church, and wider community.<ref name=\"ickesfam\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071005065054/http://www.newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Robert_Murray.php Robert E. Murray's federal campaign contribution report]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/after-obama-re-election-ceo-reads-prayer-to-staff-announces-layoffs/2012/11/09/e9bca204-2a63-11e2-bab2-eda299503684_story.html?tid=pm_pop After Obama reelection coal company CEO reads prayer to staff, announces layoffs], from ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n*[https://archive.is/oWDqI Coal Man], from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Robert E.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cuyahoga County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:Environmental skepticism]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School Advanced Management Program attendees]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Buffalo Award]]\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]\n", "name_user": "46.19.225.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_E._Murray"}
{"title_page": "Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993", "text_new": "{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993\n| fullname = An Act To grant family and temporary medical leave under certain circumstances.\n| acronym = FMLA\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 103rd\n| effective date =\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|103|3}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|107|6}}\n| acts amended =\n| title amended = [[Title 29 of the United States Code|29 USC: Labor]]\n| sections created = [[29 U.S.C.]] sec. 2601\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d103:HR00001:@@@S\n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|103|HR|1}}\n| introducedby = [[William D. Ford]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Michigan|MI]])\n| introduceddate = January 5, 1993\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Education and Labor|House Education and Labor]], [[United States House Committee on Post Office and Civil Service|House Post Office and Civil Service]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = February 3, 1993\n| passedvote1 = [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll022.xml 265\u2013163]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = February 4, 1993\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=103&session=1&vote=00011 71\u201327]\n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = February 4, 1993\n| agreedvote3 = Via {{USBill|103|HRes|71}}, [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll029.xml 247\u2013152]\n| signedpresident = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| signeddate = February 5, 1993\n| amendments = [[No Child Left Behind Act]]\n| SCOTUS cases =\n}}\nThe '''Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993''' ('''FMLA''') is a [[United States labor law]] requiring covered employers to provide employees with job-protected and unpaid leave for qualified medical and family reasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family and Medical Leave Act |first=Stephen |last=Bruce |website=HR Daily Advisor |url=http://hrdailyadvisor.blr.com/archive/category/1011.aspx |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> The FMLA was a major part of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s first-term domestic agenda, and he signed it into law on February 5, 1993. The FMLA is administered by the [[Wage and Hour Division]] of the [[United States Department of Labor]].\n\nThe FMLA allows eligible employees to take up to 12 work weeks of unpaid leave during any 12-month period to care for a new child, care for a seriously ill family member, or recover from a serious illness. The FMLA covers both public- and private-sector employees, but certain categories of employees, including elected officials and highly compensated employees, are excluded from the law or face certain limitations. In order to be eligible for FMLA leave, an employee must have worked for the employer for at least 12 months, have worked at least 1,250 hours over the past 12 months, and work for an employer with at least fifty employees. Several states have passed laws providing additional family and medical leave protections for workers.\n\n==Background==\n\nPrior to the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 presidential election]], a family medical leave act had been vetoed twice by President [[George H. W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilentz|first1=Sean|title=The Age of Reagan|date=2008|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-074480-9|pp=[https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile/page/327 327\u2013328]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile/page/327}}</ref> After [[Bill Clinton]] won the 1992 election, a law protecting family medical leave became one of his major first-term domestic priorities. Rapid growth in the workforce, including a large number of women joining, suggested a necessary federal regulation that would support the working class who desired to raise a family and/or required time off for illness related situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=46777|title=William J. Clinton: Statement on Signing the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> President Clinton signed the bill into law on February 5, 1993 ({{USPL|103|3}}; [[29 U.S.C.]] sec. 2601; 29 [[Code of Federal Regulations|CFR]] 825) to take effect on August 5, 1993.\n\nThe United States Congress passed the Act with the understanding that \u201cit is important for the development of children and the [[family]] unit that fathers and mothers be able to participate in early [[Parenting|childrearing]] \u2026 [and] the lack of employment policies to accommodate working parents can force individuals to choose between job security and parenting\u201d.<ref>Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20132 quoted</ref> It also stressed the Act was intended to provide leave protection for individuals \u201cin a manner that accommodates the legitimate interests of employers\u201d.<ref>Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20132 quoted.</ref>\n\n==Contents==\n[[File:Childcare Development Center-Crestwood High School cheerleaders 120815-F-PG936-400.jpg|thumb|right|Because there is no right to education and [[child care]] for [[Pre-kindergarten|children under five]], the costs of child care fall on parents. But in 2016, four states had legislated for [[paid family leave]].<ref>[[California]], [[New Jersey]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[New York (state)|New York]]</ref>]]\n\n===Scope of rights===\nThe Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 generally applies to employers of 50 or more employees in 20 weeks of the last year. Employees must have worked over 12 months and 1250 hours in the last year (around 25 hours a week). However, employees \"at which such employer employs less than 50 employees if the total number of employees employed by that employer within 75 miles of that worksite is less than 50.\"<ref>29 USC \u00a72611(2)</ref> A worksite includes a public agency, including schools and state, local, and federal employers. The 50 employee threshold does not apply to public agency employees and local educational agencies. There are special hours rules for certain airline employees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Family and Medical Leave Act Airline Flight Crew Technical Amendments|url=http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/airline.htm#.UMkHuIPAdBM}}</ref>\n\nEmployees must give notice of 30 days to employers if birth or adoption is \"foreseeable\",<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(e)</ref> and for serious health conditions if practicable. Treatments should be arranged \"so as not to disrupt unduly the operations of the employer\" according to medical advice.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(e)(2)</ref>\n\nAlong with the 30 day notice, there are also other requirements to be made when seeking the FMLA rights. If an employee wants to leave the first time using ones FMLA rights, the person must first claim the Family and Medical Leave Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opm.gov/policy-data-oversight/pay-leave/leave-administration/fact-sheets/family-and-medical-leave/|title=Family and Medical Leave for Federal Employees|website=U.S. Office of Personnel Management|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> In the case that an employee were to leave again under the FMLA act, the same process must proceed.<ref name=\"FS28\">{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet #28: The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28.pdf |website=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=21 August 2019 |date=2012}}</ref>\n\nWith the release of employees, there is a [[certification]] as well. The absence of an employee due to the conditions he or she may have may require a certification as proof of the verification of absence.<ref name=\"FS28\" /> In order to certify the leave of an employee, the employer may ask for other requirements. An example of these requirements are requiring multiple medical opinions. All of these prerequisites are at the employer's [[expense]]. There are also certain rules that may apply to those who work at local education [[Institution|agencies]].<ref name=\"FS28\" />\n\n===Rights during leave===\nEmployees can have up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave for child birth, adoption, to care for a close relative in poor health, or because of an employee's own poor health.<ref>29 USC \u00a72512(a)(2) and on adoption, see ''[[Kelley v Crosfield Catalysts]]'' 135 F2d 1202 (7th Circuit 1998) The same rules for federal employees were codified in 5 USC \u00a7\u00a76381\u20136387.</ref> In full, the purposes for leave are:\n* to care for a new child, whether for the birth, the adoption, or placement of a child in foster care;\n* to care for a seriously ill family member (spouse, son, daughter, or parent) (Note: Son/daughter has been clarified by the Department of Labor to mean a child under the age of 18 or a child over the age of 18 with a mental or physical disability as defined by the Americans With Disabilities Act, which excludes, among other conditions, pregnancy and post-partum recovery from childbirth);<ref>{{cite news|title=DoL Opinion|url=http://www.dol.gov/WHD/opinion/fmla/prior2002/FMLA-51.htm}}</ref>\n* to recover from a worker's own serious illness;\n* to care for an injured service member in the family; or\n* to address qualifying exigencies arising out of a family member's deployment.\n* twenty-six workweeks of leave during a single 12-month period to care for a covered servicemember with a serious injury or illness if the eligible employee is the servicemember's spouse, son, daughter, parent, or next of kin (military caregiver leave).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/ |title=Family and Medical Leave Act \u2013 Wage and Hour Division (WHD) \u2013 U.S. Department of Labor |publisher=Dol.gov |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n\nChild care leave should be taken in one lump, unless an employer agrees otherwise.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(a)(2)</ref> If a father and mother have the same employer, they must share their leave, in effect halving each person's rights, if the employer so chooses.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(f) \u201cthe aggregate number of workweeks of leave to which both may be entitled may be limited to 12 workweeks\u201d</ref>\n\nEmployers must provide benefits during the unpaid leave.<ref>29 USC \u00a72614(c). If an employee quits, the employer is enabled to recoup costs.</ref> Under \u00a72652(b) states are empowered to provide \"greater family or medical leave rights\".\n\nSince 2008, the Department of Labor has allowed the spouse, child, or parent of an active duty military member who is deployed overseas for 12 or more months to take up to 12 weeks of leave. Also, a military caregiver provision was added that would allow a caregiver to take up to 26 weeks of leave in order to actively care for a military member who requires medical attention for acute or ongoing conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/MilitaryFLProvisions.htm|title=Military Family Leave Provisions of the FMLA - Wage and Hour Division (WHD) - U.S. Department of Labor|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===Substitute leave===\nUnder \u00a72612(2)(A) an employer can make an employee substitute the right to 12 unpaid weeks of leave for \"accrued paid vacation leave, personal leave or family leave\" in an employer's personnel policy. Originally the Department of Labor had a penalty to make employers notify employees that this might happen. However, five judges in the [[US Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ragsdale v Wolverine World Wide, Inc]]'' held that the statute precluded the right of the Department of Labor to do so. Four dissenting judges would have held that nothing prevented the rule, and it was the Department of Labor's job to enforce the law.<ref>[http://www.worldlii.org/us/cases/federal/USSC/2002/557.html 535 US 81] (2002)</ref>\n\n===Right to return to job===\nAfter unpaid leave, an employee generally has the right to return to their job, except for employees who are in the top 10% of highest paid and the employer can argue refusal \"is necessary to prevent substantial and grievous economic injury to the operations of the employer.\"<ref>29 USC \u00a72614(b). Under 29 USC \u00a72612(b)(2) employers may transfer employees to another position with similar pay and benefits if health absences could be intermittent. Under \u00a72618 special rules apply for employees of local educational agencies.</ref> In full, the rights during and after unpaid leave are to:\n* the same group health insurance benefits, including employer contributions to premiums, that would exist if the employee were not on leave.\n* restoration to the same position upon return to work. If the same position is unavailable, the employer must provide the worker with a position that is substantially equal in pay, benefits, and responsibility.\n* protection of employee benefits while on leave. An employee is entitled to reinstatement of all benefits to which the employee was entitled before going on leave.\n* protection of the employee to not have their rights under the Act interfered with or denied by an employer.\n* protection of the employee from retaliation by an employer for exercising rights under the Act.\n* intermittent FMLA leave for their own serious health condition, or the serious health condition of a family member. This includes occasional leave for doctors\u2019 appointments for a chronic condition, treatment (e.g., physical therapy, psychological counseling, chemotherapy), or temporary periods of incapacity (e.g., severe morning sickness, asthma attack).<ref>{{cite news|last=Vedder Price|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/struggling-intermittent-fmla-leave |title=Struggling with Intermittent FMLA Leave |publisher=The National Law Review |date= January 26, 2011|accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref>\n\n\u201cHighly compensated employees\u201d have limited rights to return to their jobs. They are defined as \u201ca salaried eligible employee who is among the highest paid 10 percent of the employees employed by the employer within 75 miles of the facility at which the employee is employed\u201d.<ref name=\"Congress 1993\">Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20138 quoted.</ref> Their employers are not required to restore them to their original position (or an equivalent position with equivalent pay and benefits, as is guaranteed to other employees) if the employer determines that denying the employee their position is \u201cnecessary to prevent substantial and grievous economic injury to the operations of the employer\u201d <ref name=\"Congress 1993\"/> and the employer provides the worker with notice of this decision, though no time frame for providing this notice is established.\n\n===Enforcement===\nEmployees or the [[Secretary of Labor]] can bring enforcement actions,<ref>29 USC \u00a72617, and see ''[[Frizzell v Southwest Motor Freight]]'', 154 F3d 641 (6th Circuit 1998)</ref> but there is no right to a jury for reinstatement claims. Employees can seek damages for lost wages and benefits, or the cost of child care, plus an equal amount of liquidated damages unless an employer can show it acted in good faith and reasonable cause to believe it was not breaking the law.<ref>29 USC \u00a72617(a)(1)(A)(iii)</ref> There is a two-year limit on bringing claims, or three years for willful violations.<ref>See ''[[Moore v Payless Shoe Source]]'' (8th Circuit 1998)</ref>\n\n===Non-eligible workers and types of leave===\nThe federal FMLA does not apply to:\n* workers in businesses with fewer than 50 employees (this threshold does not apply to public agency employers and local educational agencies as they are covered employers by name but there still must be at least 50 employees with a 75-mile radius for the employee to be eligible for FMLA leave<ref name=\"FS28\" />);\n* [[Part-time job|part-time]] workers who have worked fewer than 1,250 hours within the 12 months preceding the leave and a paid vacation;\n* workers who need time off to care for seriously ill elderly relatives (other than parents), unless the relative was acting ''[[in loco parentis]]'' at the time the worker turned 18;<ref name=\":2\">29 U.S.C. \u00a7 2611</ref><ref>''Coutard v. Municipal Credit Union 2017 WL 526060 (2d Cir. Feb. 9, 2017)''</ref>\n* workers who need time off to care for pets;\n* workers who need time off to recover from short-term or common illness like a cold, or to care for a family member with a short-term illness;\n* elected officials; and\n* workers who need time off for routine medical care, such as check-ups.\n\n==State family leave==\nSome states have enacted laws that mandate additional family and medical leave for workers in a variety of ways. By 2016 four states had laws for paid family leave: [[California]] since 2002, [[New Jersey]] since 2008, [[Rhode Island]] since 2013, and [[New York (state)|New York]] since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/research-library/work-family/paid-leave/paid-family-and-medical-leave.pdf|title=Paid Family and Medical Leave: An Overview|last=|first=|date=March 2015|website=|publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families|access-date=May 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ny.gov/programs/paid-family-leave-strong-families-strong-ny|title=Paid Family Leave: Strong Families, Strong NY|date=2016-01-22|website=Welcome to the State of New York|access-date=2016-05-24}}</ref> Washington state passed a paid family and medical leave law in 2007, but the law has not taken effect due to a lack of funding mechanism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/endless-delays-may-doom-paid-family-leave-in-washington-state-f000c1dc2255/|title=Endless Delays May Doom Paid Family Leave In Washington State|website=ThinkProgress|access-date=2016-05-24}}</ref>\n\n===Dropping the employer threshold===\nThe federal FMLA only applies to employers with 50 or more employees, within 75 miles. Some states have enacted their own FMLAs that have a lower threshold for employer coverage:\n* [[Maine]]: 15 or more employees (private employers)<ref>26 Me. Rev. Stat. Ann. tit. 26 \u00a7 *843 (3)(A)</ref> and 25 or more (city or town employers).<ref>26 Me. Rev. Stat. Ann. tit. 26 \u00a7 843 (3)(C)</ref>\n* [[Maryland]]: 15 or more employees (private employers)Up to seven days for bone marrow donation. Up to 30 days for organ donation.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.dbm.maryland.gov/employees/Documents/Leave/fmlabookletAugust2013.pdf |title=FAMILY AND MEDICAL  LEAVE ACT (FMLA) GUIDE |publisher=STATE OF MARYLAND |date=August 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2009rs/bills_noln/sb/tsb0562.pdf |title=SENATE BILL 562 |publisher= |date=February 5, 2009 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[Minnesota]]: 21 or more employees ([[parental leave]] only).<ref>Minn. Stat. \u00a7 181.940 (Subd. 3)</ref>\n* [[Oregon]]: 25 or more employees. An employee must have worked at least 180 days, and averaged 25 hours per week at the time medical leave is requested<ref>Or. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.153 (1)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.employmentlawhq.com/state-requirements/oregon.html|title=Oregon FMLA Laws|website=www.employmentlawhq.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n* [[Rhode Island]]: 50 or more employees (private employers)<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a728-48-1(3)(i)</ref> and 30 or more employees (public employers).<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 28-48-1(3)(iii)</ref>\n* [[Vermont]]: 10 or more employees (parental leave only)<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(4)</ref> and 15 or more employees (family and medical leave).<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(3)</ref>\n* [[Washington (state)|Washington]]: 50 or more employees (FMLA reasons besides insured parental leave);<ref>RCW \u00a7 49.78.020(5)</ref> all employers are required to provide insured parental leave.<ref>RCW \u00a7 49.86.010 (6)(a)</ref><ref>RCW \u00a7 50.50.080(1)</ref>\n* [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]]: 20 or more employees.<ref>D.C. Code \u00a7 32-516(2)</ref>\n\n===Expanded coverage===\nThe federal FMLA only applies to immediate family\u2014parent, spouse, and child. The 2008 amendments to the FMLA for military family members extend the FMLA's protection to next of kin and to adult children. The Department of Labor on June 22, 2010 clarified the definition of \"son and daughter\" under the FMLA \"to ensure that an employee who assumes the role of caring for a child receives parental rights to family leave regardless of the legal or biological  relationship\" and specifying that \"an employee who intends to share in the parenting of a child with their same sex partner will be able to exercise the right to FMLA leave to bond with that child.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=US Department of Labor clarifies FMLA definition of \u2018son and daughter\u2019|url=http://www.dol.gov/opa/media/press/WHD/WHD20100877.htm|accessdate=2010-07-14|newspaper=U.S. Department of Labor|date=2010-06-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626174359/http://www.dol.gov/opa/media/press/WHD/WHD20100877.htm|archive-date=2010-06-26|url-status=dead}}  News Release Number:  10-0877-NAT</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] issued its final rule amending the definition of spouse under the FMLA in response to the decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', effective March 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Forman|first1=Shira|title=DOL Issues Final Rule Amending FMLA Definition of \"Spouse\" to Include Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/dol-issues-final-rule-amending-fmla-definition-spouse-to-include-same-sex-marriages|accessdate=28 February 2015|publisher=Sheppard Mullin Richter & Hampton LLP|date=27 February 2015}}</ref> The revised definition of \"spouse\" extends FMLA leave rights and job protections to eligible employees in a [[same-sex marriage]] or a [[common-law marriage]] entered into in a state where those statuses are legally recognized, regardless of the state in which the employee works or resides.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Trotier|first1=Geoffrey S.|title=FMLA \"Spouse\" Definition Now Includes Same-Sex Spouses and Common-Law Spouses|journal=The National Law Review|date=24 February 2015|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-spouse-definition-now-includes-same-sex-spouses-and-common-law-spouses|accessdate=28 February 2015|publisher=von Briesen & Roper, s.c}}</ref> Even if an employee works where same-sex or common law marriage is not recognized, that employee's spouse triggers FMLA coverage if the employee married in a state that recognized same-sex marriage or common law marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gozdecki|first1=Jeanine M.|title=FMLA Final Rule: \"Spouse\" Means Same-Sex Spouse (Even in Alabama)|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-final-rule-spouse-means-same-sex-spouse-even-alabama|accessdate=28 February 2015|work=The National Law Review|publisher=Barnes & Thornburg LLP|date=25 February 2015}}</ref> Some states had already expanded the definition of family in their own FMLAs:\n* [[California]]: Domestic partner and domestic partner's child.<ref>Cal. Fam. Code \u00a7 297.5</ref>\n* [[Connecticut]]: Civil union partner,<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 46b-38nn</ref> parent-in-law.<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 31-51kk (7)</ref>\n* [[Hawaii]]: Grandparent, parent-in-law, grandparent-in-law<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 398.1</ref> or an employee's reciprocal beneficiary.<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 398.3</ref>\n* Maine: Domestic partner and domestic partner's child,<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(D)</ref> siblings.<ref>LD 2132</ref>\n* [[Maryland]]: Allows the employee to use time for immediate family under the same rules if taking it for themselves. Includes step, adopted and even people who were primary caregivers even if not related.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2009rs/bills_noln/sb/tsb0562.pdf |title=SENATE BILL 562 |publisher= |date=February 5, 2009 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[New Jersey]]: Civil union partner and child of civil union partner,<ref>N.J. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 37:1-31</ref> parent-in-law, step parent.<ref>N.J. Stat Ann. \u00a7 34-11B(3)(h)</ref>\n* Oregon: Domestic partner,<ref>HB 2007</ref> grandparent, grandchild or parent-in-law.<ref>OR. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.150 (4)</ref>\n* Rhode Island: Domestic partners of state employees, parent-in-law.<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 24-48-1(5)</ref>\n* Vermont: Civil union partner,<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 1204(a)</ref> parent-in-law.<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(3)(B)</ref>\n* [[Wisconsin]]: Parent-in-law.<ref>Wis. Stat. \u00a7103.10(1)(f)</ref>\n* District of Columbia: Related to the worker by blood, legal custody, or marriage; person with whom the employee lives and has a committed relationship; child who lives with employee and for whom employee permanently assumes and discharges parental responsibility.<ref>D.C. Code 32-501(A), (B), (C)</ref>\n\n===Increasing the uses for FMLA leave===\nFMLA leave can be used for a worker's serious health condition, the serious health condition of a family member, or upon the arrival of a new child. State FMLA laws and the new military family provisions of the FMLA have broadened these categories:\n* Connecticut: Organ or bone marrow donor.<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 31-51ll (2)(E)</ref>\n* Maine: Organ donor;<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(E)</ref> death of employee's family member if that family member is a servicemember killed while on active duty.<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(F)</ref>\n* Maryland: Maryland Family Leave Act (MFLA) \u2013 Organ donor, Person Standing in Loco Parentis, For Service Leave, and added a specific anti-retaliation penalty on top of FMLA recovery. Runs parallel to FMLA.\n* Oregon: Care for the non-serious injury or illness of a child requiring home care.<ref>OR. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.159 (d)</ref>\n\n===Unpaid leave for other related purposes===\nSeveral states have passed FMLA-type statutes to give parents unpaid leave for other related purposes, including:\n* Attending child's school or educational activities. Examples include California,<ref>Cal. Lab. Code \u00a7 230.8</ref> District of Columbia,<ref>D.C. Code 32-1202</ref> Massachusetts,<ref>Mass. Gen. Laws. Ch. 149 \u00a7 52(D)(b)(1)</ref> Minnesota,<ref>Minn. Stat. \u00a7 181.9412</ref> Rhode Island,<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 24-48-12</ref> Vermont,<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 472a (a)(1)</ref> and others. \n* Taking family members to routine medical visits. Massachusetts<ref>Mass. Gen. Laws. Ch. 149 \u00a7 52(D)(b)(2)&(3)</ref> and Vermont.<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 472a (a)(2)</ref>  \n* Addressing the effects of domestic violence, stalking, or sexual assault. Examples include Colorado,<ref>Colo. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 24-34-402.7</ref> Florida,<ref>FLA. STAT. \u00a7 741.313</ref> Hawaii,<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 378-72</ref> and Illinois.<ref>820 Ill. Comp. Stat. 180/1-180/45</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nIn 2003, Han and Waldfogel found that \u201conly about 60% of private sector workers are covered\u201d <ref>Han, W.-J. and Waldfogel, J. 2003. \"Parental Leave: The Impact of Recent Legislation on Parents' Leave-Taking.\" ''Demography''. 40(1):191\u2013200. p191 quoted.</ref> due to the clause stipulating a minimum number of employees, and once the clause stipulating a minimum number of hours worked is added, only 46% of private sector workers are eligible for leave under the FMLA. In June 2007, the Department of Labor estimated that of 141.7 million workers in the United States, 94.4 million worked at FMLA-covered worksites, and 76.1 million were eligible for FMLA leave. Only eight to 17.1 percent of covered, eligible workers (or between 6.1 million and 13.0 million workers) took FMLA leave in 2005.<ref>\"Family and Medical Leave Act Regulations: A Report on the Department of Labor\u2019s Request for Information.\" 28 June 2007. Department of Labor, Employment Standards Administration, Wage and Hour Division. ''Federal Register'', Vol. 72, No. 124. [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2007-06-28/html/07-3102.htm]</ref> The 2008 National Survey of Employers found no statistically significant difference between the proportion of small employers (79%) and large employers (82%) that offer full FMLA coverage.<ref>Galinsky, E., Bond, J., Sakai, K., Kim, S., Giuntoli, N. 2008. National study of employers. New York, NY: Families and Work Institute. [http://www.familiesandwork.org/site/research/reports/2008nse.pdf]</ref>\n\nAlthough much of the research has been conducted on populations in other countries,<ref>Gregg, P.E., Washbrook et al. 2005. \"The Effects of a Mother's Return to Work Decision on Child Development in the UK.\" ''The Economic Journal''. 115(501):F48-F80.</ref> Berger et al.<ref>Berger, L.M., Hill, et al. 2005. \"Maternity Leave, Early Maternal Employment and Child Health Development in the US.\" ''The Economic Journal''. 115(501):F29-F47.</ref> found that children in the United States whose mothers return to work within the first 3 months after giving birth are less likely to be [[Breastfeeding|breastfed]], have all of their [[immunization]]s up to date (by 18 months), and receive all of their regular medical checkups; they are also more likely to exhibit behavioral problems by four years of age. Chatterji and Markowitz <ref>Chatterji, P. and Markowitz, S. 2005. \"Does the Length of Maternity Leave Affect Mental Health.\" ''Southern Economic Journal''. 72(1):16\u201341.</ref> also found an association between longer lengths of maternity leave and lesser incidence of [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among mothers.\n\nDespite the lack of rights to leave, there is no right to free [[child care]] or [[day care]]. This has encouraged several proposals to create a public system of free child care, or for the government to subsidize parents' costs.<ref>e.g. D Paquette, 'The enormous ambition of Hillary Clinton's child-care plan' (May 12, 2016) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/12/the-enormous-ambition-of-hillary-clintons-child-care-plan/ The Washington Post]</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nCritics of the act have suggested that by mandating various forms of leave that are used more often by female than male employees, the Act, like the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, makes women more expensive to employ than men. They argue that employers will engage in subtle discrimination against women in the hiring process, discrimination which is much less obvious to detect than [[pregnancy discrimination]] against the already hired. Throughout history, gender discrimination towards women was common; certain laws were placed that would restrict a woman's option in choosing a working position, as well as, how many hours she could work<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anthony|first=Deborah J.|year=2008|title=The Hidden Harms of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Gender-Neutral Versus Gender-Equal|url=http://digitalcommons.wcl.american.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1044&context=jgspl|journal=Gender, Social Policy & the Law|volume=16|pages=4|via=Digital Commons}}</ref> ei. Employers  Supporters counter that the act, in contrast to the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, is aimed at both women and men, and is part of an overall strategy to encourage both men and women to take family-related leave.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/topic/benefits-leave/fmla|title=FMLA (Family & Medical Leave)|date=2015-12-09|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=2017-04-05|language=en}}</ref> However, this is based on the assumption that men will take advantage of the opportunity of unpaid leave at comparable rates to women. According to Grossman, there is no basis for this assumption upon the inception of the legislation and no evidence has been found today to support this assumption. Therefore, the employer incentive to prefer male employees is preserved despite the equal opportunity for both sexes to take leave.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grossman|first=Joanna|date=20 April 2004|title=Job Security Without Equality: The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|journal=Journal of Law and Policy|volume=15|issue=17|pages=17\u201363 |url=https://openscholarship.wustl.edu/law_journal_law_policy/vol15/iss1/3}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, the FMLA is much less comprehensive than Western European leave policies. Namely, the United States is the only industrialized country without paid leave for parents. The following table illustrates the lack of provisions offered in the United States as compared to that of other industrialized countries. For instance, all Western European nations have maternity paid leave and over half have paternity and sick child care paid leave, while the United States has no paid leave.<ref name=\"Pyle 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Pyle |first1=Jean L. |last2=Pelletier |first2=Marianne S. |title=Family and medical leave act: unresolved issues |journal=New Solutions |date=1 March 2003 |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=353\u201384 |doi=10.2190/7K3G-MW4M-6J7X-U4EV |pmid=17208739}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Maternity\n!Paternity\n!Sick Child (over 3 years)\n!Sick Spouse/Parent\n!Own Illness\n|-\n|United States\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|-\n|Austria\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Belgium\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Denmark\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Finland\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|France\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Germany\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Greece\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Ireland\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Italy\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Luxembourg\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Netherlands\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Portugal\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Spain\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Sweden\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|United Kingdom\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>{{aye}} = available, {{nay}} = not available, {{steady}}  = not applicable<ref name=\"Pyle 2003\" />\n\nAdditionally, workplace fairness has been questioned under the Act. For instance, any woman-specific benefits provided by the legislation were considered special treatment and thus unacceptable, and ignoring the idea that women may have a greater share of burden of caregiving in reality. In retort, supporters may argue that creating such legislation that recognizes the female's greater role in child care,  stereotype would be reinforced.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Anthony|last2=Deborah|date=2008|title=The Hidden Harms of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Gender Neutral versus Gender Equal|journal=Journal of Gender Social Policy and the Law|volume=16|issue=4}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the implementation of the policy is also controversial because it is questioned whether the policy is actually going to those who need the benefits. For instance, since the leave offered is unpaid, majorities of eligible employees can not take time off because they can not afford to do so.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mory|first=Marc|last2=Pistilli|first2=Lia|date=2001|title=The Failure of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Alternative Proposals for Contemporary American Families|journal=Hofstra Labor and Employment Law Journal|volume=18|issue=2}}</ref> And according to Pyle and Pelletier, eligible workers may not even know about this policy and the benefits allotted to them.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUnder law, women are protected from sex discrimination in the workplace but a large stigma against women still exists in terms of them being equally skilled as their male co-workers, and ultimately testing the federal protection of rights in a work environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.workplacefairness.org/sexual-gender-discrimination#1|title=Sex / Gender Discrimination - Workplace Fairness|last=742-9150|website=Midwest New Media |access-date=2017-04-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405172256/http://www.workplacefairness.org/sexual-gender-discrimination#1|archive-date=2017-04-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Like any other federal regulation, it is strictly prohibited for an employer to discriminate towards an employee (especially if the employee is using their FMLA rights), and to strain from providing accurate information for all employees to access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/fmlaAmended.htm#SEC_105_PROHIBITED_ACTS|title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (WHD) The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993, as amended|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Signing Ceremony==\nVicki Yandle, a receptionist who was fired after asking for a few weeks of time off to care for a daughter with cancer, was on stage with President Clinton when the law was signed.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/04/garden/family-leave-bill-peace-of-mind-issue.html Family-Leave Bill: Peace of Mind Issue] New York Times, 4 February 1993</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States labor law]]\n*''[[Cleveland Board of Education v. LaFleur]]'' (1974)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/index.htm Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993] 29 U.S. Code Chapter 28\n* [http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/benefits-leave/fmla.htm  Department of Labor Family & Medical Leave information pages]\n* [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=103&session=1&vote=00011 Senate roll call vote]\n* [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll022.xml House roll call vote]\n* [https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/search/display.html?terms=nevada&url=/supct/html/01-1368.ZS.html ''Nevada Dept. of Human Resources v. Hibbs'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ebA_lESQas0 Your Rights Under the Federal Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA)]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0118846|title=A Child's Wish}} \u2013 A made-for-TV film about the act in which President Clinton appears briefly as himself.\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20090703173531/http://paidsickdays.nationalpartnership.org/site/PageServer?pagename=ourwork_fmla_FamilyandMedicalLeave\n* http://www.nationalpartnership.org/site/DocServer/WF_PL_FactSheet_PaidFamilyLeave_2009.pdf?docID=4682&autologin=true\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1993 in American law]]\n[[Category:103rd United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Clinton Administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Family law in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of labor relations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Leave]]\n[[Category:United States federal labor legislation]]\n[[Category:1993 in labour relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993\n| fullname = An Act To grant family and temporary medical leave under certain circumstances.\n| acronym = FMLA\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 103rd\n| effective date =\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|103|3}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|107|6}}\n| acts amended =\n| title amended = [[Title 29 of the United States Code|29 USC: Labor]]\n| sections created = [[29 U.S.C.]] sec. 2601\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d103:HR00001:@@@S\n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|103|HR|1}}\n| introducedby = [[William D. Ford]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Michigan|MI]])\n| introduceddate = January 5, 1993\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Education and Labor|House Education and Labor]], [[United States House Committee on Post Office and Civil Service|House Post Office and Civil Service]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = February 3, 1993\n| passedvote1 = [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll022.xml 265\u2013163]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = February 4, 1993\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=103&session=1&vote=00011 71\u201327]\n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = February 4, 1993\n| agreedvote3 = Via {{USBill|103|HRes|71}}, [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll029.xml 247\u2013152]\n| signedpresident = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| signeddate = February 5, 1993\n| amendments = [[No Child Left Behind Act]]\n| SCOTUS cases =\n}}\nThe '''Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993''' ('''FMLA''') is a [[United States labor law]] requiring covered employers to provide employees with job-protected and unpaid leave for qualified medical and family reasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family and Medical Leave Act |first=Stephen |last=Bruce |website=HR Daily Advisor |url=http://hrdailyadvisor.blr.com/archive/category/1011.aspx |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> The FMLA was a major part of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s first-term domestic agenda, and he signed it into law on February 5, 1993. The FMLA is administered by the [[Wage and Hour Division]] of the [[United States Department of Labor]].\n\nThe FMLA allows eligible employees to take up to 12 work weeks of unpaid leave during any 12-month period to care for a new child, care for a seriously ill family member, or recover from a serious illness. The FMLA covers both public- and private-sector employees, but certain categories of employees, including elected officials and highly compensated employees, are excluded from the law or face certain limitations. In order to be eligible for FMLA leave, an employee must have worked for the employer for at least 12 months, have worked at least 1,250 hours over the past 12 months, and work for an employer with at least fifty employees. Several states have passed laws providing additional family and medical leave protections for workers.\n\n==Background==\n\nPrior to the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 presidential election]], a family medical leave act had been vetoed twice by President [[George H. W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilentz|first1=Sean|title=The Age of Reagan|date=2008|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-074480-9|pp=[https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile/page/327 327\u2013328]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile/page/327}}</ref> After [[Bill Clinton]] won the 1992 election, a law protecting family medical leave became one of his major first-term domestic priorities. Rapid growth in the workforce, including a large number of women joining, suggested a necessary federal regulation that would support the working class who desired to raise a family and/or required time off for illness related situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=46777|title=William J. Clinton: Statement on Signing the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> President Clinton signed the bill into law on February 5, 1993 ({{USPL|103|3}}; [[29 U.S.C.]] sec. 2601; 29 [[Code of Federal Regulations|CFR]] 825) to take effect on August 5, 1993.\n\nThe United States Congress passed the Act with the understanding that \u201cit is important for the development of children and the [[family]] unit that fathers and mothers be able to participate in early [[Parenting|childrearing]] \u2026 [and] the lack of employment policies to accommodate working parents can force individuals to choose between job security and parenting\u201d.<ref>Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20132 quoted</ref> It also stressed the Act was intended to provide leave protection for individuals \u201cin a manner that accommodates the legitimate interests of employers\u201d.<ref>Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20132 quoted.</ref>\n\n==Contents==\n[[File:Childcare Development Center-Crestwood High School cheerleaders 120815-F-PG936-400.jpg|thumb|right|Because there is no right to education and [[child care]] for [[Pre-kindergarten|children under five]], the costs of child care fall on parents. But in 2016, four states had legislated for [[paid family leave]].<ref>[[California]], [[New Jersey]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[New York (state)|New York]]</ref>]]\n\n===Scope of rights===\nThe Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 generally applies to employers of 50 or more employees in 20 weeks of the last year. Employees must have worked over 12 months and 1250 hours in the last year (around 25 hours a week). However, employees \"at which such employer employs less than 50 employees if the total number of employees employed by that employer within 75 miles of that worksite is less than 50.\"<ref>29 USC \u00a72611(2)</ref> A worksite includes a public agency, including schools and state, local, and federal employers. The 50 employee threshold does not apply to public agency employees and local educational agencies. There are special hours rules for certain airline employees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Family and Medical Leave Act Airline Flight Crew Technical Amendments|url=http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/airline.htm#.UMkHuIPAdBM}}</ref>\n\nEmployees must give notice of 30 days to employers if birth or adoption is \"foreseeable\",<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(e)</ref> and for serious health conditions if practicable. Treatments should be arranged \"so as not to disrupt unduly the operations of the employer\" according to medical advice.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(e)(2)</ref>\n\nAlong with the 30 day notice, there are also other requirements to be made when seeking the FMLA rights. If an employee wants to leave the first time using ones FMLA rights, the person must first claim the Family and Medical Leave Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opm.gov/policy-data-oversight/pay-leave/leave-administration/fact-sheets/family-and-medical-leave/|title=Family and Medical Leave for Federal Employees|website=U.S. Office of Personnel Management|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> In the case that an employee were to leave again under the FMLA act, the same process must proceed.<ref name=\"FS28\">{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet #28: The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28.pdf |website=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=21 August 2019 |date=2012}}</ref>\n\nWith the release of employees, there is a [[certification]] as well. The absence of an employee due to the conditions he or she may have may require a certification as proof of the verification of absence.<ref name=\"FS28\" /> In order to certify the leave of an employee, the employer may ask for other requirements. An example of these requirements are requiring multiple medical opinions. All of these prerequisites are at the employer's [[expense]]. There are also certain rules that may apply to those who work at local education [[Institution|agencies]].<ref name=\"FS28\" />\n\n===Rights during leave===\nEmployees can have up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave for child birth, adoption, to care for a close relative in poor health, or because of an employee's own poor health.<ref>29 USC \u00a72512(a)(2) and on adoption, see ''[[Kelley v Crosfield Catalysts]]'' 135 F2d 1202 (7th Circuit 1998) The same rules for federal employees were codified in 5 USC \u00a7\u00a76381\u20136387.</ref> In full, the purposes for leave are:\n* to care for a new child, whether for the birth, the adoption, or placement of a child in foster care;\n* to care for a seriously ill family member (spouse, son, daughter, or parent) (Note: Son/daughter has been clarified by the Department of Labor to mean a child under the age of 18 or a child over the age of 18 with a mental or physical disability as defined by the Americans With Disabilities Act, which excludes, among other conditions, pregnancy and post-partum recovery from childbirth);<ref>{{cite news|title=DoL Opinion|url=http://www.dol.gov/WHD/opinion/fmla/prior2002/FMLA-51.htm}}</ref>\n* to recover from a worker's own serious illness;\n* to care for an injured service member in the family; or\n* to address qualifying exigencies arising out of a family member's deployment.\n* twenty-six workweeks of leave during a single 12-month period to care for a covered servicemember with a serious injury or illness if the eligible employee is the servicemember's spouse, son, daughter, parent, or next of kin (military caregiver leave).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/ |title=Family and Medical Leave Act \u2013 Wage and Hour Division (WHD) \u2013 U.S. Department of Labor |publisher=Dol.gov |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n\nChild care leave should be taken in one lump, unless an employer agrees otherwise.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(a)(2)</ref> If a father and mother have the same employer, they must share their leave, in effect halving each person's rights, if the employer so chooses.<ref>29 USC \u00a72612(f) \u201cthe aggregate number of workweeks of leave to which both may be entitled may be limited to 12 workweeks\u201d</ref>\n\nEmployers must provide benefits during the unpaid leave.<ref>29 USC \u00a72614(c). If an employee quits, the employer is enabled to recoup costs.</ref> Under \u00a72652(b) states are empowered to provide \"greater family or medical leave rights\".\n\nSince 2008, the Department of Labor has allowed the spouse, child, or parent of an active duty military member who is deployed overseas for 12 or more months to take up to 12 weeks of leave. Also, a military caregiver provision was added that would allow a caregiver to take up to 26 weeks of leave in order to actively care for a military member who requires medical attention for acute or ongoing conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/MilitaryFLProvisions.htm|title=Military Family Leave Provisions of the FMLA - Wage and Hour Division (WHD) - U.S. Department of Labor|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===Substitute leave===\nUnder \u00a72612(2)(A) an employer can make an employee substitute the right to 12 unpaid weeks of leave for \"accrued paid vacation leave, personal leave or family leave\" in an employer's personnel policy. Originally the Department of Labor had a penalty to make employers notify employees that this might happen. However, five judges in the [[US Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ragsdale v Wolverine World Wide, Inc]]'' held that the statute precluded the right of the Department of Labor to do so. Four dissenting judges would have held that nothing prevented the rule, and it was the Department of Labor's job to enforce the law.<ref>[http://www.worldlii.org/us/cases/federal/USSC/2002/557.html 535 US 81] (2002)</ref>\n\n===Right to return to job===\nAfter unpaid leave, an employee generally has the right to return to their job, except for employees who are in the top 10% of highest paid and the employer can argue refusal \"is necessary to prevent substantial and grievous economic injury to the operations of the employer.\"<ref>29 USC \u00a72614(b). Under 29 USC \u00a72612(b)(2) employers may transfer employees to another position with similar pay and benefits if health absences could be intermittent. Under \u00a72618 special rules apply for employees of local educational agencies.</ref> In full, the rights during and after unpaid leave are to:\n* the same group health insurance benefits, including employer contributions to premiums, that would exist if the employee were not on leave.\n* restoration to the same position upon return to work. If the same position is unavailable, the employer must provide the worker with a position that is substantially equal in pay, benefits, and responsibility.\n* protection of employee benefits while on leave. An employee is entitled to reinstatement of all benefits to which the employee was entitled before going on leave.\n* protection of the employee to not have their rights under the Act interfered with or denied by an employer.\n* protection of the employee from retaliation by an employer for exercising rights under the Act.\n* intermittent FMLA leave for their own serious health condition, or the serious health condition of a family member. This includes occasional leave for doctors\u2019 appointments for a chronic condition, treatment (e.g., physical therapy, psychological counseling, chemotherapy), or temporary periods of incapacity (e.g., severe morning sickness, asthma attack).<ref>{{cite news|last=Vedder Price|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/struggling-intermittent-fmla-leave |title=Struggling with Intermittent FMLA Leave |publisher=The National Law Review |date= January 26, 2011|accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref>\n\n\u201cHighly compensated employees\u201d have limited rights to return to their jobs. They are defined as \u201ca salaried eligible employee who is among the highest paid 10 percent of the employees employed by the employer within 75 miles of the facility at which the employee is employed\u201d.<ref name=\"Congress 1993\">Congress. 1993. Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993. Washington, D.C. pH.R.1\u20138 quoted.</ref> Their employers are not required to restore them to their original position (or an equivalent position with equivalent pay and benefits, as is guaranteed to other employees) if the employer determines that denying the employee their position is \u201cnecessary to prevent substantial and grievous economic injury to the operations of the employer\u201d <ref name=\"Congress 1993\"/> and the employer provides the worker with notice of this decision, though no time frame for providing this notice is established.\n\n===Enforcement===\nEmployees or the [[Secretary of Labor]] can bring enforcement actions,<ref>29 USC \u00a72617, and see ''[[Frizzell v Southwest Motor Freight]]'', 154 F3d 641 (6th Circuit 1998)</ref> but there is no right to a jury for reinstatement claims. Employees can seek damages for lost wages and benefits, or the cost of child care, plus an equal amount of liquidated damages unless an employer can show it acted in good faith and reasonable cause to believe it was not breaking the law.<ref>29 USC \u00a72617(a)(1)(A)(iii)</ref> There is a two-year limit on bringing claims, or three years for willful violations.<ref>See ''[[Moore v Payless Shoe Source]]'' (8th Circuit 1998)</ref>\n\n===Non-eligible workers and types of leave===\nThe federal FMLA does not apply to:\n* workers in businesses with fewer than 50 employees (this threshold does not apply to public agency employers and local educational agencies as they are covered employers by name but there still must be at least 50 employees with a 75-mile radius for the employee to be eligible for FMLA leave<ref name=\"FS28\" />);\n* [[Part-time job|part-time]] workers who have worked fewer than 1,250 hours within the 12 months preceding the leave and a paid vacation;\n* workers who need time off to care for seriously ill elderly relatives (other than parents), unless the relative was acting ''[[in loco parentis]]'' at the time the worker turned 18;<ref name=\":2\">29 U.S.C. \u00a7 2611</ref><ref>''Coutard v. Municipal Credit Union 2017 WL 526060 (2d Cir. Feb. 9, 2017)''</ref>\n* workers who need time off to care for pets;\n* workers who need time off to recover from short-term or common illness like a cold, or to care for a family member with a short-term illness;\n* elected officials; and\n* workers who need time off for routine medical care, such as check-ups.\n\n==State family leave==\nSome states have enacted laws that mandate additional family and medical leave for workers in a variety of ways. By 2016 four states had laws for paid family leave: [[California]] since 2002, [[New Jersey]] since 2008, [[Rhode Island]] since 2013, and [[New York (state)|New York]] since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/research-library/work-family/paid-leave/paid-family-and-medical-leave.pdf|title=Paid Family and Medical Leave: An Overview|last=|first=|date=March 2015|website=|publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families|access-date=May 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ny.gov/programs/paid-family-leave-strong-families-strong-ny|title=Paid Family Leave: Strong Families, Strong NY|date=2016-01-22|website=Welcome to the State of New York|access-date=2016-05-24}}</ref> Washington state passed a paid family and medical leave law in 2007, but the law has not taken effect due to a lack of funding mechanism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2013/07/26/2360341/washington-paid-family-leave/|title=Endless Delays May Doom Paid Family Leave In Washington State|website=ThinkProgress|access-date=2016-05-24}}</ref>\n\n===Dropping the employer threshold===\nThe federal FMLA only applies to employers with 50 or more employees, within 75 miles. Some states have enacted their own FMLAs that have a lower threshold for employer coverage:\n* [[Maine]]: 15 or more employees (private employers)<ref>26 Me. Rev. Stat. Ann. tit. 26 \u00a7 *843 (3)(A)</ref> and 25 or more (city or town employers).<ref>26 Me. Rev. Stat. Ann. tit. 26 \u00a7 843 (3)(C)</ref>\n* [[Maryland]]: 15 or more employees (private employers)Up to seven days for bone marrow donation. Up to 30 days for organ donation.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.dbm.maryland.gov/employees/Documents/Leave/fmlabookletAugust2013.pdf |title=FAMILY AND MEDICAL  LEAVE ACT (FMLA) GUIDE |publisher=STATE OF MARYLAND |date=August 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2009rs/bills_noln/sb/tsb0562.pdf |title=SENATE BILL 562 |publisher= |date=February 5, 2009 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[Minnesota]]: 21 or more employees ([[parental leave]] only).<ref>Minn. Stat. \u00a7 181.940 (Subd. 3)</ref>\n* [[Oregon]]: 25 or more employees. An employee must have worked at least 180 days, and averaged 25 hours per week at the time medical leave is requested<ref>Or. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.153 (1)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.employmentlawhq.com/state-requirements/oregon.html|title=Oregon FMLA Laws|website=www.employmentlawhq.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n* [[Rhode Island]]: 50 or more employees (private employers)<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a728-48-1(3)(i)</ref> and 30 or more employees (public employers).<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 28-48-1(3)(iii)</ref>\n* [[Vermont]]: 10 or more employees (parental leave only)<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(4)</ref> and 15 or more employees (family and medical leave).<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(3)</ref>\n* [[Washington (state)|Washington]]: 50 or more employees (FMLA reasons besides insured parental leave);<ref>RCW \u00a7 49.78.020(5)</ref> all employers are required to provide insured parental leave.<ref>RCW \u00a7 49.86.010 (6)(a)</ref><ref>RCW \u00a7 50.50.080(1)</ref>\n* [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]]: 20 or more employees.<ref>D.C. Code \u00a7 32-516(2)</ref>\n\n===Expanded coverage===\nThe federal FMLA only applies to immediate family\u2014parent, spouse, and child. The 2008 amendments to the FMLA for military family members extend the FMLA's protection to next of kin and to adult children. The Department of Labor on June 22, 2010 clarified the definition of \"son and daughter\" under the FMLA \"to ensure that an employee who assumes the role of caring for a child receives parental rights to family leave regardless of the legal or biological  relationship\" and specifying that \"an employee who intends to share in the parenting of a child with their same sex partner will be able to exercise the right to FMLA leave to bond with that child.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=US Department of Labor clarifies FMLA definition of \u2018son and daughter\u2019|url=http://www.dol.gov/opa/media/press/WHD/WHD20100877.htm|accessdate=2010-07-14|newspaper=U.S. Department of Labor|date=2010-06-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626174359/http://www.dol.gov/opa/media/press/WHD/WHD20100877.htm|archive-date=2010-06-26|url-status=dead}}  News Release Number:  10-0877-NAT</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] issued its final rule amending the definition of spouse under the FMLA in response to the decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', effective March 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Forman|first1=Shira|title=DOL Issues Final Rule Amending FMLA Definition of \"Spouse\" to Include Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/dol-issues-final-rule-amending-fmla-definition-spouse-to-include-same-sex-marriages|accessdate=28 February 2015|publisher=Sheppard Mullin Richter & Hampton LLP|date=27 February 2015}}</ref> The revised definition of \"spouse\" extends FMLA leave rights and job protections to eligible employees in a [[same-sex marriage]] or a [[common-law marriage]] entered into in a state where those statuses are legally recognized, regardless of the state in which the employee works or resides.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Trotier|first1=Geoffrey S.|title=FMLA \"Spouse\" Definition Now Includes Same-Sex Spouses and Common-Law Spouses|journal=The National Law Review|date=24 February 2015|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-spouse-definition-now-includes-same-sex-spouses-and-common-law-spouses|accessdate=28 February 2015|publisher=von Briesen & Roper, s.c}}</ref> Even if an employee works where same-sex or common law marriage is not recognized, that employee's spouse triggers FMLA coverage if the employee married in a state that recognized same-sex marriage or common law marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gozdecki|first1=Jeanine M.|title=FMLA Final Rule: \"Spouse\" Means Same-Sex Spouse (Even in Alabama)|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-final-rule-spouse-means-same-sex-spouse-even-alabama|accessdate=28 February 2015|work=The National Law Review|publisher=Barnes & Thornburg LLP|date=25 February 2015}}</ref> Some states had already expanded the definition of family in their own FMLAs:\n* [[California]]: Domestic partner and domestic partner's child.<ref>Cal. Fam. Code \u00a7 297.5</ref>\n* [[Connecticut]]: Civil union partner,<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 46b-38nn</ref> parent-in-law.<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 31-51kk (7)</ref>\n* [[Hawaii]]: Grandparent, parent-in-law, grandparent-in-law<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 398.1</ref> or an employee's reciprocal beneficiary.<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 398.3</ref>\n* Maine: Domestic partner and domestic partner's child,<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(D)</ref> siblings.<ref>LD 2132</ref>\n* [[Maryland]]: Allows the employee to use time for immediate family under the same rules if taking it for themselves. Includes step, adopted and even people who were primary caregivers even if not related.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2009rs/bills_noln/sb/tsb0562.pdf |title=SENATE BILL 562 |publisher= |date=February 5, 2009 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[New Jersey]]: Civil union partner and child of civil union partner,<ref>N.J. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 37:1-31</ref> parent-in-law, step parent.<ref>N.J. Stat Ann. \u00a7 34-11B(3)(h)</ref>\n* Oregon: Domestic partner,<ref>HB 2007</ref> grandparent, grandchild or parent-in-law.<ref>OR. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.150 (4)</ref>\n* Rhode Island: Domestic partners of state employees, parent-in-law.<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 24-48-1(5)</ref>\n* Vermont: Civil union partner,<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 1204(a)</ref> parent-in-law.<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 471(3)(B)</ref>\n* [[Wisconsin]]: Parent-in-law.<ref>Wis. Stat. \u00a7103.10(1)(f)</ref>\n* District of Columbia: Related to the worker by blood, legal custody, or marriage; person with whom the employee lives and has a committed relationship; child who lives with employee and for whom employee permanently assumes and discharges parental responsibility.<ref>D.C. Code 32-501(A), (B), (C)</ref>\n\n===Increasing the uses for FMLA leave===\nFMLA leave can be used for a worker's serious health condition, the serious health condition of a family member, or upon the arrival of a new child. State FMLA laws and the new military family provisions of the FMLA have broadened these categories:\n* Connecticut: Organ or bone marrow donor.<ref>Conn. Gen. Stat. \u00a7 31-51ll (2)(E)</ref>\n* Maine: Organ donor;<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(E)</ref> death of employee's family member if that family member is a servicemember killed while on active duty.<ref>26 ME. Rev. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 843 (4)(F)</ref>\n* Maryland: Maryland Family Leave Act (MFLA) \u2013 Organ donor, Person Standing in Loco Parentis, For Service Leave, and added a specific anti-retaliation penalty on top of FMLA recovery. Runs parallel to FMLA.\n* Oregon: Care for the non-serious injury or illness of a child requiring home care.<ref>OR. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 659A.159 (d)</ref>\n\n===Unpaid leave for other related purposes===\nSeveral states have passed FMLA-type statutes to give parents unpaid leave for other related purposes, including:\n* Attending child's school or educational activities. Examples include California,<ref>Cal. Lab. Code \u00a7 230.8</ref> District of Columbia,<ref>D.C. Code 32-1202</ref> Massachusetts,<ref>Mass. Gen. Laws. Ch. 149 \u00a7 52(D)(b)(1)</ref> Minnesota,<ref>Minn. Stat. \u00a7 181.9412</ref> Rhode Island,<ref>R.I. Pub. Laws \u00a7 24-48-12</ref> Vermont,<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 472a (a)(1)</ref> and others. \n* Taking family members to routine medical visits. Massachusetts<ref>Mass. Gen. Laws. Ch. 149 \u00a7 52(D)(b)(2)&(3)</ref> and Vermont.<ref>23 VSA \u00a7 472a (a)(2)</ref>  \n* Addressing the effects of domestic violence, stalking, or sexual assault. Examples include Colorado,<ref>Colo. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 24-34-402.7</ref> Florida,<ref>FLA. STAT. \u00a7 741.313</ref> Hawaii,<ref>Haw. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 378-72</ref> and Illinois.<ref>820 Ill. Comp. Stat. 180/1-180/45</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nIn 2003, Han and Waldfogel found that \u201conly about 60% of private sector workers are covered\u201d <ref>Han, W.-J. and Waldfogel, J. 2003. \"Parental Leave: The Impact of Recent Legislation on Parents' Leave-Taking.\" ''Demography''. 40(1):191\u2013200. p191 quoted.</ref> due to the clause stipulating a minimum number of employees, and once the clause stipulating a minimum number of hours worked is added, only 46% of private sector workers are eligible for leave under the FMLA. In June 2007, the Department of Labor estimated that of 141.7 million workers in the United States, 94.4 million worked at FMLA-covered worksites, and 76.1 million were eligible for FMLA leave. Only eight to 17.1 percent of covered, eligible workers (or between 6.1 million and 13.0 million workers) took FMLA leave in 2005.<ref>\"Family and Medical Leave Act Regulations: A Report on the Department of Labor\u2019s Request for Information.\" 28 June 2007. Department of Labor, Employment Standards Administration, Wage and Hour Division. ''Federal Register'', Vol. 72, No. 124. [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2007-06-28/html/07-3102.htm]</ref> The 2008 National Survey of Employers found no statistically significant difference between the proportion of small employers (79%) and large employers (82%) that offer full FMLA coverage.<ref>Galinsky, E., Bond, J., Sakai, K., Kim, S., Giuntoli, N. 2008. National study of employers. New York, NY: Families and Work Institute. [http://www.familiesandwork.org/site/research/reports/2008nse.pdf]</ref>\n\nAlthough much of the research has been conducted on populations in other countries,<ref>Gregg, P.E., Washbrook et al. 2005. \"The Effects of a Mother's Return to Work Decision on Child Development in the UK.\" ''The Economic Journal''. 115(501):F48-F80.</ref> Berger et al.<ref>Berger, L.M., Hill, et al. 2005. \"Maternity Leave, Early Maternal Employment and Child Health Development in the US.\" ''The Economic Journal''. 115(501):F29-F47.</ref> found that children in the United States whose mothers return to work within the first 3 months after giving birth are less likely to be [[Breastfeeding|breastfed]], have all of their [[immunization]]s up to date (by 18 months), and receive all of their regular medical checkups; they are also more likely to exhibit behavioral problems by four years of age. Chatterji and Markowitz <ref>Chatterji, P. and Markowitz, S. 2005. \"Does the Length of Maternity Leave Affect Mental Health.\" ''Southern Economic Journal''. 72(1):16\u201341.</ref> also found an association between longer lengths of maternity leave and lesser incidence of [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among mothers.\n\nDespite the lack of rights to leave, there is no right to free [[child care]] or [[day care]]. This has encouraged several proposals to create a public system of free child care, or for the government to subsidize parents' costs.<ref>e.g. D Paquette, 'The enormous ambition of Hillary Clinton's child-care plan' (May 12, 2016) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/12/the-enormous-ambition-of-hillary-clintons-child-care-plan/ The Washington Post]</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nCritics of the act have suggested that by mandating various forms of leave that are used more often by female than male employees, the Act, like the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, makes women more expensive to employ than men. They argue that employers will engage in subtle discrimination against women in the hiring process, discrimination which is much less obvious to detect than [[pregnancy discrimination]] against the already hired. Throughout history, gender discrimination towards women was common; certain laws were placed that would restrict a woman's option in choosing a working position, as well as, how many hours she could work<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anthony|first=Deborah J.|year=2008|title=The Hidden Harms of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Gender-Neutral Versus Gender-Equal|url=http://digitalcommons.wcl.american.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1044&context=jgspl|journal=Gender, Social Policy & the Law|volume=16|pages=4|via=Digital Commons}}</ref> ei. Employers  Supporters counter that the act, in contrast to the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, is aimed at both women and men, and is part of an overall strategy to encourage both men and women to take family-related leave.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/topic/benefits-leave/fmla|title=FMLA (Family & Medical Leave)|date=2015-12-09|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=2017-04-05|language=en}}</ref> However, this is based on the assumption that men will take advantage of the opportunity of unpaid leave at comparable rates to women. According to Grossman, there is no basis for this assumption upon the inception of the legislation and no evidence has been found today to support this assumption. Therefore, the employer incentive to prefer male employees is preserved despite the equal opportunity for both sexes to take leave.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grossman|first=Joanna|date=20 April 2004|title=Job Security Without Equality: The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|journal=Journal of Law and Policy|volume=15|issue=17|pages=17\u201363 |url=https://openscholarship.wustl.edu/law_journal_law_policy/vol15/iss1/3}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, the FMLA is much less comprehensive than Western European leave policies. Namely, the United States is the only industrialized country without paid leave for parents. The following table illustrates the lack of provisions offered in the United States as compared to that of other industrialized countries. For instance, all Western European nations have maternity paid leave and over half have paternity and sick child care paid leave, while the United States has no paid leave.<ref name=\"Pyle 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Pyle |first1=Jean L. |last2=Pelletier |first2=Marianne S. |title=Family and medical leave act: unresolved issues |journal=New Solutions |date=1 March 2003 |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=353\u201384 |doi=10.2190/7K3G-MW4M-6J7X-U4EV |pmid=17208739}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Maternity\n!Paternity\n!Sick Child (over 3 years)\n!Sick Spouse/Parent\n!Own Illness\n|-\n|United States\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|-\n|Austria\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Belgium\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Denmark\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Finland\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|France\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Germany\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Greece\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Ireland\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Italy\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Luxembourg\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Netherlands\n|{{ya}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{na}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Portugal\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{CNone|{{steady}}}} \n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Spain\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|Sweden\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|United Kingdom\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>{{aye}} = available, {{nay}} = not available, {{steady}}  = not applicable<ref name=\"Pyle 2003\" />\n\nAdditionally, workplace fairness has been questioned under the Act. For instance, any woman-specific benefits provided by the legislation were considered special treatment and thus unacceptable, and ignoring the idea that women may have a greater share of burden of caregiving in reality. In retort, supporters may argue that creating such legislation that recognizes the female's greater role in child care,  stereotype would be reinforced.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Anthony|last2=Deborah|date=2008|title=The Hidden Harms of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Gender Neutral versus Gender Equal|journal=Journal of Gender Social Policy and the Law|volume=16|issue=4}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the implementation of the policy is also controversial because it is questioned whether the policy is actually going to those who need the benefits. For instance, since the leave offered is unpaid, majorities of eligible employees can not take time off because they can not afford to do so.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mory|first=Marc|last2=Pistilli|first2=Lia|date=2001|title=The Failure of the Family and Medical Leave Act: Alternative Proposals for Contemporary American Families|journal=Hofstra Labor and Employment Law Journal|volume=18|issue=2}}</ref> And according to Pyle and Pelletier, eligible workers may not even know about this policy and the benefits allotted to them.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUnder law, women are protected from sex discrimination in the workplace but a large stigma against women still exists in terms of them being equally skilled as their male co-workers, and ultimately testing the federal protection of rights in a work environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.workplacefairness.org/sexual-gender-discrimination#1|title=Sex / Gender Discrimination - Workplace Fairness|last=742-9150|website=Midwest New Media |access-date=2017-04-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405172256/http://www.workplacefairness.org/sexual-gender-discrimination#1|archive-date=2017-04-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Like any other federal regulation, it is strictly prohibited for an employer to discriminate towards an employee (especially if the employee is using their FMLA rights), and to strain from providing accurate information for all employees to access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/fmlaAmended.htm#SEC_105_PROHIBITED_ACTS|title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (WHD) The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993, as amended|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Signing Ceremony==\nVicki Yandle, a receptionist who was fired after asking for a few weeks of time off to care for a daughter with cancer, was on stage with President Clinton when the law was signed.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/04/garden/family-leave-bill-peace-of-mind-issue.html Family-Leave Bill: Peace of Mind Issue] New York Times, 4 February 1993</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States labor law]]\n*''[[Cleveland Board of Education v. LaFleur]]'' (1974)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/index.htm Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993] 29 U.S. Code Chapter 28\n* [http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/benefits-leave/fmla.htm  Department of Labor Family & Medical Leave information pages]\n* [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=103&session=1&vote=00011 Senate roll call vote]\n* [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/1993/roll022.xml House roll call vote]\n* [https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/search/display.html?terms=nevada&url=/supct/html/01-1368.ZS.html ''Nevada Dept. of Human Resources v. Hibbs'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ebA_lESQas0 Your Rights Under the Federal Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA)]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0118846|title=A Child's Wish}} \u2013 A made-for-TV film about the act in which President Clinton appears briefly as himself.\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20090703173531/http://paidsickdays.nationalpartnership.org/site/PageServer?pagename=ourwork_fmla_FamilyandMedicalLeave\n* http://www.nationalpartnership.org/site/DocServer/WF_PL_FactSheet_PaidFamilyLeave_2009.pdf?docID=4682&autologin=true\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1993 in American law]]\n[[Category:103rd United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Clinton Administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Family law in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of labor relations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Leave]]\n[[Category:United States federal labor legislation]]\n[[Category:1993 in labour relations]]\n", "name_user": "Meonkeys", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eState family leave:fix link to WA family leave doom article on thinkprogress.org (previous returned HTTP 403)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_and_Medical_Leave_Act_of_1993"}
{"title_page": "Larry Merchant", "text_new": "{{Active editnotice}} <!-- See [[Wikipedia:Editnotice]] -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Larry Merchant\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| birthname   =\n|birth_name=Larry Kaufman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1931|2|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = Television [[journalist]] Boxing Commentator \n| alias       =\n| title       =\n| family      =\n| spouse      = [[Patricia Stich]] (former actress)\n| children    = two daughters, three step-sons\n| relatives   =\n| ethnicity      =\n| religion    =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| credits     = ''[[HBO World Championship Boxing]]'' Commentator (1978\u20132012)\n| agent       =\n}}\n'''Larry Merchant'''  (born '''Larry Kaufman'''; February 11, 1931) is an American [[sportswriter]], a longtime commentator for [[HBO]] Sports presentations of ''[[HBO World Championship Boxing]]'', ''[[Boxing After Dark]]'' and HBO [[pay-per-view]] telecasts, called \"the greatest television boxing analyst of all time\" by some, including [[ESPN]] Boxing analyst [[Dan Rafael]], <ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3859108&name=rafael_dan |title=More Merchant for boxing fans - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-18}}</ref> and derided as out of touch, biased and incoherent by others.<ref> https://www.mmamania.com/2011/9/22/2442047/dana-white-larry-merchant-is-senile-out-of-his-mind-and-an</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMerchant was born in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Brooklyn]], on February 11, 1931. After graduating from the University of Oklahoma, Merchant was interested in entering professional sports broadcasting. However due to the fear of antisemitism within the industry possibly halting any chances he had of succeeding, Merchant changed his legal surname \"Kaufman\" to its literal translation \"Merchant\".<ref>http://www.statesman.com/news/sports/hbos-merchant-back-in-his-ou-days-wouldve-taken--1/nRfgM/</ref>  In 1978, Merchant joined HBO Sports as an analyst. Prior to joining HBO Sports, Merchant was a well-regarded sports columnist with the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'' and a general reporter for the ''[[New York Post]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMerchant was part of the ''[[HBO Boxing]]'' commentary team along with [[Barry Tompkins]], [[Jim Lampley]], [[Max Kellerman]], [[Gil Clancy]], [[Sugar Ray Leonard]], [[George Foreman]], [[Roy Jones Jr.]], [[ Emanuel Steward]], and [[Harold Lederman]] for championship and pay-per-view fights. \n\nAmong the fighters who have clashed with Merchant include [[Mike Tyson]], [[Oscar De La Hoya]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr]].  The De La Hoya incident came during his fight with [[Pernell Whitaker]]. When De la Hoya entered the ring to [[Mariachi]] music, Merchant stated that while he loved [[Mariachi]] music, he felt that it \"stunk\" in this particular situation.  Merchant would later apologize on the air after De La Hoya tried to have him removed from HBO.\n\nMerchant is well known for his post fight interviews which feature his hard-hitting, blunt questions and confrontational interview style.  These have drawn both praise and ire in the past. Fans have claimed them to be candid and honest while detractors consider them to be purposely biased or agitating and insensitive at times. An example of this occurred when [[Vernon Forrest]] won a controversial decision in 2006 over [[Ike Quartey]].  When Forrest thanked those close to him, Merchant quipped, \"Would you also like to thank the judges?\"\n\nIn 1985, Merchant received the [[Sam Taub Award]] for Boxing Broadcast Journalism presented by the Boxing Writers Association of America. He is also the author of three books. He is a graduate of the University of Oklahoma.\n\nIn October 2002, he was inducted into the [[World Boxing Hall of Fame]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]]. He was inducted in the [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]] in 2009.\n\nOn January 23, 2009, HBO picked up Merchant's two-year option at the end of his 2007 contract. Merchant continued to alternate \"World Championship Boxing\" telecasts and HBO PPV cards with Kellerman.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn September 2011, following the controversial ending to the fight between [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs Victor Ortiz|Floyd Mayweather Jr. and Victor Ortiz]], Mayweather angrily called for Merchant to be fired. After Merchant pressured Mayweather to respond to fans who thought that he had taken advantage of Ortiz's apology (resulting in his win by knockout), Mayweather grew irritated by Merchant's questioning and interrupted Merchant by saying \"You never give me a fair shake...They can put somebody else up here to give me an interview. HBO need to fire you. You don't know shit about boxing. You ain't shit...All of these boxing experts\u2014how can you be a boxing expert if you never had a fight before?\"<ref name=\"floyd-defends\"/> [[Floyd Mayweather, Jr.]]'s outburst led to Merchant responding: \"I wish I was 50 years younger and I would kick your ass.\" <ref name=\"floyd-defends\">{{Cite news |date=18 September 2011|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/14966167.stm|title=Floyd Mayweather defends outburst at veteran broadcaster|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> Later Mayweather defended his outburst by saying that \"Everybody is tired of Larry Merchant.\" <ref name=\"floyd-defends\"/> Merchant also engaged in a controversial exchange with Hall of Fame boxer [[Bernard Hopkins]]<ref>http://ringobserver.com/2016/07/10/flashback-bernard-hopkins-at-his-verbal-best/</ref> after his win over Morrade Hakkar on HBO, declaring that Hopkins was paid for doing little to no work. With his daughter in his arms, Hopkins replied, \"Let me tell you something Larry, you get paid everyday on TV for not doing much.\"\n\n[[Dana White]] drew allegories between MMA commentator staff and stated negative opinions on Merchant,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fbankyonkh0</ref> \n\nDuring Merchant's interview immediately following the [[Floyd Mayweather vs. Miguel Cotto|bout]] between [[Floyd Mayweather, Jr.]] and [[Miguel Cotto]] (May 5, 2012), Merchant acknowledged that Mayweather had apologized the night before the bout and he had accepted the apology.\n\nIt was announced by HBO on December 13, 2012, that Larry Merchant would retire from broadcasting after the December 15, 2012, telecast of HBO's World Championship Boxing from Houston, Texas after 35 years of being a boxing commentator on HBO.\n\nSince leaving HBO Merchant has provided commentary for the international English language feed of some [[Top Rank]] promoted boxing shows.\n\n==Writing==\n*''[[The National Football Lottery]]'' (1973)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/boxing/people/larry-merchant/ HBO Biography]\n*[http://www.secondsout.com/usa/colhauser.cfm?ccs=208&cs=18650 Article on Merchant by Tom Hauser]\n*[http://www.doghouseboxing.com/DHB/Cassell012409.htm Interview w/ Merchant on Doghouse Boxing]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merchant, Larry}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:American sportswriters]]\n[[Category:Boxing commentators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Active editnotice}} <!-- See [[Wikipedia:Editnotice]] -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Larry Merchant\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| birthname   =\n|birth_name=Larry Kaufman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1931|2|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = Television [[journalist]] Boxing Commentator \n| alias       =\n| title       =\n| family      =\n| spouse      = [[Patricia Stich]] (former actress)\n| children    = two daughters, three step-sons\n| relatives   =\n| ethnicity      =\n| religion    =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| credits     = ''[[HBO World Championship Boxing]]'' Commentator (1978\u20132012)\n| agent       =\n}}\n'''Larry Merchant'''  (born '''Larry Kaufman'''; February 11, 1931) is an American former [[sportswriter]], a longtime commentator for [[HBO]] Sports presentations of ''[[HBO World Championship Boxing]]'', ''[[Boxing After Dark]]'' and HBO [[pay-per-view]] telecasts, called \"the greatest television boxing analyst of all time\" by some, including [[ESPN]] Boxing analyst [[Dan Rafael]], <ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3859108&name=rafael_dan |title=More Merchant for boxing fans - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-18}}</ref> and derided as out of touch, biased and incoherent by others.<ref> https://www.mmamania.com/2011/9/22/2442047/dana-white-larry-merchant-is-senile-out-of-his-mind-and-an</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMerchant was born in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Brooklyn]], on February 11, 1931. After graduating from the University of Oklahoma, Merchant was interested in entering professional sports broadcasting. However due to the fear of antisemitism within the industry possibly halting any chances he had of succeeding, Merchant changed his legal surname \"Kaufman\" to its literal translation \"Merchant\".<ref>http://www.statesman.com/news/sports/hbos-merchant-back-in-his-ou-days-wouldve-taken--1/nRfgM/</ref>  In 1978, Merchant joined HBO Sports as an analyst. Prior to joining HBO Sports, Merchant was a well-regarded sports columnist with the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'' and a general reporter for the ''[[New York Post]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMerchant was part of the ''[[HBO Boxing]]'' commentary team along with [[Barry Tompkins]], [[Jim Lampley]], [[Max Kellerman]], [[Gil Clancy]], [[Sugar Ray Leonard]], [[George Foreman]], [[Roy Jones Jr.]], [[ Emanuel Steward]], and [[Harold Lederman]] for championship and pay-per-view fights. \n\nAmong the fighters who have clashed with Merchant include [[Mike Tyson]], [[Oscar De La Hoya]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr]].  The De La Hoya incident came during his fight with [[Pernell Whitaker]]. When De la Hoya entered the ring to [[Mariachi]] music, Merchant stated that while he loved [[Mariachi]] music, he felt that it \"stunk\" in this particular situation.  Merchant would later apologize on the air after De La Hoya tried to have him removed from HBO.\n\nMerchant is well known for his post fight interviews which feature his hard-hitting, blunt questions and confrontational interview style.  These have drawn both praise and ire in the past. Fans have claimed them to be candid and honest while detractors consider them to be purposely biased or agitating and insensitive at times. An example of this occurred when [[Vernon Forrest]] won a controversial decision in 2006 over [[Ike Quartey]].  When Forrest thanked those close to him, Merchant quipped, \"Would you also like to thank the judges?\"\n\nIn 1985, Merchant received the [[Sam Taub Award]] for Boxing Broadcast Journalism presented by the Boxing Writers Association of America. He is also the author of three books. He is a graduate of the University of Oklahoma.\n\nIn October 2002, he was inducted into the [[World Boxing Hall of Fame]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]]. He was inducted in the [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]] in 2009.\n\nOn January 23, 2009, HBO picked up Merchant's two-year option at the end of his 2007 contract. Merchant continued to alternate \"World Championship Boxing\" telecasts and HBO PPV cards with Kellerman.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn September 2011, following the controversial ending to the fight between [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs Victor Ortiz|Floyd Mayweather Jr. and Victor Ortiz]], Mayweather angrily called for Merchant to be fired. After Merchant pressured Mayweather to respond to fans who thought that he had taken advantage of Ortiz's apology (resulting in his win by knockout), Mayweather grew irritated by Merchant's questioning and interrupted Merchant by saying \"You never give me a fair shake...They can put somebody else up here to give me an interview. HBO need to fire you. You don't know shit about boxing. You ain't shit...All of these boxing experts\u2014how can you be a boxing expert if you never had a fight before?\"<ref name=\"floyd-defends\"/> [[Floyd Mayweather, Jr.]]'s outburst led to Merchant responding: \"I wish I was 50 years younger and I would kick your ass.\" <ref name=\"floyd-defends\">{{Cite news |date=18 September 2011|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/14966167.stm|title=Floyd Mayweather defends outburst at veteran broadcaster|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> Later Mayweather defended his outburst by saying that \"Everybody is tired of Larry Merchant.\" <ref name=\"floyd-defends\"/> Merchant also engaged in a controversial exchange with Hall of Fame boxer [[Bernard Hopkins]]<ref>http://ringobserver.com/2016/07/10/flashback-bernard-hopkins-at-his-verbal-best/</ref> after his win over Morrade Hakkar on HBO, declaring that Hopkins was paid for doing little to no work. With his daughter in his arms, Hopkins replied, \"Let me tell you something Larry, you get paid everyday on TV for not doing much.\"\n\n[[Dana White]] drew allegories between MMA commentator staff and stated negative opinions on Merchant,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fbankyonkh0</ref> \n\nDuring Merchant's interview immediately following the [[Floyd Mayweather vs. Miguel Cotto|bout]] between [[Floyd Mayweather, Jr.]] and [[Miguel Cotto]] (May 5, 2012), Merchant acknowledged that Mayweather had apologized the night before the bout and he had accepted the apology.\n\nIt was announced by HBO on December 13, 2012, that Larry Merchant would retire from broadcasting after the December 15, 2012, telecast of HBO's World Championship Boxing from Houston, Texas after 35 years of being a boxing commentator on HBO.\n\nSince leaving HBO Merchant has provided commentary for the international English language feed of some [[Top Rank]] promoted boxing shows.\n\n==Writing==\n*''[[The National Football Lottery]]'' (1973)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/boxing/people/larry-merchant/ HBO Biography]\n*[http://www.secondsout.com/usa/colhauser.cfm?ccs=208&cs=18650 Article on Merchant by Tom Hauser]\n*[http://www.doghouseboxing.com/DHB/Cassell012409.htm Interview w/ Merchant on Doghouse Boxing]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merchant, Larry}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:American sportswriters]]\n[[Category:Boxing commentators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Genarians", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_Merchant"}
{"title_page": "2010 Buffalo Bills season", "text_new": "{{short description|51st season in franchise history}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL season\n| logo =\n| team = Buffalo Bills\n| year = 2010\n| record = 4\u201312 <!-- Do not add zero ties -->\n| division_place = 4th [[AFC East]]\n| coach = [[Chan Gailey]]\n| general manager = [[Buddy Nix]]\n| owner = [[Ralph Wilson]]\n| stadium = [[Ralph Wilson Stadium]]<br />[[Rogers Centre]] (Week 9)\n| playoffs = ''Did not qualify ''\n| pro bowlers = DT [[Kyle Williams (defensive tackle)|Kyle Williams]] \n| uniform =\n| shortnavlink    = Bills seasons\n}}\nThe [[2010 NFL season|2010 season]] was the [[Buffalo Bills]]'  51st season in the [[National Football League]], It was Buffalo's first season with [[Buddy Nix]] in the role of general manager and head coach [[Chan Gailey]]. The Bills hoped to improve on their 6\u201310 record from the [[2009 Buffalo Bills season|2009]] season, and attempt to make the playoffs for the first time since [[1999 Buffalo Bills season|1999]]. The Bills had the 9th pick in the first round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]] selecting [[C. J. Spiller]], a [[running back]] from [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]. This season marks the first 0\u20138 start since [[1984 Buffalo Bills season|1984]], in which they finished 2-14. They were eliminated from playoff contention in Week 12, extending their playoff drought to 11 seasons. Despite the poor start, Buffalo became largely competitive after the bye in Week 9. Their next four losses were by only three points each, all to teams that made the playoffs that year\u2014Baltimore, Kansas City, Chicago and Pittsburgh (three of these losses went to overtime). The Bills eventually won four of their final eight games, which carried over into a strong start to the [[2011 Buffalo Bills season|2011 season]]. The 2010 season was marked by the emergence of wide receiver [[Stevie Johnson]], who gained 1,073 receiving yards and [[nose tackle]] [[Kyle Williams (defensive tackle)|Kyle Williams]], an [[All-Pro]] in 2010 who gained status as an elite defensive tackle.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/blog/afceast/post/_/id/29870/afc-easts-best-no-11-kyle-williams ESPN: AFC East's Best \u2013 #11]</ref><ref>[http://www.profootballfocus.com/blog/2011/05/22/kyle-williams-beast/ Pro Football Focus \u2013 Kyle Williams: Beast]</ref><ref>[http://views.washingtonpost.com/theleague/smarterstats/2010/12/week-13-nfl-preview.html Washington Post \u2013 Week 13 NFL preview]</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Offseason==\nThe Bills had fired head coach [[Dick Jauron]] after Week 10 of the 2009 season; he had been replaced on an interim basis by defensive coordinator [[Perry Fewell]]. The remainder of the Jauron coaching staff was released at the end of the year, including Fewell. Former [[Dallas Cowboys]] and [[Georgia Tech Yellowjackets football|Georgia Tech]] head coach [[Chan Gailey]] was hired as the Bills' new head coach and [[Buddy Nix]] had taken over as general manager after a two-year vacancy in the position. (Current team CEO Russ Brandon had handled GM responsibilities.) Gailey installed the [[3-4 defense]] (although the team would play in a [[4-3 defense|4\u20133]] on certain downs) <ref>[http://www.footballoutsiders.com/four-downs/2011/four-downs-afc-east Football Outsiders: Four Downs \u2013 AFC East]</ref> and the \"[[Pistol offense|Pistol]]\" offensive formation. [[George Edwards (American football)|George Edwards]] was named defensive coordinator, and though Gailey stated he would call the offensive plays, [[Curtis Modkins]] was named the nominal offensive coordinator. On February 18, 2010, starting right tackle [[Brad Butler]] announced his retirement from professional football. Butler suffered a season ending (ultimately a career ending) knee injury vs. the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in week 2 of the 2009 season. The Bills held an open competition for the starting [[quarterback]] position between [[Trent Edwards]], [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] and [[Brian Brohm]] during training camp. Edwards was named starter prior to the first preseason game, but was released from the team after two poor performances. Fitzpatrick took over in Week 3 and, in 13 games, became the first Bills quarterback to throw for 3,000 passing yards in a season since [[J. P. Losman]] in [[2006 Buffalo Bills season|2006]].<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/buf/2010.htm Pro Football Reference \u2013 2010 Buffalo Bills]</ref><ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/buf/2006.htm}]</ref>\n\n===2010 Draft===\n{{main|2010 NFL Draft}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|+ 2010 Buffalo Bills Draft Selections\n! Round !! Overall !! Player !! Position !! College\n|-\n|1 || 9 || [[C. J. Spiller]] || [[Running back|RB]] || [[Clemson University|Clemson]]\n|-\n|2 || 41 || [[Torell Troup]] || [[Defensive Tackle|DT]] || [[University of Central Florida|UCF]]\n|-\n|3 || 72 || [[Alex Carrington]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[Arkansas State University|Arkansas State]]\n|-\n|4 || 107 || [[Marcus Easley]] || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[University of Connecticut|Connecticut]]\n|-\n|5 || 140 || [[Ed Wang]] || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]] || [[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University|Virginia Tech]]\n|-\n|6 || 178 || [[Arthur Moats]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[James Madison Dukes football|James Madison]]\n|-\n|6 || 192 || [[Danny Batten (American football)|Danny Batten]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[South Dakota State University|South Dakota State]]\n|-\n|7 || 209 || [[Levi Brown (quarterback)|Levi Brown]] || [[Quarterback|QB]]  || [[Troy University|Troy]]\n|-\n|7 || 216 || [[Kyle Calloway]] || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]]  || [[Iowa University|Iowa]]\n|}\n\n==In-season transactions==\n\nCome week three Fitzpatrick was named starter against the Patriots as Edwards was benched. In the game Fitzpatrick had surpassed Edwards' statistics for the first two games. This resulted in Edwards' release from the roster the following day on Monday, a day after the game, when his success in the preseason did not continue into the first two games of the regular season.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Wawrow |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/sports/bills-nfl/nfl-wire/article202688.ece |title=Bills release QB Trent Edwards \u2013 NFL Wire |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=September 27, 2010 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> He was picked up by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] off waivers the next day on Tuesday.<ref name=\"buffalonews1\">{{cite web|author=Mark Long |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/sports/bills-nfl/nfl-wire/article204012.ece |title=Jaguars claim QB Edwards off waivers from Bills \u2013 NFL Wire |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=September 28, 2010 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSimilarly, [[Marshawn Lynch]] was one of the starting running backs at the beginning of the regular season. He was only to be traded to the [[Seattle Seahawks]] after four games into the regular season with the rise of running backs [[Fred Jackson (American football)|Fred Jackson]] and first-round draft pick C. J. Spiller created a logjam. The draft picks were at first undisclosed. It was later announced that the Bills would receive a fourth-round draft pick in the 2011 draft and a conditional pick in the 2012 draft.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tim Booth |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/sports/bills-nfl/nfl-wire/article211137.ece |title=Bills send RB Lynch to Seahawks \u2013 NFL Wire |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\n==Staff==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#0f4589; color:white; text-align: center; border:2px solid #c60c30;\"|'''Buffalo Bills 2010 staff'''\n|-\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"| '''Front Office'''\n* President \u2013 [[Ralph Wilson]]\n* CEO \u2013 [[Russ Brandon]]\n* Executive Vice President/General Manager \u2013 [[Buddy Nix]]\n* Senior Vice President of Football 